The two men appeared out of nowhere, a few yards apart in the narrow, moonlit lane. For a second they stood quite still, wands directed at each other\rquote s chests; then, recognizing each other, they stowed their wands beneath their cloaks and started walking briskly in the same direction.\par
\ldblquote News?\rdblquote  asked the taller of the two.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The best,\rdblquote  replied Severus Snape.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The lane was bordered on the left by wild, low-growing brambles, on the right by a high, neatly manicured hedge. The men\rquote s long cloaks flapped around their ankles as they marched.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thought I might be late,\rdblquote  said Yaxley, his blunt features slid\-ing in and out of sight as the branches of overhanging trees broke the moonlight. \ldblquote It was a little trickier than I expected. But I hope he will be satisfied. You sound confident that your reception will be good?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape nodded, but did not elaborate. They turned right, into a\lang3081  \lang1033 wide driveway that led off the lane. The high hedge curved with them, running off into the distance beyond the pair of impressive wrought-iron gates barring the men\rquote s way. Neither of them broke step: In silence both raised their left arms in a kind of salute and passed straight through, as though the dark metal were smoke.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The yew hedges muffled the sound of the men\rquote s footsteps. There was a rustle somewhere to their right: Yaxley drew his wand again, pointing it over his companion\rquote s head, but the source of the noise proved to be nothing more than a pure-white peacock, strutting majestically along the top of the hedge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He always did himself well, Lucius. \i Peacocks\lang3081\i0  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote  Yaxley thrust his wand back under his cloak with a snort.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A handsome manor house grew out of the darkness at the end of the straight drive, lights glinting in the diamond-paned downstairs windows. Somewhere in the dark garden beyond the hedge a foun\-tain was playing. Gravel crackled beneath their feet as Snape and Yaxley sped toward the front door, which swung inward at their approach, though nobody had visibly opened it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The hallway was large, dimly lit, and sumptuously decorated, with a magnificent carpet covering most of the stone floor. The eyes of the pale-faced portraits on the walls followed Snape and Yaxley as they strode past. The two men halted at a heavy wooden door leading into the next room, hesitated for the space of a heartbeat, then Snape turned the bronze handle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The drawing room was full of silent people, sitting at a long and ornate table. The room\rquote s usual furniture had been pushed carelessly up against the walls. Illumination came from a roaring fire beneath a handsome marble mantelpiece surmounted by a gilded mirror. Snape and Yaxley lingered for a moment on the threshold. As their\lang3081  \lang1033 eyes grew accustomed to the lack of light, they were drawn upward to the strangest feature of the scene: an apparently unconscious hu\-man figure hanging upside down over the table, revolving slowly as if suspended by an invisible rope, and reflected in the mirror and in the bare, polished surface of the table below. None of the people seated underneath this singular sight was looking at it except for a pale young man sitting almost directly below it. He seemed unable to prevent himself from glancing upward every minute or so.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yaxley. Snape,\rdblquote  said a high, clear voice from the head of the table. \ldblquote You are very nearly late.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The speaker was seated directly in front of the fireplace, so that it was difficult, at first, for the new arrivals to make out more than his silhouette. As they drew nearer, however, his face shone through the gloom, hairless, snakelike, with slits for nostrils and gleaming red eyes whose pupils were vertical. He was so pale that he seemed to emit a pearly glow.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Severus, here,\rdblquote  said Voldemort, indicating the seat on his im\-mediate right. \ldblquote Yaxley \emdash  beside Dolohov.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The two men took their allotted places. Most of the eyes around the table followed Snape, and it was to him that Voldemort spoke first.\par
\ldblquote So?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My Lord, the Order of the Phoenix intends to move Harry Pot\-ter from his current place of safety on Saturday next, at nightfall.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The interest around the table sharpened palpably: Some stiffened, others fidgeted, all gazing at Snape and Voldemort.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Saturday \'85 at nightfall,\rdblquote  repeated Voldemort. His red eyes fas\-tened upon Snape\rquote s black ones with such intensity that some of the watchers looked away, apparently fearful that they themselves would\lang3081  \lang1033 be scorched by the ferocity of the gaze. Snape, however, looked calmly back into Voldemort\rquote s face and, after a moment or two, Vol\-demort\rquote s lipless mouth curved into something like a smile.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good. Very good. And this information comes \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  from the source we discussed,\rdblquote  said Snape.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My Lord.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Yaxley had leaned forward to look down the long table at Volde\-mort and Snape. All faces turned to him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My Lord, I have heard differently.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Yaxley waited, but Voldemort did not speak, so he went on, \ldblquote Dawlish, the Auror, let slip that Potter will not be moved until the thirtieth, the night before the boy turns seventeen.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape was smiling.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My source told me that there are plans to lay a false trail; this must be it. No doubt a Confundus Charm has been placed upon Dawlish. It would not be the first time; he is known to be susceptible.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I assure you, my Lord, Dawlish seemed quite certain,\rdblquote  said Yaxley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If he has been Confunded, naturally he is certain,\rdblquote  said Snape. \ldblquote I assure \i you,\i0  Yaxley, the Auror Office will play no further part in the protection of Harry Potter. The Order believes that we have infiltrated the Ministry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Order\rquote s got one thing right, then, eh?\rdblquote  said a squat man sit\-ting a short distance from Yaxley; he gave a wheezy giggle that was echoed here and there along the table.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Voldemort did not laugh. His gaze had wandered upward to the body revolving slowly overhead, and he seemed to be lost in thought.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My Lord,\rdblquote  Yaxley went on, \ldblquote Dawlish believes an entire party of Aurors will be used to transfer the boy \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Voldemort held up a large white hand, and Yaxley subsided at once, watching resentfully as Voldemort turned back to Snape.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where are they going to hide the boy next?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote At the home of one of the Order,\rdblquote  said Snape. \ldblquote The place, accord\-ing to the source, has been given every protection that the Order and Ministry together could provide. I think that there is little chance of taking him once he is there, my Lord, unless, of course, the Ministry has fallen before next Saturday, which might give us the opportunity to discover and undo enough of the enchantments to break through the rest.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, Yaxley?\rdblquote  Voldemort called down the table, the firelight glinting strangely in his red eyes. \ldblquote\i Will\lang3081\i0  \lang1033 the Ministry have fallen by next Saturday?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Once again, all heads turned. Yaxley squared his shoulders.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My Lord, I have good news on that score. I have \emdash  with dif\-ficulty, and after great effort \emdash  suceeded in placing an Imperius Curse upon Pius Thicknesse.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Many of those sitting around Yaxley looked impressed; his neigh\-bor, Dolohov, a man with a long, twisted face, clapped him on the back.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It is a start,\rdblquote  said Voldemort. \ldblquote But Thicknesse is only one man. Scrimgeour must be surrounded by our people before I act. One failed attempt on the Minister\rquote s life will set me back a long way.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes \emdash  my Lord, that is true \emdash  but you know, as Head of the Department of Magical Law Enforcement, Thicknesse has regular contact not only with the Minister himself, but also with the Heads\lang3081  \lang1033 of all the other Ministry departments. It will, I think, be easy now that we have such a high-ranking official under our control, to subjugate the others, and then they can all work together to bring Scrimgeour down.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote As long as our friend Thicknesse is not discovered before he has converted the rest,\rdblquote  said Voldemort. \ldblquote At any rate, it remains unlikely that the Ministry will be mine before next Saturday. If we cannot touch the boy at his destination, then it must be done while he travels.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We are at an advantage there, my Lord,\rdblquote  said Yaxley, who seemed determined to receive some portion of approval. \ldblquote We now have several people planted within the Department of Magical Trans\-port. If Potter Apparates or uses the Floo Network, we shall know immediately.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He will not do either,\rdblquote  said Snape. \ldblquote The Order is eschewing any form of transport that is controlled or regulated by the Ministry; they mistrust everything to do with the place.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All the better,\rdblquote  said Voldemort. \ldblquote He will have to move in the open. Easier to take, by far.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Again, Voldemort looked up at the slowly revolving body as he went on, \ldblquote I shall attend to the boy in person. There have been too many mistakes where Harry Potter is concerned. Some of them have been my own. That Potter lives is due more to my errors than to his triumphs.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The company around the table watched Voldemort apprehen\-sively, each of them, by his or her expression, afraid that they might be blamed for Harry Potter\rquote s continued existence. Voldemort, how\-ever, seemed to be speaking more to himself than to any of them, still addressing the unconscious body above him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I have been careless, and so have been thwarted by luck and chance, those wreckers of all but the best-laid plans. But I know bet\-ter now. I understand those things that I did not understand before. I must be the one to kill Harry Potter, and I shall be.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 At these words, seemingly in response to them, a sudden wail sounded, a terrible, drawn-out cry of misery and pain. Many of those at the table looked downward, startled, for the sound had seemed to issue from below their feet.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wormtail,\rdblquote  said Voldemort, with no change in his quiet, thoughtful tone, and without removing his eyes from the revolving body above, \ldblquote have I not spoken to you about keeping our prisoner quiet?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, m-my Lord,\rdblquote  gasped a small man halfway down the table, who had been sitting so low in his chair that it had appeared, at first glance, to be unoccupied. Now he scrambled from his seat and scurried from the room, leaving nothing behind him but a curious gleam of silver.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote As I was saying,\rdblquote  continued Voldemort, looking again at the tense faces of his followers, \ldblquote I understand better now. I shall need, for instance, to borrow a wand from one of you before I go to kill Potter.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The faces around him displayed nothing but shock; he might have announced that he wanted to borrow one of their arms.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No volunteers?\rdblquote  said Voldemort. \ldblquote Let\rquote s see \'85 Lucius, I see no reason for you to have a wand anymore.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lucius Malfoy looked up. His skin appeared yellowish and waxy in the firelight, and his eyes were sunken and shadowed. When he spoke, his voice was hoarse.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My Lord?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Your wand, Lucius. I require your wand.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\lang3081  \'85\rdblquote\par
\lang1033 Malfoy glanced sideways at his wife. She was staring straight ahead, quite as pale as he was, her long blonde hair hanging down her back, but beneath the table her slim fingers closed briefly on his wrist. At her touch, Malfoy put his hand into his robes, withdrew a wand, and passed it along to Voldemort, who held it up in front of his red eyes, examining it closely.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What is it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Elm, my Lord,\rdblquote  whispered Malfoy.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And the core?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dragon \emdash  dragon heartstring.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good,\rdblquote  said Voldemort. He drew out his own wand and com\-pared the lengths. Lucius Malfoy made an involuntary movement; for a fraction of a second, it seemed he expected to receive Volde\-mort\rquote s wand in exchange for his own. The gesture was not missed by Voldemort, whose eyes widened maliciously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Give you my wand, Lucius? \i My\i0  wand?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Some of the throng sniggered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I have given you your liberty, Lucius, is that not enough for you? But I have noticed that you and your family seem less than happy of late. \'85 What is it about my presence in your home that displeases you, Lucius?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nothing \emdash  nothing, my Lord!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Such \i lies,\i0  Lucius \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The soft voice seemed to hiss on even after the cruel mouth had stopped moving. One or two of the wizards barely repressed a shud\-der as the hissing grew louder; something heavy could be heard sliding across the floor beneath the table.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The huge snake emerged to climb slowly up Voldemort\rquote s chair. It rose, seemingly endlessly, and came to rest across Voldemort\rquote s shoulders: its neck the thickness of a man\rquote s thigh; its eyes, with their vertical slits for pupils, unblinking. Voldemort stroked the creature absently with long thin fingers, still looking at Lucius Malfoy.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why do the Malfoys look so unhappy with their lot? Is my re\-turn, my rise to power, not the very thing they professed to desire for so many years?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course, my Lord,\rdblquote  said Lucius Malfoy. His hand shook as he wiped sweat from his upper lip. \ldblquote We did desire it \emdash  we do.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 To Malfoy\rquote s left, his wife made an odd, stiff nod, her eyes averted from Voldemort and the snake. To his right, his son, Draco, who had been gazing up at the inert body overhead, glanced quickly at Voldemort and away again, terrified to make eye contact.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My Lord,\rdblquote  said a dark woman halfway down the table, her voice constricted with emotion, \ldblquote it is an honor to have you here, in our family\rquote s house. There can be no higher pleasure.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She sat beside her sister, as unlike her in looks, with her dark hair and heavily lidded eyes, as she was in bearing and demeanor; where Narcissa sat rigid and impassive, Bellatrix leaned toward Voldemort, for mere words could not demonstrate her longing for closeness.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No higher pleasure,\rdblquote  repeated Voldemort, his head tilted a little to one side as he considered Bellatrix. \ldblquote That means a great deal, Bellatrix, from you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Her face flooded with color; her eyes welled with tears of delight.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My Lord knows I speak nothing but the truth!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No higher pleasure \'85 even compared with the happy event that, I hear, has taken place in your family this week?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She stared at him, her lips parted, evidently confused.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t know what you mean, my Lord.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m talking about your niece, Bellatrix. And yours, Lucius and Narcissa. She has just married the werewolf, Remus Lupin. You must be so proud.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was an eruption of jeering laughter from around the table. Many leaned forward to exchange gleeful looks; a few thumped the table with their fists. The great snake, disliking the disturbance, opened its mouth wide and hissed angrily, but the Death Eaters did not hear it, so jubilant were they at Bellatrix and the Malfoys\rquote  hu\-miliation. Bellatrix\rquote s face, so recently flushed with happiness, had turned an ugly, blotchy red.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She is no niece of ours, my Lord,\rdblquote  she cried over the outpouring of mirth. \ldblquote We \emdash  Narcissa and I \emdash  have never set eyes on our sister since she married the Mudblood. This brat has nothing to do with either of us, nor any beast she marries.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What say you, Draco?\rdblquote  asked Voldemort, and though his voice was quiet, it carried clearly through the catcalls and jeers. \ldblquote Will you babysit the cubs?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The hilarity mounted; Draco Malfoy looked in terror at his father, who was staring down into his own lap, then caught his mother\rquote s eye. She shook her head almost imperceptibly, then resumed her own deadpan stare at the opposite wall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Enough,\rdblquote  said Voldemort, stroking the angry snake. \ldblquote Enough.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And the laughter died at once.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Many of our oldest family trees become a little diseased over time,\rdblquote  he said as Bellatrix gazed at him, breathless and imploring.\lang3081  \lang1033\ldblquote You must prune yours, must you not, to keep it healthy? Cut away those parts that threaten the health of the rest.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, my Lord,\rdblquote  whispered Bellatrix, and her eyes swam with tears of gratitude again. \ldblquote At the first chance!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You shall have it,\rdblquote  said Voldemort. \ldblquote And in your family, so in the world \'85 we shall cut away the canker that infects us until only those of the true blood remain. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Voldemort raised Lucius Malfoy\rquote s wand, pointed it directly at the slowly revolving figure suspended over the table, and gave it a tiny flick. The figure came to life with a groan and began to struggle against invisible bonds.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Do you recognize our guest, Severus?\rdblquote  asked Voldemort.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape raised his eyes to the upside-down face. All of the Death Eaters were looking up at the captive now, as though they had been given permission to show curiosity. As she revolved to face the fire\-light, the woman said in a cracked and terrified voice, \ldblquote Severus! Help me!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah, yes,\rdblquote  said Snape as the prisoner turned slowly away again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And you, Draco?\rdblquote  asked Voldemort, stroking the snake\rquote s snout with his wand-free hand. Draco shook his head jerkily. Now that the woman had woken, he seemed unable to look at her anymore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But you would not have taken her classes,\rdblquote  said Voldemort. \ldblquote For those of you who do not know, we are joined here tonight by Charity Burbage who, until recently, taught at Hogwarts School of Witch\-craft and Wizardry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There were small noises of comprehension around the table. A broad, hunched woman with pointed teeth cackled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes \'85 Professor Burbage taught the children of witches and\lang3081  \lang1033 wizards all about Muggles \'85 how they are not so different from us \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 One of the Death Eaters spat on the floor. Charity Burbage re\-volved to face Snape again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Severus \'85 please \'85 please \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Silence,\rdblquote  said Voldemort, with another twitch of Malfoy\rquote s wand, and Charity fell silent as if gagged. \ldblquote Not content with corrupting and polluting the minds of Wizarding children, last week Professor Burbage wrote an impassioned defense of Mudbloods in the \i Daily Prophet.\i0  Wizards, she says, must accept these thieves of their knowl\-edge and magic. The dwindling of the purebloods is, says Professor Burbage, a most desirable circumstance. \'85 She would have us all mate with Muggles \'85 or, no doubt, werewolves. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Nobody laughed this time: There was no mistaking the anger and contempt in Voldemort\rquote s voice. For the third time, Charity Burbage revolved to face Snape. Tears were pouring from her eyes into her hair. Snape looked back at her, quite impassive, as she turned slowly away from him again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Avada Kedavra.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The flash of green light illuminated every corner of the room. Charity fell, with a resounding crash, onto the table below, which trembled and creaked. Several of the Death Eaters leapt back in their chairs. Draco fell out of his onto the floor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dinner, Nagini,\rdblquote  said Voldemort softly, and the great snake swayed and slithered from his shoulders onto the polished wood.\lang3081\par
