\lang1033\ldblquote Darling Dodgy! I remember interviewing him a few years back about merpeople rights, bless him. Completely gaga, seemed to think we were sitting at the bottom of Lake Windermere, kept telling me to watch out for trout.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And yet Elphias Doge\rquote s accusations of inaccuracy have been echoed in many places. Does Skeeter re\-ally feel that four short weeks have been enough to gain a full picture of Dumbledore\rquote s long and ex\-traordinary life?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, my dear,\rdblquote  beams Skeeter, rapping me affec\-tionately across the knuckles, \ldblquote you know as well as I do how much information can be generated by a fat bag of Galleons, a refusal to hear the word \lquote no,\rquote  and a nice sharp Quick-Quotes Quill! People were queuing to dish the dirt on Dumbledore anyway. Not everyone thought he was so wonderful, you know \emdash  he trod on an awful lot of important toes. But old Dodgy Doge can get off his high hippogriff, because I\rquote ve had access to a source most journal\-ists would swap their wands for, one who has never spoken in public before and who was close to Dum\-bledore during the most turbulent and disturbing phase of his youth.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The advance publicity for Skeeter\rquote s biography has certainly suggested that there will be shocks in store for those who believe Dumbledore to have led a blameless life. What were the biggest surprises she uncovered, I ask?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now, come off it, Betty, I\rquote m not giving away all the highlights before anybody\rquote s bought the book!\rdblquote  laughs Skeeter. \ldblquote But I can promise that anybody who still thinks Dumbledore was white as his beard is in for a rude awakening! Let\rquote s just say that nobody hearing him rage against You-Know-Who would have dreamed that he dabbled in the Dark Arts himself in his youth! And for a wizard who spent his later years pleading for tolerance, he wasn\rquote t ex\-actly broad-minded when he was younger! Yes, Al\-bus Dumbledore had an extremely murky past, not to mention that very fishy family, which he worked so hard to keep hushed up.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 I ask whether Skeeter is referring to Dumbledore\rquote s brother, Aberforth, whose conviction by the Wizen\-gamot for misuse of magic caused a minor scandal fifteen years ago.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, Aberforth is just the tip of the dung heap,\rdblquote  laughs Skeeter. \ldblquote No, no, I\rquote m talking about much worse than a brother with a fondness for fiddling about with goats, worse even than the Muggle-maiming father \emdash  Dumbledore couldn\rquote t keep either of them quiet anyway, they were both charged by the Wizengamot. No, it\rquote s the mother and the sister\lang3081  \lang1033 that intrigued me, and a little digging uncovered a positive nest of nastiness \emdash  but, as I say, you\rquote ll have to wait for chapters nine to twelve for full details. All I can say now is, it\rquote s no wonder Dumbledore never talked about how his nose got broken.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Family skeletons notwithstanding, does Skeeter deny the brilliance that led to Dumbledore\rquote s many magical discoveries?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He had brains,\rdblquote  she concedes, \ldblquote although many now question whether he could really take full credit for all of his supposed achievements. As I reveal in chapter sixteen, Ivor Dillonsby claims he had al\-ready discovered eight uses of dragon\rquote s blood when Dumbledore \lquote borrowed\rquote  his papers.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But the importance of some of Dumbledore\rquote s achievements cannot, I venture, be denied. What of his famous defeat of Grindelwald?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, now, I\rquote m glad you mentioned Grindelwald,\rdblquote  says Skeeter with a tantalizing smile. \ldblquote I\rquote m afraid those who go dewy-eyed over Dumbledore\rquote s spectacular victory must brace themselves for a bombshell \emdash  or perhaps a Dungbomb. Very dirty business indeed. All I\rquote ll say is, don\rquote t be so sure that there really was the spectacular duel of legend. After they\rquote ve read my book, people may be forced to conclude that Grin\-delwald simply conjured a white handkerchief from the end of his wand and came quietly!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Skeeter refuses to give any more away on this intriguing subject, so we turn instead to the rela\-tionship that will undoubtedly fascinate her readers more than any other.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yes,\rdblquote  says Skeeter, nodding briskly, \ldblquote I devote an entire chapter to the whole Potter-Dumbledore relationship. It\rquote s been called unhealthy, even sinis\-ter. Again, your readers will have to buy my book for the whole story, but there is no question that Dumbledore took an unnatural interest in Potter from the word go. Whether that was really in the boy\rquote s best interests \emdash  well, we\rquote ll see. It\rquote s certainly an open secret that Potter has had a most troubled adolescence.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 I ask whether Skeeter is still in touch with Harry Potter, whom she so famously interviewed last year: a breakthrough piece in which Potter spoke exclu\-sively of his conviction that You-Know-Who had returned.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, yes, we\rquote ve developed a close bond,\rdblquote  says Skeeter. \ldblquote Poor Potter has few real friends, and we met at one of the most testing moments of his life \emdash  the Triwizard Tournament. I am probably one of the only people alive who can say that they know the real Harry Potter.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Which leads us neatly to the many rumors still circulating about Dumbledore\rquote s final hours. Does Skeeter believe that Potter was there when Dumble\-dore died?\lang3081\par
