\lang1033\ldblquote You claim,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon, starting to pace yet again, \ldblquote that this Lord Thing \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  Voldemort,\rdblquote  said Harry impatiently, \ldblquote and we\rquote ve been through this about a hundred times already. This isn\rquote t a claim, it\rquote s fact, Dum\-bledore told you last year, and Kingsley and Mr. Weasley \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Vernon Dursley hunched his shoulders angrily, and Harry guessed that his uncle was attempting to ward off recollections of the unan\-nounced visit, a few days into Harry\rquote s summer holidays, of two fully grown wizards. The arrival on the doorstep of Kingsley Shacklebolt and Arthur Weasley had come as a most unpleasant shock to the\lang3081  \lang1033 Dursleys. Harry had to admit, however, that as Mr. Weasley had once demolished half of the living room, his reappearance could not have been expected to delight Uncle Vernon.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  Kingsley and Mr. Weasley explained it all as well,\rdblquote  Harry pressed on remorselessly. \ldblquote Once I\rquote m seventeen, the protective charm that keeps me safe will break, and that exposes you as well as me. The Order is sure Voldemort will target you, whether to torture you to try and find out where I am, or because he thinks by holding you hostage I\rquote d come and try to rescue you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Uncle Vernon\rquote s and Harry\rquote s eyes met. Harry was sure that in that instant they were both wondering the same thing. Then Uncle Ver\-non walked on and Harry resumed, \ldblquote You\rquote ve got to go into hiding and the Order wants to help. You\rquote re being offered serious protection, the best there is.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Uncle Vernon said nothing, but continued to pace up and down. Outside the sun hung low over the privet hedges. The next-door neighbor\rquote s lawn mower stalled again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I thought there was a Ministry of Magic?\rdblquote  asked Vernon Durs\-ley abruptly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There is,\rdblquote  said Harry, surprised.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, then, why can\rquote t they protect us? It seems to me that, as innocent victims, guilty of nothing more than harboring a marked man, we ought to qualify for government protection!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry laughed; he could not help himself. It was so very typical of his uncle to put his hopes in the establishment, even within this world that he despised and mistrusted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You heard what Mr. Weasley and Kingsley said,\rdblquote  Harry replied. \ldblquote We think the Ministry has been infiltrated.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Uncle Vernon strode to the fireplace and back, breathing so heav\-ily that his great black mustache rippled, his face still purple with concentration.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All right,\rdblquote  he said, stopping in front of Harry yet again. \ldblquote All right, let\rquote s say, for the sake of argument, we accept this protection. I still don\rquote t see why we can\rquote t have that Kingsley bloke.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry managed not to roll his eyes, but with difficulty. This ques\-tion had also been addressed half a dozen times.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote As I\rquote ve told you,\rdblquote  he said through gritted teeth, \ldblquote Kingsley is protecting the Mug \emdash  I mean, your Prime Minister.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Exactly \emdash  he\rquote s the best!\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon, pointing at the blank television screen. The Dursleys had spotted Kingsley on the news, walking along discreetly behind the Muggle Prime Minister as he visited a hospital. This, and the fact that Kingsley had mastered the knack of dressing like a Muggle, not to mention a certain reas\-suring something in his slow, deep voice, had caused the Dursleys to take to Kingsley in a way that they had certainly not done with any other wizard, although it was true that they had never seen him with his earring in.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, he\rquote s taken,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote But Hestia Jones and Dedalus Diggle are more than up to the job \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If we\rquote d even seen CVs\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote  began Uncle Vernon, but Harry lost patience. Getting to his feet, he advanced on his uncle, now point\-ing at the TV set himself.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote These accidents aren\rquote t accidents \emdash  the crashes and explosions and derailments and whatever else has happened since we last watched the news. People are disappearing and dying and he\rquote s be\-hind it \emdash  Voldemort. I\rquote ve told you this over and over again, he kills\lang3081  \lang1033 Muggles for fun. Even the fogs \emdash  they\rquote re caused by dementors, and if you can\rquote t remember what they are, ask your son!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dudley\rquote s hands jerked upward to cover his mouth. With his par\-ents\rquote  and Harry\rquote s eyes upon him, he slowly lowered them again and asked, \ldblquote There are \'85 more of them?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote More?\rdblquote  laughed Harry. \ldblquote More than the two that attacked us, you mean? Of course there are, there are hundreds, maybe thousands by this time, seeing as they feed off fear and despair \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All right, all right,\rdblquote  blustered Vernon Dursley. \ldblquote You\rquote ve made your point \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I hope so,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote because once I\rquote m seventeen, all of them \emdash  Death Eaters, dementors, maybe even Inferi \emdash  which means dead bodies enchanted by a Dark wizard \emdash  will be able to find you and will certainly attack you. And if you remember the last time you tried to outrun wizards, I think you\rquote ll agree you need help.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a brief silence in which the distant echo of Hagrid smashing down a wooden front door seemed to reverberate through the intervening years. Aunt Petunia was looking at Uncle Vernon; Dudley was staring at Harry. Finally Uncle Vernon blurted out, \ldblquote But what about my work? What about Dudley\rquote s school? I don\rquote t suppose those things matter to a bunch of layabout wizards \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t you understand?\rdblquote  shouted Harry. \ldblquote\i They will torture and kill you like they did my parents\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dad,\rdblquote  said Dudley in a loud voice, \ldblquote Dad \emdash  I\rquote m going with these Order people.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dudley,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote for the first time in your life, you\rquote re talk\-ing sense.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He knew that the battle was won. If Dudley was frightened\lang3081  \lang1033 enough to accept the Order\rquote s help, his parents would accompany him: There could be no question of being separated from their Did\-dykins. Harry glanced at the carriage clock on the mantelpiece.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They\rquote ll be here in about five minutes,\rdblquote  he said, and when none of the Dursleys replied, he left the room. The prospect of part\-ing \emdash  probably forever \emdash  from his aunt, uncle, and cousin was one that he was able to contemplate quite cheerfully, but there was nevertheless a certain awkwardness in the air. What did you say to one another at the end of sixteen years\rquote  solid dislike?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Back in his bedroom, Harry fiddled aimlessly with his rucksack, then poked a couple of owl nuts through the bars of Hedwig\rquote s cage. They fell with dull thuds to the bottom, where she ignored them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote re leaving soon, really soon,\rdblquote  Harry told her. \ldblquote And then you\rquote ll be able to fly again.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The doorbell rang. Harry hesitated, then headed back out of his room and downstairs. It was too much to expect Hestia and Dedalus to cope with the Dursleys on their own.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry Potter!\rdblquote  squeaked an excited voice, the moment Harry had opened the door; a small man in a mauve top hat was sweeping him a deep bow. \ldblquote An honor, as ever!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thanks, Dedalus,\rdblquote  said Harry, bestowing a small and em\-barrassed smile upon the dark-haired Hestia. \ldblquote It\rquote s really good of you to do this. \'85 They\rquote re through here, my aunt and uncle and cousin. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good day to you, Harry Potter\rquote s relatives!\rdblquote  said Dedalus hap\-pily, striding into the living room. The Dursleys did not look at all happy to be addressed thus; Harry half expected another change of mind. Dudley shrank nearer to his mother at the sight of the witch and wizard.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I see you are packed and ready. Excellent! The plan, as Harry has told you, is a simple one,\rdblquote  said Dedalus, pulling an immense pocket watch out of his waistcoat and examining it. \ldblquote We shall be leaving before Harry does. Due to the danger of using magic in your house \emdash  Harry being still underage, it could provide the Ministry with an excuse to arrest him \emdash  we shall be driving, say, ten miles or so, before Disapparating to the safe location we have picked out for you. You know how to drive, I take it?\rdblquote  he asked Uncle Vernon politely.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Know how to \emdash  ? Of course I ruddy well know how to drive!\rdblquote  spluttered Uncle Vernon.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very clever of you, sir, very clever, I personally would be ut\-terly bamboozled by all those buttons and knobs,\rdblquote  said Dedalus. He was clearly under the impression that he was flattering Vernon Dursley, who was visibly losing confidence in the plan with every word Dedalus spoke.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Can\rquote t even drive,\rdblquote  he muttered under his breath, his mustache rippling indignantly, but fortunately neither Dedalus nor Hestia seemed to hear him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You, Harry,\rdblquote  Dedalus continued, \ldblquote will wait here for your guard. There has been a little change in the arrangements \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What d\rquote you mean?\rdblquote  said Harry at once. \ldblquote I thought Mad-Eye was going to come and take me by Side-Along-Apparition?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Can\rquote t do it,\rdblquote  said Hestia tersely. \ldblquote Mad-Eye will explain.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Dursleys, who had listened to all of this with looks of utter incomprehension on their faces, jumped as a loud voice screeched, \ldblquote\i Hurry up\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081  \lang1033 Harry looked all around the room before realizing that the voice had issued from Dedalus\rquote s pocket watch.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Quite right, we\rquote re operating to a very tight schedule,\rdblquote  said\lang3081  \lang1033 Dedalus, nodding at his watch and tucking it back into his waist\-coat. \ldblquote We are attempting to time your departure from the house with your family\rquote s Disapparition, Harry; thus, the charm breaks at the moment you all head for safety.\rdblquote  He turned to the Dursleys. \ldblquote Well, are we all packed and ready to go?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 None of them answered him. Uncle Vernon was still staring, ap\-palled, at the bulge in Dedalus\rquote s waistcoat pocket.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Perhaps we should wait outside in the hall, Dedalus,\rdblquote  murmured Hestia. She clearly felt that it would be tactless for them to remain in the room while Harry and the Dursleys exchanged loving, pos\-sibly tearful farewells.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There\rquote s no need,\rdblquote  Harry muttered, but Uncle Vernon made any further explanation unnecessary by saying loudly,\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, this is good-bye, then, boy.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He swung his right arm upward to shake Harry\rquote s hand, but at the last moment seemed unable to face it, and merely closed his fist and began swinging it backward and forward like a metronome.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ready, Diddy?\rdblquote  asked Aunt Petunia, fussily checking the clasp of her handbag so as to avoid looking at Harry altogether.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dudley did not answer, but stood there with his mouth slightly ajar, reminding Harry a little of the giant, Grawp.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Come along, then,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He had already reached the living room door when Dudley mum\-bled, \ldblquote I don\rquote t understand.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What don\rquote t you understand, popkin?\rdblquote  asked Aunt Petunia, look\-ing up at her son.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dudley raised a large, hamlike hand to point at Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why isn\rquote t he coming with us?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Uncle Vernon and Aunt Petunia froze where they stood, star\-ing at Dudley as though he had just expressed a desire to become a ballerina.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon loudly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why isn\rquote t he coming too?\rdblquote  asked Dudley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, he \emdash  he doesn\rquote t want to,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon, turning to glare at Harry and adding, \ldblquote You don\rquote t want to, do you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not in the slightest,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There you are,\rdblquote  Uncle Vernon told Dudley. \ldblquote Now come on, we\rquote re off.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He marched out of the room. They heard the front door open, but Dudley did not move and after a few faltering steps Aunt Pe\-tunia stopped too.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What now?\rdblquote  barked Uncle Vernon, reappearing in the doorway.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It seemed that Dudley was struggling with concepts too difficult to put into words. After several moments of apparently painful in\-ternal struggle he said, \ldblquote But where\rquote s he going to go?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Aunt Petunia and Uncle Vernon looked at each other. It was clear that Dudley was frightening them. Hestia Jones broke the silence.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But \'85 surely you know where your nephew is going?\rdblquote  she asked, looking bewildered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Certainly we know,\rdblquote  said Vernon Dursley. \ldblquote He\rquote s off with some of your lot, isn\rquote t he? Right, Dudley, let\rquote s get in the car, you heard the man, we\rquote re in a hurry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Again, Vernon Dursley marched as far as the front door, but Dudley did not follow.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Off with some of \i our\i0  lot?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hestia looked outraged. Harry had met this attitude before: Witches and wizards seemed stunned that his closest living relatives took so little interest in the famous Harry Potter.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s fine,\rdblquote  Harry assured her. \ldblquote It doesn\rquote t matter, honestly.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Doesn\rquote t matter?\rdblquote  repeated Hestia, her voice rising ominously. \ldblquote Don\rquote t these people realize what you\rquote ve been through? What danger you are in? The unique position you hold in the hearts of the anti-Voldemort movement?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash  no, they don\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote They think I\rquote m a waste of space, actually, but I\rquote m used to \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t think you\rquote re a waste of space.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 If Harry had not seen Dudley\rquote s lips move, he might not have believed it. As it was, he stared at Dudley for several seconds before accepting that it must have been his cousin who had spoken; for one thing, Dudley had turned red. Harry was embarrassed and astonished himself.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 er \'85 thanks, Dudley.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Again, Dudley appeared to grapple with thoughts too unwieldy for expression before mumbling, \ldblquote You saved my life.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not really,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote It was your soul the dementor would have taken. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He looked curiously at his cousin. They had had virtually no con\-tact during this summer or last, as Harry had come back to Privet Drive so briefly and kept to his room so much. It now dawned on Harry, however, that the cup of cold tea on which he had trodden that morning might not have been a booby trap at all. Although rather touched, he was nevertheless quite relieved that Dudley ap\-peared to have exhausted his ability to express his feelings. After\lang3081  \lang1033 opening his mouth once or twice more, Dudley subsided into scarlet-faced silence.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Aunt Petunia burst into tears. Hestia Jones gave her an approv\-ing look that changed to outrage as Aunt Petunia ran forward and embraced Dudley rather than Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote S-so sweet, Dudders \'85\rdblquote  she sobbed into his massive chest. \ldblquote S-such a lovely b-boy\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 s-saying thank you \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But he hasn\rquote t said thank you at all!\rdblquote  said Hestia indignantly. \ldblquote He only said he didn\rquote t think Harry was a waste of space!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, but coming from Dudley that\rquote s like \lquote I love you,\rquote  \rdblquote  said Harry, torn between annoyance and a desire to laugh as Aunt Pe\-tunia continued to clutch at Dudley as if he had just saved Harry from a burning building.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are we going or not?\rdblquote  roared Uncle Vernon, reappearing yet again at the living room door. \ldblquote I thought we were on a tight schedule!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes \emdash  yes, we are,\rdblquote  said Dedalus Diggle, who had been watch\-ing these exchanges with an air of bemusement and now seemed to pull himself together. \ldblquote We really must be off. Harry \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He tripped forward and wrung Harry\rquote s hand with both of his own.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  good luck. I hope we meet again. The hopes of the Wizard\-ing world rest upon your shoulders.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote right. Thanks.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Farewell, Harry,\rdblquote  said Hestia, also clasping his hand. \ldblquote Our thoughts go with you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I hope everything\rquote s okay,\rdblquote  said Harry with a glance toward Aunt Petunia and Dudley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, I\rquote m sure we shall end up the best of chums,\rdblquote  said Diggle brightly, waving his hat as he left the room. Hestia followed him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dudley gently released himself from his mother\rquote s clutches and walked toward Harry, who had to repress an urge to threaten him with magic. Then Dudley held out his large, pink hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Blimey, Dudley,\rdblquote  said Harry over Aunt Petunia\rquote s renewed sobs, \ldblquote did the dementors blow a different personality into you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dunno,\rdblquote  muttered Dudley. \ldblquote See you, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah \'85\rdblquote  said Harry, taking Dudley\rquote s hand and shaking it. \ldblquote Maybe. Take care, Big D.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dudley nearly smiled, then lumbered from the room. Harry heard his heavy footfalls on the graveled drive, and then a car door slammed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Aunt Petunia, whose face had been buried in her handkerchief, looked around at the sound. She did not seem to have expected to find herself alone with Harry. Hastily stowing her wet handkerchief into her pocket, she said, \ldblquote Well \emdash  good-bye,\rdblquote  and marched toward the door without looking at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good-bye,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She stopped and looked back. For a moment Harry had the strangest feeling that she wanted to say something to him: She gave him an odd, tremulous look and seemed to teeter on the edge of speech, but then, with a little jerk of her head, she bustled out of the room after her husband and son.\lang3081\par
