\ldblquote Hagrid?\rdblquote\par
Harry struggled to raise himself out of the debris of metal and leather that surrounded him; his hands sank into inches of muddy water as he tried to stand. He could not understand where Voldemort had gone and expected him to swoop out of the darkness at any moment. Something hot and wet was trickling down his chin and from his forehead. He crawled out of the pond and stumbled toward the great dark mass on the ground that was Hagrid.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hagrid? Hagrid, talk to me \emdash\rdblquote\par
But the dark mass did not stir.\par
\ldblquote Who\rquote s there? Is it Potter? Are you Harry Potter?\rdblquote\par
Harry did not recognize the man\rquote s voice. Then a woman shouted, \ldblquote They\rquote ve crashed, Ted! Crashed in the garden!\rdblquote\par
Harry\rquote s head was swimming.\par
\ldblquote Hagrid,\rdblquote  he repeated stupidly, and his knees buckled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The next thing he knew, he was lying on his back on what felt like cushions, with a burning sensation in his ribs and right arm. His missing tooth had been regrown. The scar on his forehead was still throbbing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hagrid?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He opened his eyes and saw that he was lying on a sofa in an un\-familiar, lamplit sitting room. His rucksack lay on the floor a short distance away, wet and muddy. A fair-haired, big-bellied man was watching Harry anxiously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hagrid\rquote s fine, son,\rdblquote  said the man, \ldblquote the wife\rquote s seeing to him now. How are you feeling? Anything else broken? I\rquote ve fixed your ribs, your tooth, and your arm. I\rquote m Ted, by the way, Ted Tonks \emdash  Dora\rquote s father.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry sat up too quickly: Lights popped in front of his eyes and he felt sick and giddy.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Voldemort \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Easy, now,\rdblquote  said Ted Tonks, placing a hand on Harry\rquote s shoul\-der and pushing him back against the cushions. \ldblquote That was a nasty crash you just had. What happened, anyway? Something go wrong with the bike? Arthur Weasley overstretch himself again, him and his Muggle contraptions?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry, as his scar pulsed like an open wound. \ldblquote Death Eaters, loads of them \emdash  we were chased \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Death Eaters?\rdblquote  said Ted sharply. \ldblquote What d\rquote you mean, Death Eaters? I thought they didn\rquote t know you were being moved tonight, I thought \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They knew,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ted Tonks looked up at the ceiling as though he could see through it to the sky above.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, we know our protective charms hold, then, don\rquote t we? They shouldn\rquote t be able to get within a hundred yards of the place in any direction.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Now Harry understood why Voldemort had vanished; it had been at the point when the motorbike crossed the barrier of the Order\rquote s charms. He only hoped they would continue to work: He imagined Voldemort, a hundred yards above them as they spoke, looking for a way to penetrate what Harry visualized as a great transparent bubble.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He swung his legs off the sofa; he needed to see Hagrid with his own eyes before he would believe that he was alive. He had barely stood up, however, when a door opened and Hagrid squeezed through it, his face covered in mud and blood, limping a little but miraculously alive.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Knocking over two delicate tables and an aspidistra, he covered the floor between them in two strides and pulled Harry into a hug that nearly cracked his newly repaired ribs. \ldblquote Blimey, Harry, how did yeh get out o\rquote  that? I thought we were both goners.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, me too. I can\rquote t believe \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry broke off. He had just noticed the woman who had entered the room behind Hagrid.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You!\rdblquote  he shouted, and he thrust his hand into his pocket, but it was empty.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Your wand\rquote s here, son,\rdblquote  said Ted, tapping it on Harry\rquote s arm. \ldblquote It fell right beside you, I picked it up. And that\rquote s my wife you\rquote re shouting at.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, I\rquote m \emdash  I\rquote m sorry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As she moved forward into the room, Mrs. Tonks\rquote s resemblance\lang3081  \lang1033 to her sister Bellatrix became much less pronounced: Her hair was a light, soft brown and her eyes were wider and kinder. Nevertheless, she looked a little haughty after Harry\rquote s exclamation.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What happened to our daughter?\rdblquote  she asked. \ldblquote Hagrid said you were ambushed; where is Nymphadora?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t know,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote We don\rquote t know what happened to anyone else.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She and Ted exchanged looks. A mixture of fear and guilt gripped Harry at the sight of their expressions; if any of the others had died, it was his fault, all his fault. He had consented to the plan, given them his hair. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Portkey,\rdblquote  he said, remembering all of a sudden. \ldblquote We\rquote ve got to get back to the Burrow and find out \emdash  then we\rquote ll be able to send you word, or \emdash  or Tonks will, once she\rquote s \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dora\rquote ll be okay, \rquote Dromeda,\rdblquote  said Ted. \ldblquote She knows her stuff, she\rquote s been in plenty of tight spots with the Aurors. The Portkey\rquote s through here,\rdblquote  he added to Harry. \ldblquote It\rquote s supposed to leave in three minutes, if you want to take it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, we do,\rdblquote  said Harry. He seized his rucksack, swung it onto his shoulders. \ldblquote I \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He looked at Mrs. Tonks, wanting to apologize for the state of fear in which he left her and for which he felt so terribly respon\-sible, but no words occurred to him that did not seem hollow and insincere.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ll tell Tonks \emdash  Dora \emdash  to send word, when she \'85 Thanks for patching us up, thanks for everything. I \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was glad to leave the room and follow Ted Tonks along a short hallway and into a bedroom. Hagrid came after them, bending low to avoid hitting his head on the door lintel.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There you go, son. That\rquote s the Portkey.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Tonks was pointing to a small, silver-backed hairbrush lying on the dressing table.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thanks,\rdblquote  said Harry, reaching out to place a finger on it, ready to leave.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wait a moment,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, looking around. \ldblquote Harry, where\rquote s Hedwig?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She \'85 she got hit,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The realization crashed over him: He felt ashamed of himself as the tears stung his eyes. The owl had been his companion, his one great link with the magical world whenever he had been forced to return to the Dursleys.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hagrid reached out a great hand and patted him painfully on the shoulder.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Never mind,\rdblquote  he said gruffly. \ldblquote Never mind. She had a great old life \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hagrid!\rdblquote  said Ted Tonks warningly, as the hairbrush glowed bright blue, and Hagrid only just got his forefinger to it in time.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 With a jerk behind the navel as though an invisible hook and line had dragged him forward, Harry was pulled into nothingness, spin\-ning uncontrollably, his finger glued to the Portkey as he and Hagrid hurtled away from Mr. Tonks. Seconds later Harry\rquote s feet slammed onto hard ground and he fell onto his hands and knees in the yard of the Burrow. He heard screams. Throwing aside the no longer glowing hairbrush, Harry stood up, swaying slightly, and saw Mrs. Weasley and Ginny running down the steps by the back door as Hagrid, who had also collapsed on landing, clambered laboriously to his feet.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry? You are the real Harry? What happened? Where are the others?\rdblquote  cried Mrs. Weasley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What d\rquote you mean? Isn\rquote t anyone else back?\rdblquote  Harry panted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The answer was clearly etched in Mrs. Weasley\rquote s pale face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Death Eaters were waiting for us,\rdblquote  Harry told her. \ldblquote We were surrounded the moment we took off\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash  they knew it was to\-night \emdash  I don\rquote t know what happened to anyone else, four of them chased us, it was all we could do to get away, and then Voldemort caught up with us \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He could hear the self-justifying note in his voice, the plea for her to understand why he did not know what had happened to her sons, but \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank goodness you\rquote re all right,\rdblquote  she said, pulling him into a hug he did not feel he deserved.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Haven\rquote t go\rquote  any brandy, have yeh, Molly?\rdblquote  asked Hagrid a little shakily. \ldblquote Fer medicinal purposes?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She could have summoned it by magic, but as she hurried back toward the crooked house, Harry knew that she wanted to hide her face. He turned to Ginny and she answered his unspoken plea for information at once.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ron and Tonks should have been back first, but they missed their Portkey, it came back without them,\rdblquote  she said, pointing at a rusty oil can lying on the ground nearby. \ldblquote And that one,\rdblquote  she pointed at an ancient sneaker, \ldblquote should have been Dad and Fred\rquote s, they were supposed to be second. You and Hagrid were third and,\rdblquote  she checked her watch, \ldblquote if they made it, George and Lupin ought to be back in about a minute.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Weasley reappeared carrying a bottle of brandy, which she handed to Hagrid. He uncorked it and drank it straight down in one.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mum!\rdblquote  shouted Ginny, pointing to a spot several feet away.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A blue light had appeared in the darkness: It grew larger and brighter, and Lupin and George appeared, spinning and then falling. Harry knew immediately that there was something wrong: Lupin was supporting George, who was unconscious and whose face was covered in blood.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry ran forward and seized George\rquote s legs. Together, he and Lupin carried George into the house and through the kitchen to the sitting room, where they laid him on the sofa. As the lamplight fell across George\rquote s head, Ginny gasped and Harry\rquote s stomach lurched: One of George\rquote s ears was missing. The side of his head and neck were drenched in wet, shockingly scarlet blood.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 No sooner had Mrs. Weasley bent over her son than Lupin grabbed Harry by the upper arm and dragged him, none too gently, back into the kitchen, where Hagrid was still attempting to ease his bulk through the back door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oi!\rdblquote  said Hagrid indignantly. \ldblquote Le\rquote  go of him! Le\rquote  go of Harry!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin ignored him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What creature sat in the corner the first time that Harry Potter visited my office at Hogwarts?\rdblquote  he said, giving Harry a small shake. \ldblquote Answer me!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A \emdash  a grindylow in a tank, wasn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin released Harry and fell back against a kitchen cupboard.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wha\rquote  was tha\rquote  about?\rdblquote  roared Hagrid.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry, Harry, but I had to check,\rdblquote  said Lupin tersely. \ldblquote We\rquote ve been betrayed. Voldemort knew that you were being moved tonight and the only people who could have told him were directly involved in the plan. You might have been an impostor.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So why aren\rquote  you checkin\rquote  me?\rdblquote  panted Hagrid, still struggling to fit through the door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re half-giant,\rdblquote  said Lupin, looking up at Hagrid. \ldblquote The Polyjuice Potion is designed for human use only.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote None of the Order would have told Voldemort we were mov\-ing tonight,\rdblquote  said Harry. The idea was dreadful to him, he could not believe it of any of them. \ldblquote Voldemort only caught up with me toward the end, he didn\rquote t know which one I was in the beginning. If he\rquote d been in on the plan he\rquote d have known from the start I was the one with Hagrid.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Voldemort caught up with you?\rdblquote  said Lupin sharply. \ldblquote What happened? How did you escape?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry explained briefly how the Death Eaters pursuing them had seemed to recognize him as the true Harry, how they had aban\-doned the chase, how they must have summoned Voldemort, who had appeared just before he and Hagrid had reached the sanctuary of Tonks\rquote s parents.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They recognized you? But how? What had you done?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \'85\rdblquote  Harry tried to remember; the whole journey seemed like a blur of panic and confusion. \ldblquote I saw Stan Shunpike. \'85 You know, the bloke who was the conductor on the Knight Bus? And I tried to Disarm him instead of\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash  well, he doesn\rquote t know what he\rquote s doing, does he? He must be Imperiused!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin looked aghast.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, the time for Disarming is past! These people are trying to capture and kill you! At least Stun if you aren\rquote t prepared to kill!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We were hundreds of feet up! Stan\rquote s not himself, and if I Stunned him and he\rquote d fallen, he\rquote d have died the same as if I\rquote d used Avada Kedavra! Expelliarmus saved me from Voldemort two years ago,\rdblquote  Harry added defiantly. Lupin was reminding him of the sneering\lang3081  \lang1033 Hufflepuff Zacharias Smith, who had jeered at Harry for wanting to teach Dumbledore\rquote s Army how to Disarm.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, Harry,\rdblquote  said Lupin with painful restraint, \ldblquote and a great num\-ber of Death Eaters witnessed that happening! Forgive me, but it was a very unusual move then, under imminent threat of death. Repeating it tonight in front of Death Eaters who either witnessed or heard about the first occasion was close to suicidal!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So you think I should have killed Stan Shunpike?\rdblquote  said Harry angrily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course not,\rdblquote  said Lupin, \ldblquote but the Death Eaters \emdash  frankly, most people! \emdash  would have expected you to attack back! Expelliar\-mus is a useful spell, Harry, but the Death Eaters seem to think it is your signature move, and I urge you not to let it become so!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin was making Harry feel idiotic, and yet there was still a grain of defiance inside him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I won\rquote t blast people out of my way just because they\rquote re there,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote That\rquote s Voldemort\rquote s job.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin\rquote s retort was lost: Finally succeeding in squeezing through the door, Hagrid staggered to a chair and sat down; it collapsed beneath him. Ignoring his mingled oaths and apologies, Harry ad\-dressed Lupin again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Will George be okay?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 All Lupin\rquote s frustration with Harry seemed to drain away at the question.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think so, although there\rquote s no chance of replacing his ear, not when it\rquote s been cursed off\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a scuffling from outside. Lupin dived for the back door; Harry leapt over Hagrid\rquote s legs and sprinted into the yard.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Two figures had appeared in the yard, and as Harry ran toward them he realized they were Hermione, now returning to her normal appearance, and Kingsley, both clutching a bent coat hanger. Hermi\-one flung herself into Harry\rquote s arms, but Kingsley showed no pleasure at the sight of any of them. Over Hermione\rquote s shoulder Harry saw him raise his wand and point it at Lupin\rquote s chest.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The last words Albus Dumbledore spoke to the pair of us?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote Harry is the best hope we have. Trust him,\rquote  \rdblquote  said Lupin calmly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Kingsley turned his wand on Harry, but Lupin said, \ldblquote It\rquote s him, I\rquote ve checked!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All right, all right!\rdblquote  said Kingsley, stowing his wand back be\-neath his cloak. \ldblquote But somebody betrayed us! They knew, they knew it was tonight!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So it seems,\rdblquote  replied Lupin, \ldblquote but apparently they did not realize that there would be seven Harrys.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Small comfort!\rdblquote  snarled Kingsley. \ldblquote Who else is back?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Only Harry, Hagrid, George, and me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione stifled a little moan behind her hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What happened to you?\rdblquote  Lupin asked Kingsley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Followed by five, injured two, might\rquote ve killed one,\rdblquote  Kingsley reeled off, \ldblquote and we saw You-Know-Who as well, he joined the chase halfway through but vanished pretty quickly. Remus, he can \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fly,\rdblquote  supplied Harry. \ldblquote I saw him too, he came after Hagrid and me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So that\rquote s why he left, to follow you!\rdblquote  said Kingsley. \ldblquote I couldn\rquote t un\-derstand why he\rquote d vanished. But what made him change targets?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry behaved a little too kindly to Stan Shunpike,\rdblquote  said Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Stan?\rdblquote  repeated Hermione. \ldblquote But I thought he was in Azkaban?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Kingsley let out a mirthless laugh.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hermione, there\rquote s obviously been a mass breakout which the Ministry has hushed up. Travers\rquote s hood fell off when I cursed him, he\rquote s supposed to be inside too. But what happened to you, Remus? Where\rquote s George?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He lost an ear,\rdblquote  said Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Lost an \emdash  ?\rdblquote  repeated Hermione in a high voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Snape\rquote s work,\rdblquote  said Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Snape\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081  \lang1033 shouted Harry. \ldblquote You didn\rquote t say\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He lost his hood during the chase. Sectumsempra was always a speciality of Snape\rquote s. I wish I could say I\rquote d paid him back in kind, but it was all I could do to keep George on the broom after he was injured, he was losing so much blood.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Silence fell between the four of them as they looked up at the sky. There was no sign of movement; the stars stared back, unblinking, indifferent, unobscured by flying friends. Where was Ron? Where were Fred and Mr. Weasley? Where were Bill, Fleur, Tonks, Mad-Eye, and Mundungus?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, give us a hand!\rdblquote  called Hagrid hoarsely from the door, in which he was stuck again. Glad of something to do, Harry pulled him free, then headed through the empty kitchen and back into the sitting room, where Mrs. Weasley and Ginny were still tending to George. Mrs. Weasley had staunched his bleeding now, and by the lamplight Harry saw a clean, gaping hole where George\rquote s ear had been.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How is he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Weasley looked around and said, \ldblquote I can\rquote t make it grow back, not when it\rquote s been removed by Dark Magic. But it could have been so much worse. \'85 He\rquote s alive.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Thank God.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did I hear someone else in the yard?\rdblquote  Ginny asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hermione and Kingsley,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank goodness,\rdblquote  Ginny whispered. They looked at each other; Harry wanted to hug her, hold on to her; he did not even care much that Mrs. Weasley was there, but before he could act on the impulse there was a great crash from the kitchen.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ll prove who I am, Kingsley, after I\rquote ve seen my son, now back off if you know what\rquote s good for you!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had never heard Mr. Weasley shout like that before. He burst into the living room, his bald patch gleaming with sweat, his spectacles askew, Fred right behind him, both pale but uninjured.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Arthur!\rdblquote  sobbed Mrs. Weasley. \ldblquote Oh thank goodness!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How is he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Weasley dropped to his knees beside George. For the first time since Harry had known him, Fred seemed to be lost for words. He gaped over the back of the sofa at his twin\rquote s wound as if he could not believe what he was seeing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Perhaps roused by the sound of Fred and their father\rquote s arrival, George stirred.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How do you feel, Georgie?\rdblquote  whispered Mrs. Weasley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 George\rquote s fingers groped for the side of his head.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Saintlike,\rdblquote  he murmured.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s wrong with him?\rdblquote  croaked Fred, looking terrified. \ldblquote Is his mind affected?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Saintlike,\rdblquote  repeated George, opening his eyes and looking up at his brother. \ldblquote You see \'85 I\rquote m holy. \i Holey,\i0  Fred, geddit?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Weasley sobbed harder than ever. Color flooded Fred\rquote s pale face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Pathetic,\rdblquote  he told George. \ldblquote Pathetic! With the whole wide world of ear-related humor before you, you go for \i holey\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah well,\rdblquote  said George, grinning at his tear-soaked mother. \ldblquote You\rquote ll be able to tell us apart now, anyway, Mum.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He looked around.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hi, Harry \emdash  you are Harry, right?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I am,\rdblquote  said Harry, moving closer to the sofa.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, at least we got you back okay,\rdblquote  said George. \ldblquote Why aren\rquote t Ron and Bill huddled round my sickbed?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They\rquote re not back yet, George,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley. George\rquote s grin faded. \par
Harry glanced at Ginny and motioned to her to accompany him back outside. As they walked through the kitchen she said in a low voice, \ldblquote Ron and Tonks should be back by now. They didn\rquote t have a long journey; Auntie Muriel\rquote s not that far from here.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry said nothing. He had been trying to keep fear at bay ever since reaching the Burrow, but now it enveloped him, seeming to crawl over his skin, throbbing in his chest, clogging his throat. As they walked down the back steps into the dark yard, Ginny took his hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Kingsley was striding backward and forward, glancing up at the sky every time he turned. Harry was reminded of Uncle Vernon pacing the living room a million years ago. Hagrid, Hermione, and Lupin stood shoulder to shoulder, gazing upward in silence. None of them looked around when Harry and Ginny joined their silent vigil.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The minutes stretched into what might as well have been years. The slightest breath of wind made them all jump and turn toward the whispering bush or tree in the hope that one of the missing Order members might leap unscathed from its leaves \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And then a broom materialized directly above them and streaked toward the ground \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s them!\rdblquote  screamed Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Tonks landed in a long skid that sent earth and pebbles everywhere.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Remus!\rdblquote  Tonks cried as she staggered off the broom into Lupin\rquote s arms. His face was set and white: He seemed unable to speak. Ron tripped dazedly toward Harry and Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re okay,\rdblquote  he mumbled, before Hermione flew at him and hugged him tightly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I thought \emdash  I thought \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \rquote M all right,\rdblquote  said Ron, patting her on the back. \ldblquote  \rquote M fine.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ron was great,\rdblquote  said Tonks warmly, relinquishing her hold on Lupin. \ldblquote Wonderful. Stunned one of the Death Eaters, straight to the head, and when you\rquote re aiming at a moving target from a flying broom \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You did?\rdblquote  said Hermione, gazing up at Ron with her arms still around his neck.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Always the tone of surprise,\rdblquote  he said a little grumpily, breaking free. \ldblquote Are we the last back?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Ginny, \ldblquote we\rquote re still waiting for Bill and Fleur and Mad-Eye and Mundungus. I\rquote m going to tell Mum and Dad you\rquote re okay, Ron \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She ran back inside.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So what kept you? What happened?\rdblquote  Lupin sounded almost angry at Tonks.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bellatrix,\rdblquote  said Tonks. \ldblquote She wants me quite as much as she wants Harry, Remus, she tried very hard to kill me. I just wish I\rquote d got her, I owe Bellatrix. But we definitely injured Rodolphus. \'85 Then we\lang3081  \lang1033 got to Ron\rquote s Auntie Muriel\rquote s and we\rquote d missed our Portkey and she was fussing over us \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A muscle was jumping in Lupin\rquote s jaw. He nodded, but seemed unable to say anything else.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So what happened to you lot?\rdblquote  Tonks asked, turning to Harry, Hermione, and Kingsley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They recounted the stories of their own journeys, but all the time the continued absence of Bill, Fleur, Mad-Eye, and Mundungus seemed to lie upon them like a frost, its icy bite harder and harder to ignore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m going to have to get back to Downing Street, I should have been there an hour ago,\rdblquote  said Kingsley finally, after a last sweeping gaze at the sky. \ldblquote Let me know when they\rquote re back.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin nodded. With a wave to the others, Kingsley walked away into the darkness toward the gate. Harry thought he heard the faintest \i pop\i0  as Kingsley Disapparated just beyond the Burrow\rquote s boundaries.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. and Mrs. Weasley came racing down the back steps, Ginny behind them. Both parents hugged Ron before turning to Lupin and Tonks.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank you,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, \ldblquote for our sons.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t be silly, Molly,\rdblquote  said Tonks at once.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How\rquote s George?\rdblquote  asked Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s wrong with him?\rdblquote  piped up Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s lost \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But the end of Mrs. Weasley\rquote s sentence was drowned in a gen\-eral outcry: A thestral had just soared into sight and landed a few feet from them. Bill and Fleur slid from its back, windswept but unhurt.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bill! Thank God, thank God \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Weasley ran forward, but the hug Bill bestowed upon her was perfunctory. Looking directly at his father, he said, \ldblquote Mad-Eye\rquote s dead.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Nobody spoke, nobody moved. Harry felt as though something inside him was falling, falling through the earth, leaving him forever.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We saw it,\rdblquote  said Bill; Fleur nodded, tear tracks glittering on her cheeks in the light from the kitchen window. \ldblquote It happened just after we broke out of the circle: Mad-Eye and Dung were close by us, they were heading north too. Voldemort \emdash  he can fly \emdash  went straight for them. Dung panicked, I heard him cry out, Mad-Eye tried to stop him, but he Disapparated. Voldemort\rquote s curse hit Mad-Eye full in the face, he fell backward off his broom and \emdash  there was nothing we could do, nothing, we had half a dozen of them on our own tail \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Bill\rquote s voice broke.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course you couldn\rquote t have done anything,\rdblquote  said Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They all stood looking at each other. Harry could not quite com\-prehend it. Mad-Eye dead; it could not be. \'85 Mad-Eye, so tough, so brave, the consummate survivor \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 At last it seemed to dawn on everyone, though nobody said it, that there was no point waiting in the yard anymore, and in silence they followed Mr. and Mrs. Weasley back into the Burrow, and into the living room, where Fred and George were laughing together.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s wrong?\rdblquote  said Fred, scanning their faces as they entered. \ldblquote What\rquote s happened? Who\rquote s \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mad-Eye,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote Dead.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The twins\rquote  grins turned to grimaces of shock. Nobody seemed\lang3081  \lang1033 to know what to do. Tonks was crying silently into a handkerchief: She had been close to Mad-Eye, Harry knew, his favorite and his prot\'e9g\'e9e at the Ministry of Magic. Hagrid, who had sat down on the floor in the corner where he had most space, was dabbing at his eyes with his tablecloth-sized handkerchief.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Bill walked over to the sideboard and pulled out a bottle of fire-whisky and some glasses.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Here,\rdblquote  he said, and with a wave of his wand he sent twelve full glasses soaring through the room to each of them, holding the thir\-teenth aloft. \ldblquote Mad-Eye.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mad-Eye,\rdblquote  they all said, and drank.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mad-Eye,\rdblquote  echoed Hagrid, a little late, with a hiccup.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The firewhisky seared Harry\rquote s throat. It seemed to burn feeling back into him, dispelling the numbness and sense of unreality, fir\-ing him with something that was like courage.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So Mundungus disappeared?\rdblquote  said Lupin, who had drained his own glass in one.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The atmosphere changed at once. Everybody looked tense, watch\-ing Lupin, both wanting him to go on, it seemed to Harry, and slightly afraid of what they might hear.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I know what you\rquote re thinking,\rdblquote  said Bill, \ldblquote and I wondered that too, on the way back here, because they seemed to be expecting us, didn\rquote t they? But Mundungus can\rquote t have betrayed us. They didn\rquote t know there would be seven Harrys, that confused them the moment we appeared, and in case you\rquote ve forgotten, it was Mundungus who suggested that little bit of skullduggery. Why wouldn\rquote t he have told them the essential point? I think Dung panicked, it\rquote s as simple as that. He didn\rquote t want to come in the first place, but Mad-Eye made him, and You-Know-Who went straight for them. It was enough to make anyone panic.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You-Know-Who acted exactly as Mad-Eye expected him to,\rdblquote  sniffed Tonks. \ldblquote Mad-Eye said he\rquote d expect the real Harry to be with the toughest, most skilled Aurors. He chased Mad-Eye first, and when Mundungus gave them away he switched to Kingsley. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, and zat eez all very good,\rdblquote  snapped Fleur, \ldblquote but still eet does not explain \rquote ow zey knew we were moving \rquote Arry tonight, does eet? Somebody must \rquote ave been careless. Somebody let slip ze date to an outsider. It is ze only explanation for zem knowing ze date but not ze \rquote ole plan.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She glared around at them all, tear tracks still etched on her beau\-tiful face, silently daring any of them to contradict her. Nobody did. The only sound to break the silence was that of Hagrid hiccuping from behind his handkerchief. Harry glanced at Hagrid, who had just risked his own life to save Harry\rquote s \emdash  Hagrid, whom he loved, whom he trusted, who had once been tricked into giving Voldemort crucial information in exchange for a dragon\rquote s egg. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  Harry said aloud, and they all looked at him, surprised: The firewhisky seemed to have amplified his voice. \ldblquote I mean \'85 if somebody made a mistake,\rdblquote  Harry went on, \ldblquote and let something slip, I know they didn\rquote t mean to do it. It\rquote s not their fault,\rdblquote  he repeated, again a little louder than he would usually have spoken. \ldblquote We\rquote ve got to trust each other. I trust all of you, I don\rquote t think anyone in this room would ever sell me to Voldemort.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 More silence followed his words. They were all looking at him;\lang3081  \lang1033 Harry felt a little hot again, and drank some more firewhisky for\lang3081  \lang1033 something to do. As he drank, he thought of Mad-Eye. Mad-Eye\lang3081  \lang1033 had always been scathing about Dumbledore\rquote s willingness to trust\lang3081  \lang1033 people.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well said, Harry,\rdblquote  said Fred unexpectedly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, \rquote ear, \rquote ear,\rdblquote  said George, with half a glance at Fred, the cor\-ner of whose mouth twitched.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin was wearing an odd expression as he looked at Harry. It was close to pitying.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You think I\rquote m a fool?\rdblquote  demanded Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I think you\rquote re like James,\rdblquote  said Lupin, \ldblquote who would have regarded it as the height of dishonor to mistrust his friends.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry knew what Lupin was getting at: that his father had been betrayed by his friend, Peter Pettigrew. He felt irrationally angry. He wanted to argue, but Lupin had turned away from him, set down his glass upon a side table, and addressed Bill, \ldblquote There\rquote s work to do. I can ask Kingsley whether \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Bill at once, \ldblquote I\rquote ll do it, I\rquote ll come.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where are you going?\rdblquote  said Tonks and Fleur together.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mad-Eye\rquote s body,\rdblquote  said Lupin. \ldblquote We need to recover it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Can\rquote t it \emdash  ?\rdblquote  began Mrs. Weasley with an appealing look at Bill.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wait?\rdblquote  said Bill. \ldblquote Not unless you\rquote d rather the Death Eaters took it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Nobody spoke. Lupin and Bill said good-bye and left.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The rest of them now dropped into chairs, all except for Harry, who remained standing. The suddenness and completeness of death was with them like a presence.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve got to go too,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ten pairs of startled eyes looked at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t be silly, Harry,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley. \ldblquote What are you talk\-ing about?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I can\rquote t stay here.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He rubbed his forehead; it was prickling again, it had not hurt like this for more than a year.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re all in danger while I\rquote m here. I don\rquote t want \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But don\rquote t be so silly!\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley. \ldblquote The whole point of tonight was to get you here safely, and thank goodness it worked. And Fleur\rquote s agreed to get married here rather than in France, we\rquote ve arranged everything so that we can all stay together and look after you \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She did not understand; she was making him feel worse, not better.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If Voldemort finds out I\rquote m here \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But why should he?\rdblquote  asked Mrs. Weasley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There are a dozen places you might be now, Harry,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote He\rquote s got no way of knowing which safe house you\rquote re in.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s not me I\rquote m worried for!\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We know that,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley quietly, \ldblquote but it would make our efforts tonight seem rather pointless if you left.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yer not goin\rquote  anywhere,\rdblquote  growled Hagrid. \ldblquote Blimey, Harry, after all we wen\rquote  through ter get you here?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, what about my bleeding ear?\rdblquote  said George, hoisting him\-self up on his cushions.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I know that \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mad-Eye wouldn\rquote t want \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I KNOW!\rdblquote  Harry bellowed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He felt beleaguered and blackmailed: Did they think he did not know what they had done for him, didn\rquote t they understand that it was for precisely that reason that he wanted to go now, before they\lang3081  \lang1033 had to suffer any more on his behalf? There was a long and awkward silence in which his scar continued to prickle and throb, and which was broken at last by Mrs. Weasley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where\rquote s Hedwig, Harry?\rdblquote  she said coaxingly. \ldblquote We can put her up with Pigwidgeon and give her something to eat.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His insides clenched like a fist. He could not tell her the truth. He drank the last of his firewhisky to avoid answering.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wait till it gets out yeh did it again, Harry,\rdblquote  said Hagrid. \ldblquote Es\-caped him, fought him off when he was right on top of yeh!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It wasn\rquote t me,\rdblquote  said Harry flatly. \ldblquote It was my wand. My wand acted of its own accord.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 After a few moments, Hermione said gently, \ldblquote But that\rquote s impos\-sible, Harry. You mean that you did magic without meaning to; you reacted instinctively.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote The bike was falling, I couldn\rquote t have told you where Voldemort was, but my wand spun in my hand and found him and shot a spell at him, and it wasn\rquote t even a spell I recognized. I\rquote ve never made gold flames appear before.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Often,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, \ldblquote when you\rquote re in a pressured situation you can produce magic you never dreamed of. Small children often find, before they\rquote re trained \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It wasn\rquote t like that,\rdblquote  said Harry through gritted teeth. His scar was burning: He felt angry and frustrated; he hated the idea that they were all imagining him to have power to match Voldemort\rquote s.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 No one said anything. He knew that they did not believe him. Now that he came to think of it, he had never heard of a wand per\-forming magic on its own before.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His scar seared with pain; it was all he could do not to moan aloud. Muttering about fresh air, he set down his glass and left the room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As he crossed the dark yard, the great skeletal thestral looked up, rustled its enormous batlike wings, then resumed its grazing. Harry stopped at the gate into the garden, staring out at its overgrown plants, rubbing his pounding forehead and thinking of Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore would have believed him, he knew it. Dumbledore would have known how and why Harry\rquote s wand had acted indepen\-dently, because Dumbledore always had the answers; he had known about wands, had explained to Harry the strange connection that existed between his wand and Voldemort\rquote s. \'85 But Dumbledore, like Mad-Eye, like Sirius, like his parents, like his poor owl, all were gone where Harry could never talk to them again. He felt a burning in his throat that had nothing to do with firewhisky \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And then, out of nowhere, the pain in his scar peaked. As he clutched his forehead and closed his eyes, a voice screamed inside his head.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i You told me the problem would be solved by using another\rquote s wand\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And into his mind burst the vision of an emaciated old man lying in rags upon a stone floor, screaming, a horrible, drawn-out scream, a scream of unendurable agony. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No! No! I beg you, I beg you. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You lied to Lord Voldemort, Ollivander!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I did not. \'85 I swear I did not. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You sought to help Potter, to help him escape me!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I swear I did not. \'85 I believed a different wand would work. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Explain, then, what happened. Lucius\rquote s wand is destroyed!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I cannot understand. \'85 The connection \'85 exists only \'85 be\-tween your two wands. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Lies\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Please \'85 I beg you. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And Harry saw the white hand raise its wand and felt Voldemort\rquote s surge of vicious anger, saw the frail old man on the floor writhe in agony \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was over as quickly as it had come: Harry stood shaking in the darkness, clutching the gate into the garden, his heart racing, his scar still tingling. It was several moments before he realized that Ron and Hermione were at his side.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, come back in the house,\rdblquote  Hermione whispered. \ldblquote You aren\rquote t still thinking of leaving?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, you\rquote ve got to stay, mate,\rdblquote  said Ron, thumping Harry on the back.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you all right?\rdblquote  Hermione asked, close enough now to look into Harry\rquote s face. \ldblquote You look awful!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Harry shakily, \ldblquote I probably look better than Olli\-vander. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 When he had finished telling them what he had seen, Ron looked appalled, but Hermione downright terrified.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But it was supposed to have stopped! Your scar \emdash  it wasn\rquote t sup\-posed to do this anymore! You mustn\rquote t let that connection open up again \emdash  Dumbledore wanted you to close your mind!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 When he did not reply, she gripped his arm.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, he\rquote s taking over the Ministry and the newspapers and half the Wizarding world! Don\rquote t let him inside your head too!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\par
