The shock of losing Mad-Eye hung over the house in the days that followed; Harry kept expecting to see him stumping in through the back door like the other Order members, who passed in and out to relay news. Harry felt that nothing but action would assuage his feelings of guilt and grief and that he ought to set out on his mission to find and destroy Horcruxes as soon as possible.\par
\ldblquote Well, you can\rquote t do anything about the\rdblquote  \emdash  Ron mouthed the word \i Horcruxes\i0  \emdash  \ldblquote till you\rquote re seventeen. You\rquote ve still got the Trace on you. And we can plan here as well as anywhere, can\rquote t we? Or,\rdblquote  he dropped his voice to a whisper, \ldblquote d\rquote you reckon you already know where the You-Know-Whats are?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  Harry admitted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think Hermione\rquote s been doing a bit of research,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote She said she was saving it for when you got here.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were sitting at the breakfast table; Mr. Weasley and Bill had\lang3081  \lang1033 just left for work. Mrs. Weasley had gone upstairs to wake Hermione and Ginny, while Fleur had drifted off to take a bath.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Trace\rquote ll break on the thirty-first,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote That means I only need to stay here four days. Then I can \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
