\lang1033\ldblquote Dad is. He helped Fred and George transform the ghoul. Mum \'85 well, you\rquote ve seen what she\rquote s like. She won\rquote t accept we\rquote re going till we\rquote ve gone.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was silence in the room, broken only by gentle thuds as Hermione continued to throw books onto one pile or the other. Ron sat watching her, and Harry looked from one to the other, unable to say anything. The measures they had taken to protect their families made him realize, more than anything else could have done, that they really were going to come with him and that they knew exactly how dangerous that would be. He wanted to tell them what that meant to him, but he simply could not find words important enough.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Through the silence came the muffled sounds of Mrs. Weasley shouting from four floors below.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ginny\rquote s probably left a speck of dust on a poxy napkin ring,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote I dunno why the Delacours have got to come two days before the wedding.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fleur\rquote s sister\rquote s a bridesmaid, she needs to be here for the rehearsal, and she\rquote s too young to come on her own,\rdblquote  said Hermione, as she pored indecisively over \i Break with a Banshee.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, guests aren\rquote t going to help Mum\rquote s stress levels,\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What we really need to decide,\rdblquote  said Hermione, tossing \i Defensive Magical Theory\i0  into the bin without a second glance and picking up \i An Appraisal of Magical Education in Europe,\i0  \ldblquote is where we\rquote re going after we leave here. I know you said you wanted to go to Godric\rquote s Hollow first, Harry, and I understand why, but\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 shouldn\rquote t we make the Horcruxes our priority?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If we knew where any of the Horcruxes were, I\rquote d agree with you,\rdblquote  said Harry, who did not believe that Hermione really understood his desire to return to Godric\rquote s Hollow. His parents\rquote  graves were only part of the attraction: He had a strong, though inexplicable, feeling that the place held answers for him. Perhaps it was simply because it was there that he had survived Voldemort\rquote s Killing Curse; now that he was facing the challenge of repeating the feat, Harry was drawn to the place where it had happened, wanting to understand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t you think there\rquote s a possibility that Voldemort\rquote s keeping a watch on Godric\rquote s Hollow?\rdblquote  Hermione asked. \ldblquote He might expect you to go back and visit your parents\rquote  graves once you\rquote re free to go wherever you like?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 This had not occurred to Harry. While he struggled to find a counterargument, Ron spoke up, evidently following his own train of thought.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This R.A.B. person,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote You know, the one who stole the real locket?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione nodded.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He said in his note he was going to destroy it, didn\rquote t he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry dragged his rucksack toward him and pulled out the fake Horcrux in which R.A.B.\rquote s note was still folded.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i I have stolen the real Horcrux and intend to destroy it as soon as I can,\i0\rquote  \rdblquote  Harry read out.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, what if he \i did\i0  finish it off?\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Or she,\rdblquote  interposed Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Whichever,\rdblquote  said Ron, \ldblquote it\rquote d be one less for us to do!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, but we\rquote re still going to have to try and trace the real locket, aren\rquote t we?\rdblquote  said Hermione, \ldblquote to find out whether or not it\rquote s destroyed.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And once we get hold of it, how \i do\i0  you destroy a Horcrux?\rdblquote  asked Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Hermione, \ldblquote I\rquote ve been researching that.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How?\rdblquote  asked Harry. \ldblquote I didn\rquote t think there were any books on Horcruxes in the library?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There weren\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Hermione, who had turned pink. \ldblquote Dumble\-dore removed them all, but he \emdash  he didn\rquote t destroy them.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron sat up straight, wide-eyed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How in the name of Merlin\rquote s pants have you managed to get your hands on those Horcrux books?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It \emdash  it wasn\rquote t stealing!\rdblquote  said Hermione, looking from Harry to Ron with a kind of desperation. \ldblquote They were still library books, even if Dumbledore had taken them off the shelves. Anyway, if he \i really\i0  didn\rquote t want anyone to get at them, I\rquote m sure he would have made it much harder to \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Get to the point!\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 it was easy,\rdblquote  said Hermione in a small voice. \ldblquote I just did a Summoning Charm. You know \emdash  Accio. And \emdash  they zoomed out of Dumbledore\rquote s study window right into the girls\rquote  dormitory.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But when did you do this?\rdblquote  Harry asked, regarding Hermione with a mixture of admiration and incredulity.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Just after his \emdash  Dumbledore\rquote s \emdash  funeral,\rdblquote  said Hermione in an even smaller voice. \ldblquote Right after we agreed we\rquote d leave school and go and look for the Horcruxes. When I went back upstairs to get my things it \emdash  it just occurred to me that the more we knew about them, the better it would be \'85 and I was alone in there \'85 so I tried \'85 and it worked. They flew straight in through the open window and I \emdash  I packed them.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She swallowed and then said imploringly, \ldblquote I can\rquote t believe Dum\-bledore would have been angry, it\rquote s not as though we\rquote re going to use the information to make a Horcrux, is it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Can you hear us complaining?\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Where are these books anyway?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione rummaged for a moment and then extracted from the pile a large volume, bound in faded black leather. She looked a little nauseated and held it as gingerly as if it were something re\-cently dead.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This is the one that gives explicit instructions on how to make a Horcrux. \i Secrets of the Darkest Art\lang3081\i0  \lang1033\emdash  it\rquote s a horrible book, really awful, full of evil magic. I wonder when Dumbledore removed it from the library. \'85 If he didn\rquote t do it until he was headmaster, I bet Voldemort got all the instruction he needed from here.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why did he have to ask Slughorn how to make a Horcrux, then, if he\rquote d already read that?\rdblquote  asked Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He only approached Slughorn to find out what would happen if you split your soul into seven,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Dumbledore was sure Riddle already knew how to make a Horcrux by the time he asked Slughorn about them. I think you\rquote re right, Hermione, that could easily have been where he got the information.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And the more I\rquote ve read about them,\rdblquote  said Hermione, \ldblquote the more horrible they seem, and the less I can believe that he actually made six. It warns in this book how unstable you make the rest of your soul by ripping it, and that\rquote s just by making one Horcrux!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry remembered what Dumbledore had said about Voldemort moving beyond \ldblquote usual evil.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Isn\rquote t there any way of putting yourself back together?\rdblquote  Ron asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Hermione with a hollow smile, \ldblquote but it would be ex\-cruciatingly painful.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why? How do you do it?\rdblquote  asked Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Remorse,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote You\rquote ve got to really feel what you\rquote ve done. There\rquote s a footnote. Apparently the pain of it can destroy you. I can\rquote t see Voldemort attempting it somehow, can you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Ron, before Harry could answer. \ldblquote So does it say how to destroy Horcruxes in that book?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Hermione, now turning the fragile pages as if examin\-ing rotting entrails, \ldblquote because it warns Dark wizards how strong they have to make the enchantments on them. From all that I\rquote ve read, what Harry did to Riddle\rquote s diary was one of the few really foolproof ways of destroying a Horcrux.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What, stabbing it with a basilisk fang?\rdblquote  asked Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh well, lucky we\rquote ve got such a large supply of basilisk fangs, then,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote I was wondering what we were going to do with them.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It doesn\rquote t have to be a basilisk fang,\rdblquote  said Hermione patiently. \ldblquote It has to be something so destructive that the Horcrux can\rquote t re\-pair itself. Basilisk venom only has one antidote, and it\rquote s incredibly rare \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  phoenix tears,\rdblquote  said Harry, nodding.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Exactly,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote Our problem is that there are very few substances as destructive as basilisk venom, and they\rquote re all danger\-ous to carry around with you. That\rquote s a problem we\rquote re going to have to solve, though, because ripping, smashing, or crushing a Horcrux won\rquote t do the trick. You\rquote ve got to put it beyond magical repair.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But even if we wreck the thing it lives in,\rdblquote  said Ron, \ldblquote why can\rquote t the bit of soul in it just go and live in something else?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because a Horcrux is the complete opposite of a human being.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Seeing that Harry and Ron looked thoroughly confused, Hermi\-one hurried on, \ldblquote Look, if I picked up a sword right now, Ron, and ran you through with it, I wouldn\rquote t damage your soul at all.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Which would be a real comfort to me, I\rquote m sure,\rdblquote  said Ron. Harry laughed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It should be, actually! But my point is that whatever happens to your body, your soul will survive, untouched,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote But it\rquote s the other way round with a Horcrux. The fragment of soul inside it depends on its container, its enchanted body, for survival. It can\rquote t exist without it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That diary sort of died when I stabbed it,\rdblquote  said Harry, remem\-bering ink pouring like blood from the punctured pages, and the screams of the piece of Voldemort\rquote s soul as it vanished.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And once the diary was properly destroyed, the bit of soul trapped in it could no longer exist. Ginny tried to get rid of the\lang3081  \lang1033 diary before you did, flushing it away, but obviously it came back good as new.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hang on,\rdblquote  said Ron, frowning. \ldblquote The bit of soul in that diary was possessing Ginny, wasn\rquote t it? How does that work, then?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote While the magical container is still intact, the bit of soul inside it can flit in and out of someone if they get too close to the object. I don\rquote t mean holding it for too long, it\rquote s nothing to do with touching it,\rdblquote  she added before Ron could speak. \ldblquote I mean close emotionally. Ginny poured her heart out into that diary, she made herself incred\-ibly vulnerable. You\rquote re in trouble if you get too fond of or dependent on the Horcrux.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I wonder how Dumbledore destroyed the ring?\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Why didn\rquote t I ask him? I never really \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His voice tailed away: He was thinking of all the things he should have asked Dumbledore, and of how, since the headmaster had died, it seemed to Harry that he had wasted so many opportunities when Dumbledore had been alive, to find out more \'85 to find out everything. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The silence was shattered as the bedroom door flew open with a wall-shaking crash. Hermione shrieked and dropped \i Secrets of the Darkest Art\i0 ; Crookshanks streaked under the bed, hissing indig\-nantly; Ron jumped off the bed, skidded on a discarded Chocolate Frog wrapper, and smacked his head on the opposite wall; and Harry instinctively dived for his wand before realizing that he was looking up at Mrs. Weasley, whose hair was disheveled and whose face was contorted with rage.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m so sorry to break up this cozy little gathering,\rdblquote  she said, her voice trembling. \ldblquote I\rquote m sure you all need your rest \'85 but there are\lang3081  \lang1033 wedding presents stacked in my room that need sorting out and I was under the impression that you had agreed to help.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yes,\rdblquote  said Hermione, looking terrified as she leapt to her feet, sending books flying in every direction, \ldblquote we will \'85 we\rquote re sorry \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 With an anguished look at Harry and Ron, Hermione hurried out of the room after Mrs. Weasley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s like being a house-elf,\rdblquote  complained Ron in an undertone, still massaging his head as he and Harry followed. \ldblquote Except without the job satisfaction. The sooner this wedding\rquote s over, the happier I\rquote ll be.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote then we\rquote ll have nothing to do except find Horcruxes. \'85 It\rquote ll be like a holiday, won\rquote t it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron started to laugh, but at the sight of the enormous pile of wedding presents waiting for them in Mrs. Weasley\rquote s room, stopped quite abruptly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Delacours arrived the following morning at eleven o\rquote clock. Harry, Ron, Hermione, and Ginny were feeling quite resentful to\-ward Fleur\rquote s family by this time, and it was with ill grace that Ron stumped back upstairs to put on matching socks, and Harry at\-tempted to flatten his hair. Once they had all been deemed smart enough, they trooped out into the sunny backyard to await the visitors.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had never seen the place looking so tidy. The rusty caul\-drons and old Wellington boots that usually littered the steps by the back door were gone, replaced by two new Flutterby bushes standing either side of the door in large pots; though there was no breeze, the leaves waved lazily, giving an attractive rippling effect. The chickens had been shut away, the yard had been swept, and the nearby garden\lang3081  \lang1033 had been pruned, plucked, and generally spruced up, although Harry, who liked it in its overgrown state, thought that it looked rather for\-lorn without its usual contingent of capering gnomes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He had lost track of how many security enchantments had been placed upon the Burrow by both the Order and the Ministry; all he knew was that it was no longer possible for anybody to travel by magic directly into the place. Mr. Weasley had therefore gone to meet the Delacours on top of a nearby hill, where they were to arrive by Portkey. The first sound of their approach was an unusu\-ally high-pitched laugh, which turned out to be coming from Mr. Weasley, who appeared at the gate moments later, laden with luggage and leading a beautiful blonde woman in long, leaf-green robes, who could only be Fleur\rquote s mother.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Maman!\rdblquote  cried Fleur, rushing forward to embrace her. \ldblquote Papa!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Monsieur Delacour was nowhere near as attractive as his wife; he was a head shorter and extremely plump, with a little, pointed black beard. However, he looked good-natured. Bouncing toward Mrs. Weasley on high-heeled boots, he kissed her twice on each cheek, leaving her flustered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You \rquote ave been to much trouble,\rdblquote  he said in a deep voice. \ldblquote Fleur tells us you \rquote ave been working very \rquote ard.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, it\rquote s been nothing, nothing!\rdblquote  trilled Mrs. Weasley. \ldblquote No trou\-ble at all!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
