\lang1033\ldblquote Dear lady!\rdblquote  said Monsieur Delacour, still holding Mrs. Weasley\rquote s hand between his own two plump ones and beaming. \ldblquote We are most honored at the approaching union of our two families! Let me pres\-ent my wife, Apolline.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Madame Delacour glided forward and stooped to kiss Mrs. Wea\-sley too.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Enchant\lang3081\'e9\lang1033 e,\i0\rdblquote\lang3081  \lang1033 she said. \ldblquote Your \rquote usband \rquote as been telling us such amus\-ing stories!\rdblquote\lang3081\i\par
\lang1033\i0 Mr. Weasley gave a maniacal laugh; Mrs. Weasley threw him a look, upon which he became immediately silent and assumed an expression appropriate to the sickbed of a close friend.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And, of course, you \rquote ave met my leetle daughter, Gabrielle!\rdblquote  said Monsieur Delacour. Gabrielle was Fleur in miniature; eleven years old, with waist-length hair of pure, silvery blonde, she gave Mrs. Weasley a dazzling smile and hugged her, then threw Harry a glow\-ing look, batting her eyelashes. Ginny cleared her throat loudly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, come in, do!\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley brightly, and she ushered the Delacours into the house, with many \ldblquote No, please!\rdblquote s and \ldblquote After you!\rdblquote s and \ldblquote Not at all!\rdblquote s.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Delacours, it soon transpired, were helpful, pleasant guests. They were pleased with everything and keen to assist with the prepa\-rations for the wedding. Monsieur Delacour pronounced every\-thing from the seating plan to the bridesmaids\rquote  shoes \ldblquote\i Charmant\i0 !\rdblquote  Madame Delacour was most accomplished at household spells and had the oven properly cleaned in a trice; Gabrielle followed her elder sister around, trying to assist in any way she could and jabbering away in rapid French.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 On the downside, the Burrow was not built to accommodate so many people. Mr. and Mrs. Weasley were now sleeping in the sit\-ting room, having shouted down Monsieur and Madame Delacour\rquote s protests and insisted they take their bedroom. Gabrielle was sleeping with Fleur in Percy\rquote s old room, and Bill would be sharing with Charlie, his best man, once Charlie arrived from Romania. Opportunities to make plans together became virtually nonexistent, and it was in desperation that Harry, Ron, and Hermione took to volunteering to feed the chickens just to escape the overcrowded house.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But she \i still\i0  won\rquote t leave us alone!\rdblquote  snarled Ron, as their second attempt at a meeting in the yard was foiled by the appearance of Mrs. Weasley carrying a large basket of laundry in her arms.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, good, you\rquote ve fed the chickens,\rdblquote  she called as she approached them. \ldblquote We\rquote d better shut them away again before the men arrive tomorrow \'85 to put up the tent for the wedding,\rdblquote  she explained, pausing to lean against the henhouse. She looked exhausted. \ldblquote Mil\-lamant\rquote s Magic Marquees \'85 they\rquote re very good, Bill\rquote s escorting them. \'85 You\rquote d better stay inside while they\rquote re here, Harry. I must say it does complicate organizing a wedding, having all these secu\-rity spells around the place.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry,\rdblquote  said Harry humbly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, don\rquote t be silly, dear!\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley at once. \ldblquote I didn\rquote t mean \emdash  well, your safety\rquote s much more important! Actually, I\rquote ve been wanting to ask you how you want to celebrate your birthday, Harry. Seventeen, after all, it\rquote s an important day. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t want a fuss,\rdblquote  said Harry quickly, envisaging the addi\-tional strain this would put on them all. \ldblquote Really, Mrs. Weasley, just a normal dinner would be fine. \'85 It\rquote s the day before the wed\-ding. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, well, if you\rquote re sure, dear. I\rquote ll invite Remus and Tonks, shall I? And how about Hagrid?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote d be great,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote But please don\rquote t go to loads of trouble.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not at all, not at all\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 It\rquote s no trouble. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She looked at him, a long, searching look, then smiled a little sadly, straightened up, and walked away. Harry watched as she waved her wand near the washing line, and the damp clothes rose into the air to hang themselves up, and suddenly he felt a great wave of remorse for the inconvenience and the pain he was giving her.\lang3081\par
