\lang1033\ldblquote That is a valuable object,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour, watching Ron. \ldblquote It may even be unique. Certainly it is of Dumbledore\rquote s own design. Why would he have left you an item so rare?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron shook his head, looking bewildered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore must have taught thousands of students,\rdblquote  Scrim\-geour persevered. \ldblquote Yet the only ones he remembered in his will are you three. Why is that? To what use did he think you would put his Deluminator, Mr. Weasley?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Put out lights, I s\rquote pose,\rdblquote  mumbled Ron. \ldblquote What else could I do with it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Evidently Scrimgeour had no suggestions. After squinting at Ron for a moment or two, he turned back to Dumbledore\rquote s will.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i To Miss Hermione Jean Granger, I leave my copy of\i0  The Tales\lang3081  \lang1033 of Beedle the Bard, \i in the hope that she will find it entertaining and instructive.\i0\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Scrimgeour now pulled out of the bag a small book that looked as ancient as the copy of\lang3081  \lang1033\i Secrets of the Darkest Art\i0  upstairs. Its binding was stained and peeling in places. Hermione took it from Scrim\-geour without a word. She held the book in her lap and gazed at it. Harry saw that the title was in runes; he had never learned to read them. As he looked, a tear splashed onto the embossed symbols.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why do you think Dumbledore left you that book, Miss Granger?\rdblquote  asked Scrimgeour.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He \'85 he knew I liked books,\rdblquote  said Hermione in a thick voice, mopping her eyes with her sleeve.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But why that particular book?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t know. He must have thought I\rquote d enjoy it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did you ever discuss codes, or any means of passing secret mes\-sages, with Dumbledore?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I didn\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Hermione, still wiping her eyes on her sleeve. \ldblquote And if the Ministry hasn\rquote t found any hidden codes in this book in thirty-one days, I doubt that I will.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She suppressed a sob. They were wedged together so tightly that Ron had difficulty extracting his arm to put it around Hermione\rquote s shoulders. Scrimgeour turned back to the will.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i To Harry James Potter,\i0\rquote  \rdblquote\i  \i0 he read, and Harry\rquote s insides contracted with a sudden excitement, \ldblquote  \lquote\i I leave the Snitch he caught in his first Quidditch match at Hogwarts, as a reminder of the rewards of perse\-verance and skill.\i0\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As Scrimgeour pulled out the tiny, walnut-sized golden ball, its silver wings fluttered rather feebly, and Harry could not help feeling a definite sense of anticlimax.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why did Dumbledore leave you this Snitch?\rdblquote  asked Scrimgeour.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No idea,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote For the reasons you just read out, I sup\-pose \'85 to remind me what you can get if you \'85 persevere and whatever it was.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You think this a mere symbolic keepsake, then?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I suppose so,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote What else could it be?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m asking the questions,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour, shifting his chair a little closer to the sofa. Dusk was really falling outside now; the mar\-quee beyond the windows towered ghostly white over the hedge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I notice that your birthday cake is in the shape of a Snitch,\rdblquote  Scrimgeour said to Harry. \ldblquote Why is that?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione laughed derisively.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, it can\rquote t be a reference to the fact Harry\rquote s a great Seeker, that\rquote s way too obvious,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote There must be a secret message from Dumbledore hidden in the icing!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t think there\rquote s anything hidden in the icing,\rdblquote  said Scrim\-geour, \ldblquote but a Snitch would be a very good hiding place for a small object. You know why, I\rquote m sure?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry shrugged. Hermione, however, answered: Harry thought that answering questions correctly was such a deeply ingrained habit she could not suppress the urge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because Snitches have flesh memories,\rdblquote  she said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Harry and Ron together; both considered Hermi\-one\rquote s Quidditch knowledge negligible.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Correct,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour. \ldblquote A Snitch is not touched by bare skin before it is released, not even by the maker, who wears gloves. It carries an enchantment by which it can identify the first human to lay hands upon it, in case of a disputed capture. This Snitch\rdblquote  \emdash  he held up the tiny golden ball \emdash  \ldblquote will remember your touch, Potter.\lang3081  \lang1033 It occurs to me that Dumbledore, who had prodigious magical skill, whatever his other faults, might have enchanted this Snitch so that it will open only for you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s heart was beating rather fast. He was sure that Scrim\-geour was right. How could he avoid taking the Snitch with his bare hand in front of the Minister?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You don\rquote t say anything,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour. \ldblquote Perhaps you already know what the Snitch contains?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry, still wondering how he could appear to touch the Snitch without really doing so. If only he knew Legilimency, really knew it, and could read Hermione\rquote s mind; he could practi\-cally hear her brain whirring beside him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Take it,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour quietly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry met the Minister\rquote s yellow eyes and knew he had no option but to obey. He held out his hand, and Scrimgeour leaned forward again and placed the Snitch, slowly and deliberately, into Harry\rquote s palm.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Nothing happened. As Harry\rquote s fingers closed around the Snitch, its tired wings fluttered and were still. Scrimgeour, Ron, and Her\-mione continued to gaze avidly at the now partially concealed ball, as if still hoping it might transform in some way.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That was dramatic,\rdblquote  said Harry coolly. Both Ron and Hermi\-one laughed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s all, then, is it?\rdblquote  asked Hermione, making to prise herself off the sofa.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not quite,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour, who looked bad-tempered now. \ldblquote Dumbledore left you a second bequest, Potter.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What is it?\rdblquote  asked Harry, excitement rekindling.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Scrimgeour did not bother to read from the will this time.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The sword of Godric Gryffindor,\rdblquote  he said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione and Ron both stiffened. Harry looked around for a sign of the ruby-encrusted hilt, but Scrimgeour did not pull the sword from the leather pouch, which in any case looked much too small to contain it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So where is it?\rdblquote  Harry asked suspiciously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Unfortunately,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour, \ldblquote that sword was not Dumble\-dore\rquote s to give away. The sword of Godric Gryffindor is an important historical artifact, and as such, belongs \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It belongs to Harry!\rdblquote  said Hermione hotly. \ldblquote It chose him, he was the one who found it, it came to him out of the Sorting Hat \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote According to reliable historical sources, the sword may present itself to any worthy Gryffindor,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour. \ldblquote That does not make it the exclusive property of Mr. Potter, whatever Dumbledore may have decided.\rdblquote  Scrimgeour scratched his badly shaven cheek, scrutinizing Harry. \ldblquote Why do you think \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  Dumbledore wanted to give me the sword?\rdblquote  said Harry, struggling to keep his temper. \ldblquote Maybe he thought it would look nice on my wall.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This is not a joke, Potter!\rdblquote  growled Scrimgeour. \ldblquote Was it because Dumbledore believed that only the sword of Godric Gryffindor could defeat the Heir of Slytherin? Did he wish to give you that sword, Potter, because he believed, as do many, that you are the one destined to destroy He-Who-Must-Not-Be-Named?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Interesting theory,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Has anyone ever tried sticking a sword in Voldemort? Maybe the Ministry should put some people onto that, instead of wasting their time stripping down Delumina\-tors or covering up breakouts from Azkaban. So is this what you\rquote ve been doing, Minister, shut up in your office, trying to break open\lang3081  \lang1033 a Snitch? People are dying \emdash  I was nearly one of them \emdash  Volde\-mort chased me across three counties, he killed Mad-Eye Moody, but there\rquote s been no word about any of that from the Ministry, has there? And you still expect us to cooperate with you!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You go too far!\rdblquote  shouted Scrimgeour, standing up; Harry jumped to his feet too. Scrimgeour limped toward Harry and jabbed him hard in the chest with the point of his wand: It singed a hole in Harry\rquote s T-shirt like a lit cigarette.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oi!\rdblquote  said Ron, jumping up and raising his own wand, but Harry said,\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No! D\rquote you want to give him an excuse to arrest us?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Remembered you\rquote re not at school, have you?\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour, breathing hard into Harry\rquote s face. \ldblquote Remembered that I am not Dum\-bledore, who forgave your insolence and insubordination? You may wear that scar like a crown, Potter, but it is not up to a seventeen-year-old boy to tell me how to do my job! It\rquote s time you learned some respect!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s time you earned it,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The floor trembled; there was a sound of running footsteps, then the door to the sitting room burst open and Mr. and Mrs. Weasley ran in.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We \emdash  we thought we heard \emdash\rdblquote  began Mr. Weasley, looking thoroughly alarmed at the sight of Harry and the Minister virtu\-ally nose to nose.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  raised voices,\rdblquote  panted Mrs. Weasley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Scrimgeour took a couple of steps back from Harry, glancing at the hole he had made in Harry\rquote s T-shirt. He seemed to regret his loss of temper.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It \emdash  it was nothing,\rdblquote  he growled. \ldblquote I\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 regret your attitude,\rdblquote  he\lang3081  \lang1033 said, looking Harry full in the face once more. \ldblquote You seem to think that the Ministry does not desire what you \emdash  what Dumbledore \emdash  desired. We ought to be working together.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t like your methods, Minister,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Remember?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 For the second time, he raised his right fist and displayed to Scrimgeour the scars that still showed white on the back of it, spelling \i I must not tell lies.\i0  Scrimgeour\rquote s expression hardened. He turned away without another word and limped from the room. Mrs. Weasley hurried after him; Harry heard her stop at the back door. After a minute or so she called, \ldblquote He\rquote s gone!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What did he want?\rdblquote  Mr. Weasley asked, looking around at Harry, Ron, and Hermione as Mrs. Weasley came hurrying back to them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote To give us what Dumbledore left us,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote They\rquote ve only just released the contents of his will.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Outside in the garden, over the dinner tables, the three objects Scrimgeour had given them were passed from hand to hand. Ev\-eryone exclaimed over the Deluminator and \i The Tales of\lang3081  \lang1033 Beedle the Bard\i0  and lamented the fact that Scrimgeour had refused to pass on the sword, but none of them could offer any suggestion as to why Dumbledore would have left Harry an old Snitch. As Mr. Weas\-ley examined the Deluminator for the third or fourth time, Mrs. Weasley said tentatively, \ldblquote Harry, dear, everyone\rquote s awfully hungry, we didn\rquote t like to start without you. \'85 Shall I serve dinner now?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They all ate rather hurriedly and then, after a hasty chorus of \ldblquote Happy Birthday\rdblquote  and much gulping of cake, the party broke up. Hagrid, who was invited to the wedding the following day, but was far too bulky to sleep in the overstretched Burrow, left to set up a tent for himself in a neighboring field.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Meet us upstairs,\rdblquote  Harry whispered to Hermione, while they helped Mrs. Weasley restore the garden to its normal state. \ldblquote After everyone\rquote s gone to bed.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Up in the attic room, Ron examined his Deluminator, and Harry filled Hagrid\rquote s mokeskin purse, not with gold, but with those items he most prized, apparently worthless though some of them were: the Marauder\rquote s Map, the shard of Sirius\rquote s enchanted mirror, and R.A.B.\rquote s locket. He pulled the strings tight and slipped the purse around his neck, then sat holding the old Snitch and watching its wings flutter feebly. At last, Hermione tapped on the door and tiptoed inside.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Muffliato,\i0\rdblquote  she whispered, waving her wand in the direction of the stairs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thought you didn\rquote t approve of that spell?\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Times change,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote Now, show us that Delumi\-nator.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron obliged at once. Holding it up in front of him, he clicked it. The solitary lamp they had lit went out at once.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The thing is,\rdblquote  whispered Hermione through the dark, \ldblquote we could have achieved that with Peruvian Instant Darkness Powder.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a small \i click,\i0  and the ball of light from the lamp flew back to the ceiling and illuminated them all once more.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Still, it\rquote s cool,\rdblquote  said Ron, a little defensively. \ldblquote And from what they said, Dumbledore invented it himself!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I know, but surely he wouldn\rquote t have singled you out in his will just to help us turn out the lights!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote D\rquote you think he knew the Ministry would confiscate his will and examine everything he\rquote d left us?\rdblquote  asked Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Definitely,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote He couldn\rquote t tell us in the will why he was leaving us these things, but that still doesn\rquote t explain \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 why he couldn\rquote t have given us a hint when he was alive?\rdblquote  asked Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, exactly,\rdblquote  said Hermione, now flicking through \i The Tales of\lang3081  \lang1033 Beedle the Bard.\i0  \ldblquote If these things are important enough to pass on right under the nose of the Ministry, you\rquote d think he\rquote d have let us know why \'85 unless he thought it was obvious?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thought wrong, then, didn\rquote t he?\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote I always said he was mental. Brilliant and everything, but cracked. Leaving Harry an old Snitch \emdash  what the hell was that about?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve no idea,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote When Scrimgeour made you take it, Harry, I was so sure that something was going to happen!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, well,\rdblquote  said Harry, his pulse quickening as he raised the Snitch in his fingers. \ldblquote I wasn\rquote t going to try too hard in front of Scrimgeour, was I?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What do you mean?\rdblquote  asked Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Snitch I caught in my first ever Quidditch match?\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Don\rquote t you remember?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione looked simply bemused. Ron, however, gasped, point\-ing frantically from Harry to the Snitch and back again until he found his voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That was the one you nearly swallowed!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Exactly,\rdblquote  said Harry, and with his heart beating fast, he pressed his mouth to the Snitch.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It did not open. Frustration and bitter disappointment welled up inside him: He lowered the golden sphere, but then Hermione cried out.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Writing! There\rquote s writing on it, quick, look!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He nearly dropped the Snitch in surprise and excitement. Her\-mione was quite right. Engraved upon the smooth golden surface,\lang3081  \lang1033 where seconds before there had been nothing, were five words written in the thin, slanting handwriting that Harry recognized as Dumbledore\rquote s:\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc\i I\lang3081  \lang1033 open at the close.\lang3081\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033\i0\par
He had barely read them when the words vanished again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote I open at the close \'85\rquote  What\rquote s that supposed to mean?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione and Ron shook their heads, looking blank.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I open at the close \'85 at the \i close\lang3081\i0  \lang1033\'85 I open at the close \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But no matter how often they repeated the words, with many different inflections, they were unable to wring any more meaning from them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And the sword,\rdblquote  said Ron finally, when they had at last aban\-doned their attempts to divine meaning in the Snitch\rquote s inscription. \ldblquote Why did he want Harry to have the sword?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And why couldn\rquote t he just have told me?\rdblquote  Harry said quietly. \ldblquote It was \i there,\i0  it was right there on the wall of his office during all our talks last year! If he wanted me to have it, why didn\rquote t he just give it to me then?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He felt as though he were sitting in an examination with a ques\-tion he ought to have been able to answer in front of him, his brain slow and unresponsive. Was there something he had missed in the long talks with Dumbledore last year? Ought he to know what it all meant? Had Dumbledore expected him to understand?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And as for this book,\rdblquote  said Hermione, \ldblquote\i The Tales of\lang3081  \lang1033 Beedle the Bard\lang3081\i0  \lang1033\'85\i  \i0 I\rquote ve never even heard of them!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote ve never heard of \i The Tales of\lang3081  \lang1033 Beedle the Bard\i0 ?\rdblquote  said Ron incredulously. \ldblquote You\rquote re kidding, right?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I\rquote m not!\rdblquote  said Hermione in surprise. \ldblquote Do you know them, then?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, of course I do!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked up, diverted. The circumstance of Ron having read a book that Hermione had not was unprecedented. Ron, however, looked bemused by their surprise.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh come on! All the old kids\rquote  stories are supposed to be Beedle\rquote s, aren\rquote t they? \lquote The Fountain of Fair Fortune\rquote  \'85 \lquote The Wizard and the Hopping Pot\rquote\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 \lquote Babbitty Rabbitty and her Cackling Stump\rquote\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Excuse me?\rdblquote  said Hermione, giggling. \ldblquote What was that last one?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Come off it!\rdblquote  said Ron, looking in disbelief from Harry to Her\-mione. \ldblquote You must\rquote ve heard of Babbitty Rabbitty \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ron, you know full well Harry and I were brought up by Muggles!\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote We didn\rquote t hear stories like that when we were little, we heard \lquote Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs\rquote  and \lquote Cinderella\rquote  \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s that, an illness?\rdblquote  asked Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So these are children\rquote s stories?\rdblquote  asked Hermione, bending again over the runes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Ron uncertainly, \ldblquote I mean, that\rquote s just what you hear, you know, that all these old stories came from Beedle. I dunno what they\rquote re like in the original versions.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But I wonder why Dumbledore thought I should read them?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Something creaked downstairs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Probably just Charlie, now Mum\rquote s asleep, sneaking off to regrow his hair,\rdblquote  said Ron nervously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All the same, we should get to bed,\rdblquote  whispered Hermione. \ldblquote It wouldn\rquote t do to oversleep tomorrow.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  agreed Ron. \ldblquote A brutal triple murder by the bridegroom\rquote s mother might put a bit of a damper on the wedding. I\rquote ll get the lights.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And he clicked the Deluminator once more as Hermione left the room.\lang3081\par
