\lang1033\ldblquote Mr. Doge, I\rquote m Harry Potter.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Doge gasped.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My dear boy! Arthur told me you were here, disguised. \'85 I am so glad, so honored!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 In a flutter of nervous pleasure Doge poured Harry a goblet of champagne.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I thought of writing to you,\rdblquote  he whispered, \ldblquote after Dumbledore \'85 the shock \'85 and for you, I am sure \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Doge\rquote s tiny eyes filled with sudden tears.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I saw the obituary you wrote for the \i Daily Prophet,\i0\rquote\rquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I didn\rquote t realize you knew Professor Dumbledore so well.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote As well as anyone,\rdblquote  said Doge, dabbing his eyes with a napkin. \ldblquote Certainly I knew him longest, if you don\rquote t count Aberforth \emdash  and somehow, people never \i do\i0  seem to count Aberforth.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Speaking of the \i Daily Prophet\lang3081\i0  \lang1033\'85 I don\rquote t know whether you saw, Mr. Doge \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, please call me Elphias, dear boy.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Elphias, I don\rquote t know whether you saw the interview Rita Skeeter gave about Dumbledore?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Doge\rquote s face flooded with angry color.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yes, Harry, I saw it. That woman, or vulture might be a more accurate term, positively pestered me to talk to her. I am ashamed to say that I became rather rude, called her an interfering trout, which resulted, as you may have seen, in aspersions cast upon my sanity.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, in that interview,\rdblquote  Harry went on, \ldblquote Rita Skeeter hinted that Professor Dumbledore was involved in the Dark Arts when he was young.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t believe a word of it!\rdblquote  said Doge at once. \ldblquote Not a word, Harry! Let nothing tarnish your memories of Albus Dumbledore!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked into Doge\rquote s earnest, pained face and felt, not reas\-sured, but frustrated. Did Doge really think it was that easy, that\lang3081  \lang1033 Harry could simply \i choose\i0  not to believe? Didn\rquote t Doge understand Harry\rquote s need to be sure, to know \i everything\i0 ?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Perhaps Doge suspected Harry\rquote s feelings, for he looked concerned and hurried on, \ldblquote Harry, Rita Skeeter is a dreadful \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But he was interrupted by a shrill cackle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Rita Skeeter? Oh, I love her, always read her!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry and Doge looked up to see Auntie Muriel standing there, the plumes dancing on her hat, a goblet of champagne in her hand. \ldblquote She\rquote s written a book about Dumbledore, you know!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hello, Muriel,\rdblquote  said Doge. \ldblquote Yes, we were just discussing \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You there! Give me your chair, I\rquote m a hundred and seven!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Another redheaded Weasley cousin jumped off his seat, look\-ing alarmed, and Auntie Muriel swung it around with surprising strength and plopped herself down upon it between Doge and Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hello again, Barry, or whatever your name is,\rdblquote  she said to Harry. \ldblquote Now, what were you saying about Rita Skeeter, Elphias? You know she\rquote s written a biography of Dumbledore? I can\rquote t wait to read it, I must remember to place an order at Flourish and Blotts!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Doge looked stiff and solemn at this, but Auntie Muriel drained her goblet and clicked her bony fingers at a passing waiter for a re\-placement. She took another large gulp of champagne, belched, and then said, \ldblquote There\rquote s no need to look like a pair of stuffed frogs! Before he became so respected and respectable and all that tosh, there were some mighty funny rumors about Albus!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ill-informed sniping,\rdblquote  said Doge, turning radish-colored again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You would say that, Elphias,\rdblquote  cackled Auntie Muriel. \ldblquote I noticed how you skated over the sticky patches in that obituary of yours!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry you think so,\rdblquote  said Doge, more coldly still. \ldblquote I assure you I was writing from the heart.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, we all know you worshipped Dumbledore; I daresay you\rquote ll still think he was a saint even if it does turn out that he did away with his Squib sister!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Muriel\i0 !\rdblquote  exclaimed Doge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A chill that had nothing to do with the iced champagne was stealing through Harry\rquote s chest.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What do you mean?\rdblquote  he asked Muriel. \ldblquote Who said his sister was a Squib? I thought she was ill?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thought wrong, then, didn\rquote t you, Barry!\rdblquote  said Auntie Muriel, looking delighted at the effect she had produced. \ldblquote Anyway, how could you expect to know anything about it? It all happened years and years before you were even thought of, my dear, and the truth is that those of us who were alive then never knew what really hap\-pened. That\rquote s why I can\rquote t wait to find out what Skeeter\rquote s unearthed! Dumbledore kept that sister of his quiet for a long time!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Untrue!\rdblquote  wheezed Doge. \ldblquote Absolutely untrue!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He never told me his sister was a Squib,\rdblquote  said Harry, without thinking, still cold inside.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And why on earth would he tell you?\rdblquote  screeched Muriel, swaying a little in her seat as she attempted to focus upon Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The reason Albus never spoke about Ariana,\rdblquote  began Elphias in a voice stiff with emotion, \ldblquote is, I should have thought, quite clear. He was so devastated by her death \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why did nobody ever see her, Elphias?\rdblquote  squawked Muriel. \ldblquote Why did half of us never even know she existed, until they car\-ried the coffin out of the house and held a funeral for her? Where was saintly Albus while Ariana was locked in the cellar? Off being\lang3081  \lang1033 brilliant at Hogwarts, and never mind what was going on in his own house!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What d\rquote you mean, locked in the cellar?\rdblquote  asked Harry. \ldblquote What is this?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Doge looked wretched. Auntie Muriel cackled again and an\-swered Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore\rquote s mother was a terrifying woman, simply terrifying. Muggle-born, though I heard she pretended otherwise \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She never pretended anything of the sort! Kendra was a fine woman,\rdblquote  whispered Doge miserably, but Auntie Muriel ignored him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  proud and very domineering, the sort of witch who would have been mortified to produce a Squib \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ariana was not a Squib!\rdblquote  wheezed Doge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So you say, Elphias, but explain, then, why she never attended Hogwarts!\rdblquote  said Auntie Muriel. She turned back to Harry. \ldblquote In our day, Squibs were often hushed up, though to take it to the extreme of actually imprisoning a little girl in the house and pretending she didn\rquote t exist \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I tell you, that\rquote s not what happened!\rdblquote  said Doge, but Auntie Muriel steamrollered on, still addressing Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Squibs were usually shipped off to Muggle schools and encour\-aged to integrate into the Muggle community\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 much kinder than trying to find them a place in the Wizarding world, where they must always be second class; but naturally Kendra Dumbledore wouldn\rquote t have dreamed of letting her daughter go to a Muggle school \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ariana was delicate!\rdblquote  said Doge desperately. \ldblquote Her health was always too poor to permit her \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  to permit her to leave the house?\rdblquote  cackled Muriel. \ldblquote And yet\lang3081  \lang1033 she was never taken to St. Mungo\rquote s and no Healer was ever sum\-moned to see her!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Really, Muriel, how you can possibly know whether \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote For your information, Elphias, my cousin Lancelot was a Healer at St. Mungo\rquote s at the time, and he told my family in strictest con\-fidence that Ariana had never been seen there. All most suspicious, Lancelot thought!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Doge looked to be on the verge of tears. Auntie Muriel, who seemed to be enjoying herself hugely, snapped her fingers for more champagne. Numbly Harry thought of how the Dursleys had once shut him up, locked him away, kept him out of sight, all for the crime of being a wizard. Had Dumbledore\rquote s sister suffered the same fate in reverse: imprisoned for her lack of magic? And had Dumbledore truly left her to her fate while he went off to Hogwarts, to prove himself brilliant and talented?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now, if Kendra hadn\rquote t died first,\rdblquote  Muriel resumed, \ldblquote I\rquote d have said that it was she who finished off Ariana \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How can you, Muriel?\rdblquote  groaned Doge. \ldblquote A mother kill her own daughter? Think what you are saying!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If the mother in question was capable of imprisoning her daugh\-ter for years on end, why not?\rdblquote  shrugged Auntie Muriel. \ldblquote But as I say, it doesn\rquote t fit, because Kendra died before Ariana \emdash  of what, nobody ever seemed sure \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, no doubt Ariana murdered her,\rdblquote  said Doge with a brave attempt at scorn. \ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, Ariana might have made a desperate bid for freedom and killed Kendra in the struggle,\rdblquote  said Auntie Muriel thoughtfully. \ldblquote Shake your head all you like, Elphias! You were at Ariana\rquote s funeral, were you not?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes I was,\rdblquote  said Doge, through trembling lips. \ldblquote And a more desper\-ately sad occasion I cannot remember. Albus was heartbroken \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote His heart wasn\rquote t the only thing. Didn\rquote t Aberforth break Albus\rquote s nose halfway through the service?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 If Doge had looked horrified before this, it was nothing to how he looked now. Muriel might have stabbed him. She cackled loudly and took another swig of champagne, which dribbled down her chin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How do you \emdash  ?\rdblquote  croaked Doge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My mother was friendly with old Bathilda Bagshot,\rdblquote  said Auntie Muriel happily. \ldblquote Bathilda described the whole thing to Mother while I was listening at the door. A coffin-side brawl! The way Bathilda told it, Aberforth shouted that it was all Albus\rquote s fault that Ariana was dead and then punched him in the face. According to Bathilda, Albus did not even defend himself, and that\rquote s odd enough in itself, Albus could have destroyed Aberforth in a duel with both hands tied behind his back.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Muriel swigged yet more champagne. The recitation of these old scandals seemed to elate her as much as they horrified Doge. Harry did not know what to think, what to believe: He wanted the truth, and yet all Doge did was sit there and bleat feebly that Ariana had been ill. Harry could hardly believe that Dumbledore would not have intervened if such cruelty was happening inside his own house, and yet there was undoubtedly something odd about the story.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And I\rquote ll tell you something else,\rdblquote  Muriel said, hiccuping slightly as she lowered her goblet. \ldblquote I think Bathilda has spilled the beans to Rita Skeeter. All those hints in Skeeter\rquote s interview about an impor\-tant source close to the Dumbledores \emdash  goodness knows she was there all through the Ariana business, and it would fit!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bathilda would never talk to Rita Skeeter!\rdblquote  whispered Doge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bathilda Bagshot?\rdblquote  Harry said. \ldblquote The author of \i A History of Magic\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The name was printed on the front of one of Harry\rquote s text\-books, though admittedly not one of the ones he had read most attentively.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Doge, clutching at Harry\rquote s question like a drown\-ing man at a life belt. \ldblquote A most gifted magical historian and an old friend of Albus\rquote s.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Quite gaga these days, I\rquote ve heard,\rdblquote  said Auntie Muriel cheer\-fully.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If that is so, it is even more dishonorable for Skeeter to have taken advantage of her,\rdblquote  said Doge, \ldblquote and no reliance can be placed on anything Bathilda may have said!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, there are ways of bringing back memories, and I\rquote m sure Rita Skeeter knows them all,\rdblquote  said Auntie Muriel. \ldblquote But even if Bathilda\rquote s completely cuckoo, I\rquote m sure she\rquote d still have old photographs, maybe even letters. She knew the Dumbledores for years. \'85 Well worth a trip to Godric\rquote s Hollow, I\rquote d have thought.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry, who had been taking a sip of butterbeer, choked. Doge banged him on the back as Harry coughed, looking at Auntie Mu\-riel through streaming eyes. Once he had control of his voice again, he asked, \ldblquote Bathilda Bagshot lives in Godric\rquote s Hollow?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yes, she\rquote s been there forever! The Dumbledores moved there after Percival was imprisoned, and she was their neighbor.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Dumbledores lived in Godric\rquote s Hollow?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, Barry, that\rquote s what I just said,\rdblquote  said Auntie Muriel testily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt drained, empty. Never once, in six years, had Dum\-bledore told Harry that they had both lived and lost loved ones in Godric\rquote s Hollow. Why? Were Lily and James buried close to\lang3081  \lang1033 Dumbledore\rquote s mother and sister? Had Dumbledore visited their graves, perhaps walked past Lily\rquote s and James\rquote s to do so? And he had never once told Harry \'85 never bothered to say \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And why it was so important, Harry could not explain even to himself, yet he felt it had been tantamount to a lie not to tell him that they had this place and these experiences in common. He stared ahead of him, barely noticing what was going on around him, and did not realize that Hermione had appeared out of the crowd until she drew up a chair beside him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I simply can\rquote t dance anymore,\rdblquote  she panted, slipping off one of her shoes and rubbing the sole of her foot. \ldblquote Ron\rquote s gone looking to find more butterbeers. It\rquote s a bit odd, I\rquote ve just seen Viktor storming away from Luna\rquote s father, it looked like they\rquote d been arguing \emdash\rdblquote  She dropped her voice, staring at him. \ldblquote Harry, are you okay?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry did not know where to begin, but it did not matter. At that moment, something large and silver came falling through the canopy over the dance floor. Graceful and gleaming, the lynx landed lightly in the middle of the astonished dancers. Heads turned, as those nearest it froze absurdly in mid-dance. Then the Patronus\rquote s mouth opened wide and it spoke in the loud, deep, slow voice of Kingsley Shacklebolt.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i The Ministry has fallen. Scrimgeour is dead. They are coming.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\par
