If Kreacher could escape a lake full of Inferi, Harry was confident that the capture of Mundungus would take a few hours at most, and he prowled the house all morning in a state of high anticipation. However, Kreacher did not return that morning or even that after\-noon. By nightfall, Harry felt discouraged and anxious, and a supper composed largely of moldy bread, upon which Hermione had tried a variety of unsuccessful Transfigurations, did nothing to help.\par
Kreacher did not return the following day, nor the day after that. However, two cloaked men had appeared in the square outside num\-ber twelve, and they remained there into the night, gazing in the direction of the house that they could not see.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Death Eaters, for sure,\rdblquote  said Ron, as he, Harry, and Hermione watched from the drawing room windows. \ldblquote Reckon they know we\rquote re in here?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t think so,\rdblquote  said Hermione, though she looked frightened, \ldblquote or they\rquote d have sent Snape in after us, wouldn\rquote t they?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote D\rquote you reckon he\rquote s been in here and had his tongue tied by Moody\rquote s curse?\rdblquote  asked Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Hermione, \ldblquote otherwise he\rquote d have been able to tell that lot how to get in, wouldn\rquote t he? But they\rquote re probably watching to see whether we turn up. They know that Harry owns the house, after all.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How do they \emdash  ?\rdblquote  began Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wizarding wills are examined by the Ministry, remember? They\rquote ll know Sirius left you the place.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The presence of the Death Eaters outside increased the ominous mood inside number twelve. They had not heard a word from any\-one beyond Grimmauld Place since Mr. Weasley\rquote s Patronus, and the strain was starting to tell. Restless and irritable, Ron had developed an annoying habit of playing with the Deluminator in his pocket: This particularly infuriated Hermione, who was whiling away the wait for Kreacher by studying \i The Tales of\lang3081  \lang1033 Beedle the Bard\i0  and did not appreciate the way the lights kept flashing on and off.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Will you stop it!\rdblquote  she cried on the third evening of Kreacher\rquote s absence, as all light was sucked from the drawing room yet again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sorry, sorry!\rdblquote  said Ron, clicking the Deluminator and restoring the lights. \ldblquote I don\rquote t know I\rquote m doing it!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, can\rquote t you find something useful to occupy yourself?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What, like reading kids\rquote  stories?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore left me this book, Ron \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  and he left me the Deluminator, maybe I\rquote m supposed to use it!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Unable to stand the bickering, Harry slipped out of the room unnoticed by either of them. He headed downstairs toward the kitchen, which he kept visiting because he was sure that was where\lang3081  \lang1033 Kreacher was most likely to reappear. Halfway down the flight of stairs into the hall, however, he heard a tap on the front door, then metallic clicks and the grinding of the chain.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Every nerve in his body seemed to tauten: He pulled out his wand, moved into the shadows beside the decapitated elf heads, and waited. The door opened: He saw a glimpse of the lamplit square outside, and a cloaked figure edged into the hall and closed the door behind it. The intruder took a step forward, and Moody\rquote s voice asked, \ldblquote\i Severus Snape\i0 ?\rdblquote  Then the dust figure rose from the end of the hall and rushed him, raising its dead hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It was not I who killed you, Albus,\rdblquote  said a quiet voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The jinx broke: The dust-figure exploded again, and it was im\-possible to make out the newcomer through the dense gray cloud it left behind.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry pointed his wand into the middle of it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t move!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He had forgotten the portrait of Mrs. Black: At the sound of his yell, the curtains hiding her flew open and she began to scream, \ldblquote\i Mudbloods and filth dishonoring my house\i0  \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron and Hermione came crashing down the stairs behind Harry, wands pointing, like his, at the unknown man now standing with his arms raised in the hall below.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hold your fire, it\rquote s me, Remus!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, thank goodness,\rdblquote  said Hermione weakly, pointing her wand at Mrs. Black instead; with a bang, the curtains swished shut again and silence fell. Ron too lowered his wand, but Harry did not.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Show yourself!\rdblquote  he called back.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin moved forward into the lamplight, hands still held high in a gesture of surrender.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am Remus John Lupin, werewolf, sometimes known as Moony, one of the four creators of the Marauder\rquote s Map, married to Nympha\-dora, usually known as Tonks, and I taught you how to produce a Patronus, Harry, which takes the form of a stag.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, all right,\rdblquote  said Harry, lowering his wand, \ldblquote but I had to check, didn\rquote t I?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Speaking as your ex-Defense Against the Dark Arts teacher, I quite agree that you had to check. Ron, Hermione, you shouldn\rquote t be quite so quick to lower your defenses.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They ran down the stairs toward him. Wrapped in a thick black traveling cloak, he looked exhausted, but pleased to see them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No sign of Severus, then?\rdblquote  he asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote What\rquote s going on? Is everyone okay?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Lupin, \ldblquote but we\rquote re all being watched. There are a couple of Death Eaters in the square outside \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We know \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I had to Apparate very precisely onto the top step outside the front door to be sure that they would not see me. They can\rquote t know you\rquote re in here or I\rquote m sure they\rquote d have more people out there; they\rquote re staking out everywhere that\rquote s got any connection with you, Harry. Let\rquote s go downstairs, there\rquote s a lot to tell you, and I want to know what happened after you left the Burrow.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They descended into the kitchen, where Hermione pointed her wand at the grate. A fire sprang up instantly: It gave the illusion of coziness to the stark stone walls and glistened off the long wooden table. Lupin pulled a few butterbeers from beneath his traveling cloak and they sat down.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote d have been here three days ago but I needed to shake off the\lang3081  \lang1033 Death Eater tailing me,\rdblquote  said Lupin. \ldblquote So, you came straight here after the wedding?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote only after we ran into a couple of Death Eaters in a caf\'e9 on Tottenham Court Road.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin slopped most of his butterbeer down his front.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i What\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They explained what had happened; when they had finished, Lupin looked aghast.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But how did they find you so quickly? It\rquote s impossible to track anyone who Apparates, unless you grab hold of them as they disappear!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And it doesn\rquote t seem likely they were just strolling down Totten\-ham Court Road at the time, does it?\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We wondered,\rdblquote  said Hermione tentatively, \ldblquote whether Harry could still have the Trace on him?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Impossible,\rdblquote  said Lupin. Ron looked smug, and Harry felt hugely relieved. \ldblquote Apart from anything else, they\rquote d know for sure Harry was here if he still had the Trace on him, wouldn\rquote t they? But I can\rquote t see how they could have tracked you to Tottenham Court Road, that\rquote s worrying, really worrying.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He looked disturbed, but as far as Harry was concerned, that question could wait.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Tell us what happened after we left, we haven\rquote t heard a thing since Ron\rquote s dad told us the family were safe.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, Kingsley saved us,\rdblquote  said Lupin. \ldblquote Thanks to his warning most of the wedding guests were able to Disapparate before they arrived.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Were they Death Eaters or Ministry people?\rdblquote  interjected Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A mixture; but to all intents and purposes they\rquote re the same thing now,\rdblquote  said Lupin. \ldblquote There were about a dozen of them, but they didn\rquote t know you were there, Harry. Arthur heard a rumor that they tried to torture your whereabouts out of Scrimgeour before they killed him; if it\rquote s true, he didn\rquote t give you away.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked at Ron and Hermione; their expressions reflected the mingled shock and gratitude he felt. He had never liked Scrim\-geour much, but if what Lupin said was true, the man\rquote s final act had been to try to protect Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Death Eaters searched the Burrow from top to bottom,\rdblquote  Lu\-pin went on. \ldblquote They found the ghoul, but didn\rquote t want to get too close \emdash  and then they interrogated those of us who remained for hours. They were trying to get information on you, Harry, but of course nobody apart from the Order knew that you had been there.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote At the same time that they were smashing up the wedding, more Death Eaters were forcing their way into every Order-connected house in the country. No deaths,\rdblquote  he added quickly, forestalling the question, \ldblquote but they were rough. They burned down Dedalus Diggle\rquote s house, but as you know he wasn\rquote t there, and they used the Cruciatus Curse on Tonks\rquote s family. Again, trying to find out where you went after you visited them. They\rquote re all right \emdash  shaken, obvi\-ously, but otherwise okay.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Death Eaters got through all those protective charms?\rdblquote  Harry asked, remembering how effective these had been on the night he had crashed in Tonks\rquote s parents\rquote  garden.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What you\rquote ve got to realize, Harry, is that the Death Eaters have got the full might of the Ministry on their side now,\rdblquote  said Lupin. \ldblquote They\rquote ve got the power to perform brutal spells without fear of\lang3081  \lang1033 identification or arrest. They managed to penetrate every defensive spell we\rquote d cast against them, and once inside, they were completely open about why they\rquote d come.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And are they bothering to give an excuse for torturing Harry\rquote s whereabouts out of people?\rdblquote  asked Hermione, an edge to her voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Lupin. He hesitated, then pulled out a folded copy of the \i Daily Prophet.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Here,\rdblquote  he said, pushing it across the table to Harry, \ldblquote you\rquote ll know sooner or later anyway. That\rquote s their pretext for going after you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry smoothed out the paper. A huge photograph of his own face filled the front page. He read the headline over it:\par
\par
