As August wore on, the square of unkempt grass in the middle of Grimmauld Place shriveled in the sun until it was brittle and brown. The inhabitants of number twelve were never seen by anybody in the surrounding houses, and nor was number twelve itself. The Muggles who lived in Grimmauld Place had long since accepted the amusing mistake in the numbering that had caused number eleven to sit beside number thirteen.\par
And yet the square was now attracting a trickle of visitors who seemed to find the anomaly most intriguing. Barely a day passed without one or two people arriving in Grimmauld Place with no other purpose, or so it seemed, than to lean against the railings facing numbers eleven and thirteen, watching the join between the two houses. The lurkers were never the same two days running, although they all seemed to share a dislike for normal clothing. Most of the Londoners who passed them were used to eccentric dressers and took little notice, though occasionally one of them\lang3081  \lang1033 might glance back, wondering why anyone would wear such long cloaks in this heat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The watchers seemed to be gleaning little satisfaction from their vigil. Occasionally one of them started forward excitedly, as if they had seen something interesting at last, only to fall back looking disappointed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 On the first day of September there were more people lurking in the square than ever before. Half\lang3081  \lang1033 a dozen men in long cloaks stood silent and watchful, gazing as ever at houses eleven and thirteen, but the thing for which they were waiting still appeared elusive. As evening drew in, bringing with it an unexpected gust of chilly rain for the first time in weeks, there occurred one of those inexplicable moments when they appeared to have seen something interesting. The man with the twisted face pointed and his closest companion, a podgy, pallid man, started forward, but a moment later they had relaxed into their previous state of inactivity, looking frustrated and disappointed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Meanwhile, inside number twelve, Harry had just entered the hall. He had nearly lost his balance as he Apparated onto the top step just outside the front door, and thought that the Death Eaters might have caught a glimpse of his momentarily exposed elbow. Shutting the front door carefully behind him, he pulled off the Invisibility Cloak, draped it over his arm, and hurried along the gloomy hallway toward the door that led to the basement, a stolen copy of the \i Daily Prophet\i0  clutched in his hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The usual low whisper of \ldblquote\i Severus Snape\i0 ?\rdblquote  greeted him, the chill wind swept him, and his tongue rolled up for a moment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I didn\rquote t kill you,\rdblquote  he said, once it had unrolled, then held his breath as the dusty jinx-figure exploded. He waited until he was\lang3081  \lang1033 halfway down the stairs to the kitchen, out of earshot of Mrs. Black and clear of the dust cloud, before calling, \ldblquote I\rquote ve got news, and you won\rquote t like it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The kitchen was almost unrecognizable. Every surface now shone: Copper pots and pans had been burnished to a rosy glow; the wooden tabletop gleamed; the goblets and plates already laid for dinner glinted in the light from a merrily blazing fire, on which a cauldron was simmering. Nothing in the room, however, was more dramatically different than the house-elf who now came hurrying toward Harry, dressed in a snowy-white towel, his ear hair as clean and fluffy as cotton wool, Regulus\rquote s locket bouncing on his thin chest.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Shoes off, if you please, Master Harry, and hands washed be\-fore dinner,\rdblquote  croaked Kreacher, seizing the Invisibility Cloak and slouching off to hang it on a hook on the wall, beside a number of old-fashioned robes that had been freshly laundered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s happened?\rdblquote  Ron asked apprehensively. He and Hermi\-one had been poring over a sheaf of scribbled notes and hand-drawn maps that littered the end of the long kitchen table, but now they watched Harry as he strode toward them and threw down the news\-paper on top of their scattered parchment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A large picture of a familiar, hook-nosed, black-haired man stared up at them all, beneath a headline that read:\par
\par
\pard\qc SEVERUS SNAPE CONFIRMED AS HOGWARTS HEADMASTER\lang3081\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033\par
\ldblquote No!\rdblquote  said Ron and Hermione loudly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione was quickest; she snatched up the newspaper and be\-gan to read the accompanying story out loud.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i Severus Snape, long-standing Potions master at Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry, was today appointed headmaster in the most important of several staffing changes at the ancient school. Following the resignation of the previous Muggle Studies teacher, Alecto Carrow will take over the post while her brother, Amycus, fills the position of Defense Against the Dark Arts professor.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i I welcome the opportunity to uphold our finest Wizarding tradi\-tions and values\i0  \emdash\rquote  Like committing murder and cutting off peo\-ple\rquote s ears, I suppose! Snape, headmaster! Snape in Dumbledore\rquote s study \emdash  Merlin\rquote s pants!\rdblquote  she shrieked, making both Harry and Ron jump. She leapt up from the table and hurtled from the room, shouting as she went, \ldblquote I\rquote ll be back in a minute!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote Merlin\rquote s pants\rquote ?\rdblquote  repeated Ron, looking amused. \ldblquote She must be upset.\rdblquote  He pulled the newspaper toward him and perused the article about Snape.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The other teachers won\rquote t stand for this. McGonagall and Flit\-wick and Sprout all know the truth, they know how Dumbledore died. They won\rquote t accept Snape as headmaster. And who are these Carrows?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Death Eaters,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote There are pictures of them inside. They were at the top of the tower when Snape killed Dumbledore, so it\rquote s all friends together. And,\rdblquote  Harry went on bitterly, drawing up a chair, \ldblquote I can\rquote t see that the other teachers have got any choice but to stay. If the Ministry and Voldemort are behind Snape it\rquote ll be a choice between staying and teaching, or a nice few years in Az\-kaban \emdash  and that\rquote s if they\rquote re lucky. I reckon they\rquote ll stay to try and protect the students.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Kreacher came bustling to the table with a large tureen in his\lang3081  \lang1033 hands, and ladled out soup into pristine bowls, whistling between his teeth as he did so.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thanks, Kreacher,\rdblquote  said Harry, flipping over the \i Prophet\i0  so as not to have to look at Snape\rquote s face. \ldblquote Well, at least we know exactly where Snape is now.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He began to spoon soup into his mouth. The quality of Kreacher\rquote s cooking had improved dramatically ever since he had been given Regulus\rquote s locket: Today\rquote s French onion was as good as Harry had ever tasted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There are still a load of Death Eaters watching the house,\rdblquote  he told Ron as he ate, \ldblquote more than usual. It\rquote s like they\rquote re hoping we\rquote ll march out carrying our school trunks and head off for the Hog\-warts Express.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron glanced at his watch.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve been thinking about that all day. It left nearly six hours ago. Weird, not being on it, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 In his mind\rquote s eye Harry seemed to see the scarlet steam engine as he and Ron had once followed it by air, shimmering between fields and hills, a rippling scarlet caterpillar. He was sure Ginny, Neville, and Luna were sitting together at this moment, perhaps wonder\-ing where he, Ron, and Hermione were, or debating how best to undermine Snape\rquote s new regime.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They nearly saw me coming back in just now,\rdblquote  Harry said. \ldblquote I landed badly on the top step, and the Cloak slipped.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I do that every time. Oh, here she is,\rdblquote  Ron added, craning around in his seat to watch Hermione reentering the kitchen. \ldblquote And what in the name of Merlin\rquote s most baggy Y Fronts was that about?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I remembered this,\rdblquote  Hermione panted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She was carrying a large, framed picture, which she now lowered to the floor before seizing her small, beaded bag from the kitchen sideboard. Opening it, she proceeded to force the painting inside, and despite the fact that it was patently too large to fit inside the tiny bag, within a few seconds it had vanished, like so much else, into the bag\rquote s capacious depths.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Phineas Nigellus,\rdblquote  Hermione explained as she threw the bag onto the kitchen table with the usual sonorous, clanking crash.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sorry?\rdblquote  said Ron, but Harry understood. The painted image of Phineas Nigellus Black was able to flit between his portrait in Grimmauld Place and the one that hung in the headmaster\rquote s office at Hogwarts: the circular tower-top room where Snape was no doubt sitting right now, in triumphant possession of Dumbledore\rquote s collec\-tion of delicate, silver magical instruments, the stone Pensieve, the Sorting Hat and, unless it had been moved elsewhere, the sword of Gryffindor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Snape could send Phineas Nigellus to look inside this house for him,\rdblquote  Hermione explained to Ron as she resumed her seat. \ldblquote But let him try it now, all Phineas Nigellus will be able to see is the inside of my handbag.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good thinking!\rdblquote  said Ron, looking impressed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank you,\rdblquote  smiled Hermione, pulling her soup toward her. \ldblquote So, Harry, what else happened today?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nothing,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Watched the Ministry entrance for seven hours. No sign of her. Saw your dad, though, Ron. He looks fine.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron nodded his appreciation of this news. They had agreed that it was far too dangerous to try and communicate with Mr. Weasley while he walked in and out of the Ministry, because he was always surrounded by other Ministry workers. It was, however, reassuring\lang3081  \lang1033 to catch these glimpses of him, even if he did look very strained and anxious.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dad always told us most Ministry people use the Floo Network to get to work,\rdblquote  Ron said. \ldblquote That\rquote s why we haven\rquote t seen Umbridge, she\rquote d never walk, she\rquote d think she\rquote s too important.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And what about that funny old witch and that little wizard in the navy robes?\rdblquote  Hermione asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yeah, the bloke from Magical Maintenance,\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How do you know he works for Magical Maintenance?\rdblquote  Hermi\-one asked, her soupspoon suspended in midair.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dad said everyone from Magical Maintenance wears navy blue robes.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But you never told us that!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione dropped her spoon and pulled toward her the sheaf of notes and maps that she and Ron had been examining when Harry had entered the kitchen.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There\rquote s nothing in here about navy blue robes, nothing!\rdblquote  she said, flipping feverishly through the pages.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, does it really matter?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ron, it \i all\i0  matters! If we\rquote re going to get into the Ministry and not give ourselves away when they\rquote re \i bound\i0  to be on the lookout for intruders, every little detail matters! We\rquote ve been over and over this, I mean, what\rquote s the point of all these reconnaissance trips if you aren\rquote t even bothering to tell us \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Blimey, Hermione, I forget one little thing \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You do realize, don\rquote t you, that there\rquote s probably no more dan\-gerous place in the whole world for us to be right now than the Ministry of\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think we should do it tomorrow,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione stopped dead, her jaw hanging; Ron choked a little over his soup.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Tomorrow?\rdblquote  repeated Hermione. \ldblquote You aren\rquote t serious, Harry?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I don\rquote t think we\rquote re going to be much better prepared than we are now even if we skulk around the Ministry entrance for another month. The longer we put it off, the farther away that locket could be. There\rquote s already a good chance Umbridge has chucked it away; the thing doesn\rquote t open.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Unless,\rdblquote  said Ron, \ldblquote she\rquote s found a way of opening it and she\rquote s now possessed.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wouldn\rquote t make any difference to her, she was so evil in the first place,\rdblquote  Harry shrugged.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione was biting her lip, deep in thought.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We know everything important,\rdblquote  Harry went on, addressing Hermione. \ldblquote We know they\rquote ve stopped Apparition in and out of the Ministry. We know only the most senior Ministry members are al\-lowed to connect their homes to the Floo Network now, because Ron heard those two Unspeakables complaining about it. And we know roughly where Umbridge\rquote s office is, because of what you heard that bearded bloke saying to his mate \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i I\rquote ll be up on level one, Dolores wants to see me,\i0\rquote  \rdblquote\i  \i0 Hermione re\-cited immediately.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Exactly,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote And we know you get in using those funny coins, or tokens, or whatever they are, because I saw that witch bor\-rowing one from her friend \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But we haven\rquote t got any!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If the plan works, we will have,\rdblquote  Harry continued calmly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t know, Harry, I don\rquote t know. \'85 There are an awful lot of things that could go wrong, so much relies on chance. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote ll be true even if we spend another three months prepar\-ing,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote It\rquote s time to act.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He could tell from Ron\rquote s and Hermione\rquote s faces that they were scared; he was not particularly confident himself, and yet he was sure the time had come to put their plan into operation.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They had spent the previous four weeks taking it in turns to don the Invisibility Cloak and spy on the official entrance to the Minis\-try, which Ron, thanks to Mr. Weasley, had known since childhood. They had tailed Ministry workers on their way in, eavesdropped on their conversations, and learned by careful observation which of them could be relied upon to appear, alone, at the same time every day. Occasionally there had been a chance to sneak a \i Daily Prophet\i0  out of somebody\rquote s briefcase. Slowly they had built up the sketchy maps and notes now stacked in front of Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All right,\rdblquote  said Ron slowly, \ldblquote let\rquote s say we go for it tomorrow. \'85 I think it should just be me and Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, don\rquote t start that again!\rdblquote  sighed Hermione. \ldblquote I thought we\rquote d settled this.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s one thing hanging around the entrances under the Cloak, but this is different, Hermione.\rdblquote  Ron jabbed a finger at a copy of the \i Daily Prophet\i0  dated ten days previously. \ldblquote You\rquote re on the list of Muggle-borns who didn\rquote t present themselves for interrogation!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And you\rquote re supposed to be dying of spattergroit at the Burrow! If anyone shouldn\rquote t go, it\rquote s Harry, he\rquote s got a ten-thousand-Galleon price on his head \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fine, I\rquote ll stay here,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Let me know if you ever defeat Voldemort, won\rquote t you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As Ron and Hermione laughed, pain shot through the scar on Harry\rquote s forehead. His hand jumped to it: He saw Hermione\rquote s eyes\lang3081  \lang1033 narrow, and he tried to pass off the movement by brushing his hair out of his eyes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, if all three of us go we\rquote ll have to Disapparate separately,\rdblquote  Ron was saying. \ldblquote We can\rquote t all fit under the Cloak anymore.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s scar was becoming more and more painful. He stood up. At once, Kreacher hurried forward.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Master has not finished his soup, would Master prefer the savory stew, or else the treacle tart to which Master is so partial?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thanks, Kreacher, but I\rquote ll be back in a minute \emdash  er \emdash  bath\-room.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Aware that Hermione was watching him suspiciously, Harry hur\-ried up the stairs to the hall and then to the first landing, where he dashed into the bathroom and bolted the door again. Grunting with pain, he slumped over the black basin with its taps in the form of open-mouthed serpents and closed his eyes. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was gliding along a twilit street. The buildings on either side of him had high, timbered gables; they looked like gingerbread houses.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He approached one of them, then saw the whiteness of his own long-fingered hand against the door. He knocked. He felt a mount\-ing excitement. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The door opened: A laughing woman stood there. Her face fell as she looked into Harry\rquote s face: humor gone, terror replacing it. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Gregorovitch?\rdblquote  said a high, cold voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She shook her head: She was trying to close the door. A white hand held it steady, prevented her shutting him out. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I want Gregorovitch.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Er wohnt hier nicht mehr\i0 !\rdblquote  she cried, shaking her head. \ldblquote He no live here! He no live here! I know him not!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Abandoning the attempt to close the door, she began to back away down the dark hall, and Harry followed, gliding toward her, and his long-fingered hand had drawn his wand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where is he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Das wei\'df\lang3081  \lang1033 ich nicht\i0 !\lang3081  \lang1033 He move! I know not, I know not!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He raised the wand. She screamed. Two young children came running into the hall. She tried to shield them with her arms. There was a flash of green light \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry! HARRY!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He opened his eyes; he had sunk to the floor. Hermione was pounding on the door again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, open up!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He had shouted out, he knew it. He got up and unbolted the door; Hermione toppled inside at once, regained her balance, and looked around suspiciously. Ron was right behind her, looking unnerved as he pointed his wand into the corners of the chilly bathroom.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What were you doing?\rdblquote  asked Hermione sternly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What d\rquote you think I was doing?\rdblquote  asked Harry with feeble bravado.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You were yelling your head off!\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yeah \'85 I must\rquote ve dozed off or \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, please don\rquote t insult our intelligence,\rdblquote  said Hermione, tak\-ing deep breaths. \ldblquote We know your scar hurt downstairs, and you\rquote re white as a sheet.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry sat down on the edge of the bath.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fine. I\rquote ve just seen Voldemort murdering a woman. By now he\rquote s probably killed her whole family. And he didn\rquote t need to. It was Cedric all over again, they were just \i there. \'85\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, you aren\rquote t supposed to let this happen anymore!\rdblquote\lang3081  \lang1033 Hermione cried, her voice echoing through the bathroom. \ldblquote Dum\-bledore wanted you to use Occlumency! He thought the connection was dangerous \emdash  Voldemort can \i use\i0  it, Harry! What good is it to watch him kill and torture, how can it help?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because it means I know what he\rquote s doing,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So you\rquote re not even going to \i try\i0  to shut him out?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hermione, I can\rquote t. You know I\rquote m lousy at Occlumency, I never got the hang of it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You never really tried!\rdblquote  she said hotly. \ldblquote I don\rquote t get it, Harry \emdash  do you \i like\i0  having this special connection or relationship or what \emdash  whatever \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She faltered under the look he gave her as he stood up.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Like it?\rdblquote  he said quietly. \ldblquote Would\lang3081  \lang1033\i you\i0  like it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \emdash  no \emdash  I\rquote m sorry, Harry, I didn\rquote t mean \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I hate it, I hate the fact that he can get inside me, that I have to watch him when he\rquote s most dangerous. But I\rquote m going to use it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Forget Dumbledore. This is my choice, nobody else\rquote s. I want to know why he\rquote s after Gregorovitch.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Who?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s a foreign wandmaker,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote He made Krum\rquote s wand and Krum reckons he\rquote s brilliant.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But according to you,\rdblquote  said Ron, \ldblquote Voldemort\rquote s got Ollivander locked up somewhere. If he\rquote s already got a wandmaker, what does he need another one for?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Maybe he agrees with Krum, maybe he thinks Gregorovitch is better \'85 or else he thinks Gregorovitch will be able to explain what my wand did when he was chasing me, because Ollivander didn\rquote t know.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry glanced into the cracked, dusty mirror and saw Ron and Hermione exchanging skeptical looks behind his back.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, you keep talking about what your wand did,\rdblquote  said Her\-mione, \ldblquote but \i you\i0  made it happen! Why are you so determined not to take responsibility for your own power?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because I know it wasn\rquote t me! And so does Voldemort, Hermione! We both know what really happened!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They glared at each other: Harry knew that he had not con\-vinced Hermione and that she was marshaling counterarguments, against both his theory on his wand and the fact that he was per\-mitting himself to see into Voldemort\rquote s mind. To his relief, Ron intervened.\lang3081\par
