\ldblquote Undesirable Number One,\rdblquote  Harry muttered under his breath as he replaced Mr. Weasley\rquote s folder and shut the drawer. He had an idea he knew who that was, and sure enough, as he straightened up and glanced around the office for fresh hiding places, he saw a poster of himself on the wall, with the words undesirable no. 1 emblazoned across his chest. A little pink note was stuck to it with a picture of a kitten in the corner. Harry moved across to read it and saw that Umbridge had written, \ldblquote\i To be punished.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Angrier than ever, he proceeded to grope in the bottoms of the vases and baskets of dried flowers, but was not at all surprised that the locket was not there. He gave the office one last sweeping look, and his heart skipped a beat. Dumbledore was staring at him from a small rectangular mirror, propped up on a bookcase beside the desk.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry crossed the room at a run and snatched it up, but realized the moment he touched it that it was not a mirror at all. Dumble\-dore was smiling wistfully out of the front cover of a glossy book. Harry had not immediately noticed the curly green writing across his hat \emdash  \i The Life and Lies of\lang3081  \lang1033 Albus Dumbledore\i0  \emdash  nor the slightly smaller writing across his chest: \ldblquote by Rita Skeeter, bestselling author of \i Armando Dippet: Master or Moron\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry opened the book at random and saw a full-page photo\-graph of two teenage boys, both laughing immoderately with their arms around each other\rquote s shoulders. Dumbledore, now with elbow-length hair, had grown a tiny wispy beard that recalled the one on Krum\rquote s chin that had so annoyed Ron. The boy who roared in si\-lent amusement beside Dumbledore had a gleeful, wild look about him. His golden hair fell in curls to his shoulders. Harry wondered whether it was a young Doge, but before he could check the caption, the door of the office opened.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 If Thicknesse had not been looking over his shoulder as he en\-tered, Harry would not have had time to pull the Invisibility Cloak over himself. As it was, he thought Thicknesse might have caught a glimpse of movement, because for a moment or two he remained quite still, staring curiously at the place where Harry had just vanished. Perhaps deciding that all he had seen was Dumbledore scratching his nose on the front of the book, for Harry had hastily replaced it upon the shelf, Thicknesse finally walked to the desk and pointed his wand at the quill standing ready in the ink pot. It sprang out and began scribbling a note to Umbridge. Very slowly, hardly daring to breathe, Harry backed out of the office into the open area beyond.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The pamphlet-makers were still clustered around the remains of the Decoy Detonator, which continued to hoot feebly as it smoked. Harry hurried off up the corridor as the young witch said, \ldblquote I bet it sneaked up here from Experimental Charms, they\rquote re so careless, remember that poisonous duck?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Speeding back toward the lifts, Harry reviewed his options. It had never been likely that the locket was here at the Ministry, and there was no hope of bewitching its whereabouts out of Umbridge while\lang3081  \lang1033 she was sitting in a crowded court. Their priority now had to be to leave the Ministry before they were exposed, and try again another day. The first thing to do was to find Ron, and then they could work out a way of extracting Hermione from the courtroom.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The lift was empty when it arrived. Harry jumped in and pulled off the Invisibility Cloak as it started its descent. To his enormous relief, when it rattled to a halt at level two, a soaking-wet and wild-eyed Ron got in.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote M-morning,\rdblquote  he stammered to Harry as the lift set off again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ron, it\rquote s me, Harry!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry! Blimey, I forgot what you looked like \emdash  why isn\rquote t Her\-mione with you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She had to go down to the courtrooms with Umbridge, she couldn\rquote t refuse, and \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But before Harry could finish the lift had stopped again: The doors opened and Mr. Weasley walked inside, talking to an el\-derly witch whose blonde hair was teased so high it resembled an anthill.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 I quite understand what you\rquote re saying, Wakanda, but I\rquote m afraid I cannot be party to \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Weasley broke off; he had noticed Harry. It was very strange to have Mr. Weasley glare at him with that much dislike. The lift doors closed and the four of them trundled downward once more.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, hello, Reg,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, looking around at the sound of steady dripping from Ron\rquote s robes. \ldblquote Isn\rquote t your wife in for question\-ing today? Er \emdash  what\rquote s happened to you? Why are you so wet?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yaxley\rquote s office is raining,\rdblquote  said Ron. He addressed Mr. Weasley\rquote s shoulder, and Harry felt sure he was scared that his father might rec\-ognize him if they looked directly into each other\rquote s eyes. \ldblquote I couldn\rquote t\lang3081  \lang1033 stop it, so they\rquote ve sent me to get Bernie \emdash  Pillsworth, I think they said \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, a lot of offices have been raining lately,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote Did you try Meteolojinx Recanto? It worked for Bletchley.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Meteolojinx Recanto?\rdblquote  whispered Ron. \ldblquote No, I didn\rquote t. Thanks, D \emdash  I mean, thanks, Arthur.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The lift doors opened; the old witch with the anthill hair left, and Ron darted past her out of sight. Harry made to follow him, but found his path blocked as Percy Weasley strode into the lift, his nose buried in some papers he was reading.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Not until the doors had clanged shut again did Percy realize he was in a lift with his father. He glanced up, saw Mr. Weasley, turned radish red, and left the lift the moment the doors opened again. For the second time, Harry tried to get out, but this time found his way blocked by Mr. Weasley\rquote s arm.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote One moment, Runcorn.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The lift doors closed and as they clanked down another floor, Mr. Weasley said, \ldblquote I hear you laid information about Dirk Cresswell.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had the impression that Mr. Weasley\rquote s anger was no less because of the brush with Percy. He decided his best chance was to act stupid.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sorry?\rdblquote  he said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t pretend, Runcorn,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley fiercely. \ldblquote You tracked down the wizard who faked his family tree, didn\rquote t you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \emdash  so what if I did?\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So Dirk Cresswell is ten times the wizard you are,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley quietly, as the lift sank ever lower. \ldblquote And if he survives Az\-kaban, you\rquote ll have to answer to him, not to mention his wife, his sons, and his friends \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Arthur,\rdblquote  Harry interrupted, \ldblquote you know you\rquote re being tracked, don\rquote t you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is that a threat, Runcorn?\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley loudly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote it\rquote s a fact! They\rquote re watching your every move \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The lift doors opened. They had reached the Atrium. Mr. Weasley gave Harry a scathing look and swept from the lift. Harry stood there, shaken. He wished he was impersonating somebody other than Runcorn. \'85 The lift doors clanged shut.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry pulled out the Invisibility Cloak and put it back on. He would try to extricate Hermione on his own while Ron was dealing with the raining office. When the doors opened, he stepped out into a torch-lit stone passageway quite different from the wood-paneled and carpeted corridors above. As the lift rattled away again, Harry shivered slightly, looking toward the distant black door that marked the entrance to the Department of Mysteries.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He set off, his destination not the black door, but the doorway he remembered on the left-hand side, which opened onto the flight of stairs down to the court chambers. His mind grappled with pos\-sibilities as he crept down them: He still had a couple of Decoy Detonators, but perhaps it would be better to simply knock on the courtroom door, enter as Runcorn, and ask for a quick word with Mafalda? Of course, he did not know whether Runcorn was suf\-ficiently important to get away with this, and even if he managed it, Hermione\rquote s non-reappearance might trigger a search before they were clear of the Ministry. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lost in thought, he did not immediately register the unnatural chill that was creeping over him, as if he were descending into fog. It was becoming colder and colder with every step he took: a cold\lang3081  \lang1033 that reached right down into his throat and tore at his lungs. And then he felt that stealing sense of despair, of hopelessness, filling him, expanding inside him. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i Dementors,\i0  he thought.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And as he reached the foot of the stairs and turned to his right he saw a dreadful scene. The dark passage outside the courtrooms was packed with tall, black-hooded figures, their faces completely hid\-den, their ragged breathing the only sound in the place. The petrified Muggle-borns brought in for questioning sat huddled and shivering on hard wooden benches. Most of them were hiding their faces in their hands, perhaps in an instinctive attempt to shield themselves from the dementors\rquote  greedy mouths. Some were accompanied by families, others sat alone. The dementors were gliding up and down in front of them, and the cold, and the hopelessness, and the despair of the place laid themselves upon Harry like a curse. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i Fight it,\i0  he told himself, but he knew that he could not conjure a Patronus here without revealing himself instantly. So he moved forward as silently as he could, and with every step he took numb\-ness seemed to steal over his brain, but he forced himself to think of Hermione and of Ron, who needed him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Moving through the towering black figures was terrifying: The eyeless faces hidden beneath their hoods turned as he passed, and he felt sure that they sensed him, sensed, perhaps, a human presence that still had some hope, some resilience. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And then, abruptly and shockingly amid the frozen silence, one of the dungeon doors on the left of the corridor was flung open and screams echoed out of it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, no, I\rquote m half-blood, I\rquote m half-blood, I tell you! My father was a wizard, he \i was,\i0  look him up, Arkie Alderton, he\rquote s a well-known\lang3081  \lang1033 broomstick designer, look him up, I tell you \emdash  get your hands off me, get your hands off\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This is your final warning,\rdblquote  said Umbridge\rquote s soft voice, magi\-cally magnified so that it sounded clearly over the man\rquote s desperate screams. \ldblquote If you struggle, you will be subjected to the Dementor\rquote s Kiss.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The man\rquote s screams subsided, but dry sobs echoed through the corridor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Take him away,\rdblquote  said Umbridge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Two dementors appeared in the doorway of the courtroom, their rotting, scabbed hands clutching the upper arms of a wizard who appeared to be fainting. They glided away down the corridor with him, and the darkness they trailed behind them swallowed him from sight.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Next \emdash  Mary Cattermole,\rdblquote  called Umbridge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A small woman stood up; she was trembling from head to foot. Her dark hair was smoothed back into a bun and she wore long, plain robes. Her face was completely bloodless. As she passed the dementors, Harry saw her shudder.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He did it instinctively, without any sort of plan, because he hated the sight of her walking alone into the dungeon: As the door began to swing closed, he slipped into the courtroom behind her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was not the same room in which he had once been interrogated for improper use of magic. This one was much smaller, though the ceiling was quite as high; it gave the claustrophobic sense of being stuck at the bottom of a deep well.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There were more dementors in here, casting their freezing aura over the place; they stood like faceless sentinels in the corners far\-thest from the high, raised platform. Here, behind a balustrade, sat\lang3081  \lang1033 Umbridge, with Yaxley on one side of her, and Hermione, quite as white-faced as Mrs. Cattermole, on the other. At the foot of the platform, a bright-silver, long-haired cat prowled up and down, up and down, and Harry realized that it was there to protect the pros\-ecutors from the despair that emanated from the dementors: That was for the accused to feel, not the accusers.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sit down,\rdblquote  said Umbridge in her soft, silky voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Cattermole stumbled to the single seat in the middle of the floor beneath the raised platform. The moment she had sat down, chains clinked out of the arms of the chair and bound her there.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You are Mary Elizabeth Cattermole?\rdblquote  asked Umbridge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Cattermole gave a single, shaky nod.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Married to Reginald Cattermole of the Magical Maintenance Department?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Cattermole burst into tears.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t know where he is, he was supposed to meet me here!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Umbridge ignored her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mother to Maisie, Ellie, and Alfred Cattermole?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Cattermole sobbed harder than ever.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They\rquote re frightened, they think I might not come home \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Spare us,\rdblquote  spat Yaxley. \ldblquote The brats of Mudbloods do not stir our sympathies.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Cattermole\rquote s sobs masked Harry\rquote s footsteps as he made his way carefully toward the steps that led up to the raised platform. The moment he had passed the place where the Patronus cat patrolled, he felt the change in temperature: It was warm and comfortable here. The Patronus, he was sure, was Umbridge\rquote s, and it glowed brightly because she was so happy here, in her element, upholding the twisted laws she had helped to write. Slowly and very carefully he edged\lang3081  \lang1033 his way along the platform behind Umbridge, Yaxley, and Hermi\-one, taking a seat behind the latter. He was worried about making Hermione jump. He thought of casting the \i Muffliato\i0  charm upon Umbridge and Yaxley, but even murmuring the word might cause Hermione alarm. Then Umbridge raised her voice to address Mrs. Cattermole, and Harry seized his chance.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m behind you,\rdblquote  he whispered into Hermione\rquote s ear.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As he had expected, she jumped so violently she nearly overturned the bottle of ink with which she was supposed to be recording the interview, but both Umbridge and Yaxley were concentrating upon Mrs. Cattermole, and this went unnoticed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A wand was taken from you upon your arrival at the Ministry today, Mrs. Cattermole,\rdblquote  Umbridge was saying. \ldblquote Eight-and-three-quarter inches, cherry, unicorn-hair core. Do you recognize that description?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Cattermole nodded, mopping her eyes on her sleeve.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Could you please tell us from which witch or wizard you took that wand?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote T-took?\rdblquote  sobbed Mrs. Cattermole. \ldblquote I didn\rquote t t-take it from any\-body. I b-bought it when I was eleven years old. It \emdash  it \emdash  it \emdash  \i chose\i0  me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She cried harder than ever.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Umbridge laughed a soft girlish laugh that made Harry want to attack her. She leaned forward over the barrier, the better to observe her victim, and something gold swung forward too, and dangled over the void: the locket.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione had seen it; she let out a little squeak, but Umbridge and Yaxley, still intent upon their prey, were deaf to everything else.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Umbridge, \ldblquote no, I don\rquote t think so, Mrs. Cattermole. Wands only choose witches or wizards. You are not a witch. I have your responses to the questionnaire that was sent to you here \emdash  Mafalda, pass them to me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Umbridge held out a small hand: She looked so toadlike at that moment that Harry was quite surprised not to see webs between the stubby fingers. Hermione\rquote s hands were shaking with shock. She fumbled in a pile of documents balanced on the chair beside her, finally withdrawing a sheaf of parchment with Mrs. Cattermole\rquote s name on it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s \emdash  that\rquote s pretty, Dolores,\rdblquote  she said, pointing at the pen\-dant gleaming in the ruffled folds of Umbridge\rquote s blouse.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  snapped Umbridge, glancing down. \ldblquote Oh yes \emdash  an old family heirloom,\rdblquote  she said, patting the locket lying on her large bo\-som. \ldblquote The \i S\i0  stands for Selwyn. \'85 I am related to the Selwyns. \'85 Indeed, there are few pure-blood families to whom I am not related. \'85 A pity,\rdblquote  she continued in a louder voice, flicking through Mrs. Cattermole\rquote s questionnaire, \ldblquote that the same cannot be said for you. \lquote\i Parents\i0\rquote\i  professions: greengrocers.\i0\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Yaxley laughed jeeringly. Below, the fluffy silver cat patrolled up and down, and the dementors stood waiting in the corners.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was Umbridge\rquote s lie that brought the blood surging into Harry\rquote s brain and obliterated his sense of caution \emdash  that the locket she had taken as a bribe from a petty criminal was being used to bol\-ster her own pure-blood credentials. He raised his wand, not even troubling to keep it concealed beneath the Invisibility Cloak, and said, \ldblquote\i Stupefy\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a flash of red light; Umbridge crumpled and her fore\-head hit the edge of the balustrade: Mrs. Cattermole\rquote s papers slid\lang3081  \lang1033 off her lap onto the floor and, down below, the prowling silver cat vanished. Ice-cold air hit them like an oncoming wind: Yaxley, con\-fused, looked around for the source of the trouble and saw Harry\rquote s disembodied hand and wand pointing at him. He tried to draw his own wand, but too late: \ldblquote\i Stupefy\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Yaxley slid to the ground to lie curled on the floor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hermione, if you think I was going to sit here and let her pretend \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, Mrs. Cattermole!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry whirled around, throwing off the Invisibility Cloak; down below, the dementors had moved out of their corners; they were gliding toward the woman chained to the chair: Whether because the Patronus had vanished or because they sensed that their masters were no longer in control, they seemed to have abandoned restraint. Mrs. Cattermole let out a terrible scream of fear as a slimy, scabbed hand grasped her chin and forced her face back.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i EXPECTO PATRONUM\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The silver stag soared from the tip of Harry\rquote s wand and leaped toward the dementors, which fell back and melted into the dark shadows again. The stag\rquote s light, more powerful and more warming than the cat\rquote s protection, filled the whole dungeon as it cantered around and around the room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Get the Horcrux,\rdblquote  Harry told Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He ran back down the steps, stuffing the Invisibility Cloak back into his bag, and approached Mrs. Cattermole.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You?\rdblquote  she whispered, gazing into his face. \ldblquote But \emdash  but Reg said you were the one who submitted my name for questioning!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did I?\rdblquote  muttered Harry, tugging at the chains binding her arms.\lang3081  \lang1033\ldblquote Well, I\rquote ve had a change of heart. \i Diffindo\i0 !\rdblquote  Nothing happened. \ldblquote Hermione, how do I get rid of these chains?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wait, I\rquote m trying something up here \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hermione, we\rquote re surrounded by dementors!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I know that, Harry, but if she wakes up and the locket\rquote s gone \emdash  I need to duplicate it \emdash  \i Geminio\i0 ! There \'85 That should fool her. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione came running downstairs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let\rquote s see. \'85 \i Relashio\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The chains clinked and withdrew into the arms of the chair. Mrs. Cattermole looked just as frightened as ever before.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t understand,\rdblquote  she whispered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re going to leave here with us,\rdblquote  said Harry, pulling her to her feet. \ldblquote Go home, grab your children, and get out, get out of the country if you\rquote ve got to. Disguise yourselves and run. You\rquote ve seen how it is, you won\rquote t get anything like a fair hearing here.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry,\rdblquote  said Hermione, \ldblquote how are we going to get out of here with all those dementors outside the door?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Patronuses,\rdblquote  said Harry, pointing his wand at his own: The stag slowed and walked, still gleaming brightly, toward the door. \ldblquote As many as we can muster; do yours, Hermione.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Expec \i0\emdash  \i Expecto patronum,\i0\rdblquote  said Hermione. Nothing hap\-pened.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s the only spell she ever has trouble with,\rdblquote  Harry told a com\-pletely bemused Mrs. Cattermole. \ldblquote Bit unfortunate, really\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 Come on, Hermione. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Expecto patronum\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A silver otter burst from the end of Hermione\rquote s wand and swam gracefully through the air to join the stag.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote C\rquote mon,\rdblquote  said Harry, and he led Hermione and Mrs. Cattermole to the door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 When the Patronuses glided out of the dungeon there were cries of shock from the people waiting outside. Harry looked around; the dementors were falling back on both sides of them, melding into the darkness, scattering before the silver creatures.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s been decided that you should all go home and go into hiding with your families,\rdblquote  Harry told the waiting Muggle-borns, who were dazzled by the light of the Patronuses and still cowering slightly. \ldblquote Go abroad if you can. Just get well away from the Ministry. That\rquote s the \emdash  er \emdash  new official position. Now, if you\rquote ll just follow the Pa\-tronuses, you\rquote ll be able to leave from the Atrium.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They managed to get up the stone steps without being intercepted, but as they approached the lifts Harry started to have misgivings. If they emerged into the Atrium with a silver stag, an otter soaring alongside it, and twenty or so people, half of them accused Muggle-borns, he could not help feeling that they would attract unwanted attention. He had just reached this unwelcome conclusion when the lift clanged to a halt in front of them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Reg!\rdblquote  screamed Mrs. Cattermole, and she threw herself into Ron\rquote s arms. \ldblquote Runcorn let me out, he attacked Umbridge and Yaxley, and he\rquote s told all of us to leave the country, I think we\rquote d better do it, Reg, I really do, let\rquote s hurry home and fetch the children and \emdash  why are you so wet?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Water,\rdblquote  muttered Ron, disengaging himself. \ldblquote Harry, they know there are intruders inside the Ministry, something about a hole in Umbridge\rquote s office door, I reckon we\rquote ve got five minutes if that \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione\rquote s Patronus vanished with a \i pop\i0  as she turned a horror-struck face to Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, if we\rquote re trapped here \emdash  !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We won\rquote t be if we move fast,\rdblquote  said Harry. He addressed the silent group behind them, who were all gawping at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Who\rquote s got wands?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 About half of them raised their hands.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Okay, all of you who haven\rquote t got wands need to attach yourself to somebody who has. We\rquote ll need to be fast before they stop us. Come on.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They managed to cram themselves into two lifts. Harry\rquote s Patro\-nus stood sentinel before the golden grilles as they shut and the lifts began to rise.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Level eight,\rdblquote  said the witch\rquote s cool voice, \ldblquote Atrium.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry knew at once that they were in trouble. The Atrium was full of people moving from fireplace to fireplace, sealing them off.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry!\rdblquote  squeaked Hermione. \ldblquote What are we going to \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote STOP!\rdblquote  Harry thundered, and the powerful voice of Runcorn echoed through the Atrium: The wizards sealing the fireplaces froze. \ldblquote Follow me,\rdblquote  he whispered to the group of terrified Muggle-borns, who moved forward in a huddle, shepherded by Ron and Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s up, Albert?\rdblquote  said the same balding wizard who had fol\-lowed Harry out of the fireplace earlier. He looked nervous.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This lot need to leave before you seal the exits,\rdblquote  said Harry with all the authority he could muster.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The group of wizards in front of him looked at one another.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ve been told to seal all exits and not let anyone \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Are\lang3081  \lang1033 you contradicting me\i0 ?\rdblquote  Harry blustered. \ldblquote Would you like me to have your family tree examined, like I had Dirk Cresswell\rquote s?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sorry!\rdblquote  gasped the balding wizard, backing away. \ldblquote I didn\rquote t mean\lang3081  \lang1033 nothing, Albert, but I thought\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 I thought they were in for ques\-tioning and \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Their blood is pure,\rdblquote  said Harry, and his deep voice echoed im\-pressively through the hall. \ldblquote Purer than many of yours, I daresay. Off you go,\rdblquote  he boomed to the Muggle-borns, who scurried forward into the fireplaces and began to vanish in pairs. The Ministry wiz\-ards hung back, some looking confused, others scared and resent\-ful. Then:\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mary!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Cattermole looked over her shoulder. The real Reg Catter\-mole, no longer vomiting but pale and wan, had just come running out of a lift.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote R-Reg?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She looked from her husband to Ron, who swore loudly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The balding wizard gaped, his head turning ludicrously from one Reg Cattermole to the other.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hey \emdash  what\rquote s going on? What is this?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Seal the exit! SEAL IT!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Yaxley had burst out of another lift and was running toward the group beside the fireplaces, into which all of the Muggle-borns but Mrs. Cattermole had now vanished. As the balding wizard lifted his wand, Harry raised an enormous fist and punched him, sending him flying through the air.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s been helping Muggle-borns escape, Yaxley!\rdblquote  Harry shouted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The balding wizard\rquote s colleagues set up an uproar, under cover of which Ron grabbed Mrs. Cattermole, pulled her into the still-open fireplace, and disappeared. Confused, Yaxley looked from Harry to\lang3081  \lang1033 the punched wizard, while the real Reg Cattermole screamed, \ldblquote My wife! Who was that with my wife? What\rquote s going on?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry saw Yaxley\rquote s head turn, saw an inkling of the truth dawn in that brutish face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Come on!\rdblquote  Harry shouted at Hermione; he seized her hand and they jumped into the fireplace together as Yaxley\rquote s curse sailed over Harry\rquote s head. They spun for a few seconds before shooting up out of a toilet into a cubicle. Harry flung open the door; Ron was standing there beside the sinks, still wrestling with Mrs. Cattermole.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Reg, I don\rquote t understand \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let go, I\rquote m not your husband, you\rquote ve got to go home!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a noise in the cubicle behind them; Harry looked around; Yaxley had just appeared.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote LET\rquote S GO!\rdblquote  Harry yelled. He seized Hermione by the hand and Ron by the arm and turned on the spot.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Darkness engulfed them, along with the sensation of compressing bands, but something was wrong. \'85 Hermione\rquote s hand seemed to be sliding out of his grip. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He wondered whether he was going to suffocate; he could not breathe or see and the only solid things in the world were Ron\rquote s arm and Hermione\rquote s fingers, which were slowly slipping away. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And then he saw the door of number twelve, Grimmauld Place, with its serpent door knocker, but before he could draw breath, there was a scream and a flash of purple light; Hermione\rquote s hand was sud\-denly vicelike upon his and everything went dark again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\par
