\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\fs24\par
Harry opened his eyes and was dazzled by gold and green; he had no idea what had happened, he only knew that he was lying on what seemed to be leaves and twigs. Struggling to draw breath into lungs that felt flattened, he blinked and realized that the gaudy glare was sunlight streaming through a canopy of leaves far above him. Then an object twitched close to his face. He pushed himself onto his hands and knees, ready to face some small, fierce creature, but saw that the object was Ron\rquote s foot. Looking around, Harry saw that they and Hermione were lying on a forest floor, apparently alone.\par
Harry\rquote s first thought was of the Forbidden Forest, and for a mo\-ment, even though he knew how foolish and dangerous it would be for them to appear in the grounds of Hogwarts, his heart leapt at the thought of sneaking through the trees to Hagrid\rquote s hut. How\-ever, in the few moments it took for Ron to give a low groan and Harry to start crawling toward him, he realized that this was not the\lang3081  \lang1033 Forbidden Forest: The trees looked younger, they were more widely spaced, the ground clearer.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He met Hermione, also on her hands and knees, at Ron\rquote s head. The moment his eyes fell upon Ron, all other concerns fled Harry\rquote s mind, for blood drenched the whole of Ron\rquote s left side and his face stood out, grayish-white, against the leaf-strewn earth. The Polyjuice Potion was wearing off now: Ron was halfway between Cattermole and himself in appearance, his hair turning redder and redder as his face drained of the little color it had left.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s happened to him?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Splinched,\rdblquote  said Hermione, her fingers already busy at Ron\rquote s sleeve, where the blood was wettest and darkest.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry watched, horrified, as she tore open Ron\rquote s shirt. He had always thought of Splinching as something comical, but this \'85 His insides crawled unpleasantly as Hermione laid bare Ron\rquote s up\-per arm, where a great chunk of flesh was missing, scooped cleanly away as though by a knife.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, quickly, in my bag, there\rquote s a small bottle labeled \lquote Essence of Dittany\rquote\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bag \emdash  right \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry sped to the place where Hermione had landed, seized the tiny beaded bag, and thrust his hand inside it. At once, object after object began presenting itself to his touch: He felt the leather spines of books, woolly sleeves of jumpers, heels of shoes \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Quickly\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He grabbed his wand from the ground and pointed it into the depths of the magical bag.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Accio Dittany\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A small brown bottle zoomed out of the bag; he caught it and\lang3081  \lang1033 hastened back to Hermione and Ron, whose eyes were now half-closed, strips of white eyeball all that were visible between his lids.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s fainted,\rdblquote  said Hermione, who was also rather pale; she no longer looked like Mafalda, though her hair was still gray in places. \ldblquote Unstopper it for me, Harry, my hands are shaking.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry wrenched the stopper off the little bottle, Hermione took it and poured three drops of the potion onto the bleeding wound. Greenish smoke billowed upward and when it had cleared, Harry saw that the bleeding had stopped. The wound now looked several days old; new skin stretched over what had just been open flesh.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wow,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s all I feel safe doing,\rdblquote  said Hermione shakily. \ldblquote There are spells that would put him completely right, but I daren\rquote t try in case I do them wrong and cause more damage. \'85 He\rquote s lost so much blood already. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How did he get hurt? I mean\rdblquote  \emdash  Harry shook his head, trying to clear it, to make sense of whatever had just taken place \emdash  \ldblquote why are we here? I thought we were going back to Grimmauld Place?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione took a deep breath. She looked close to tears.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, I don\rquote t think we\rquote re going to be able to go back there.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\lang3081  \lang1033 d\rquote you \emdash\lang3081  \lang1033 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote As we Disapparated, Yaxley caught hold of me and I couldn\rquote t get rid of him, he was too strong, and he was still holding on when we arrived at Grimmauld Place, and then \emdash  well, I think he must have seen the door, and thought we were stopping there, so he slackened his grip and I managed to shake him off and I brought us here instead!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But then, where\rquote s he? Hang on. \'85 You don\rquote t mean he\rquote s at Grim\-mauld Place? He can\rquote t get in there?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Her eyes sparkled with unshed tears as she nodded.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, I think he can. I \emdash  I forced him to let go with a Revul\-sion Jinx, but I\rquote d already taken him inside the Fidelius Charm\rquote s protection. Since Dumbledore died, we\rquote re Secret-Keepers, so I\rquote ve given him the secret, haven\rquote t I?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was no pretending; Harry was sure she was right. It was a serious blow. If Yaxley could now get inside the house, there was no way that they could return. Even now, he could be bringing other Death Eaters in there by Apparition. Gloomy and oppressive though the house was, it had been their one safe refuge: even, now that Kreacher was so much happier and friendlier, a kind of home. With a twinge of regret that had nothing to do with food, Harry imagined the house-elf busying himself over the steak-and-kidney pie that Harry, Ron, and Hermione would never eat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, I\rquote m sorry, I\rquote m so sorry!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t be stupid, it wasn\rquote t your fault! If anything, it was mine. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry put his hand in his pocket and drew out Mad-Eye\rquote s eye. Hermione recoiled, looking horrified.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Umbridge had stuck it to her office door, to spy on people. I couldn\rquote t leave it there \'85 but that\rquote s how they knew there were intruders.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Before Hermione could answer, Ron groaned and opened his eyes. He was still gray and his face glistened with sweat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How d\rquote you feel?\rdblquote  Hermione whispered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Lousy,\rdblquote  croaked Ron, wincing as he felt his injured arm. \ldblquote Where are we?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote In the woods where they held the Quidditch World Cup,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote I wanted somewhere enclosed, undercover, and this was \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  the first place you thought of,\rdblquote  Harry finished for her, glanc\-ing around at the apparently deserted glade. He could not help re\-membering what had happened the last time they had Apparated to the first place Hermione had thought of\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash  how Death Eaters had found them within minutes. Had it been Legilimency? Did Voldemort or his henchmen know, even now, where Hermione had taken them?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote D\rquote you reckon we should move on?\rdblquote  Ron asked Harry, and Harry could tell by the look on Ron\rquote s face that he was thinking the same.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I dunno.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron still looked pale and clammy. He had made no attempt to sit up and it looked as though he was too weak to do so. The prospect of moving him was daunting.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let\rquote s stay here for now,\rdblquote  Harry said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Looking relieved, Hermione sprang to her feet.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where are you going?\rdblquote  asked Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If we\rquote re staying, we should put some protective enchantments around the place,\rdblquote  she replied, and raising her wand, she began to walk in a wide circle around Harry and Ron, murmuring in\-cantations as she went. Harry saw little disturbances in the sur\-rounding air: It was as if Hermione had cast a heat haze upon their clearing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Salvio Hexia\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 Protego Totalum \'85 Repello Muggletum \'85 Muffliato\i0  \i\'85 \i0 You could get out the tent, Harry. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Tent?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote In the bag!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote In the \'85 of course,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He did not bother to grope inside it this time, but used another\lang3081  \lang1033 Summoning Charm. The tent emerged in a lumpy mass of canvas, rope, and poles. Harry recognized it, partly because of the smell of cats, as the same tent in which they had slept on the night of the Quidditch World Cup.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I thought this belonged to that bloke Perkins at the Ministry?\rdblquote  he asked, starting to disentangle the tent pegs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Apparently he didn\rquote t want it back, his lumbago\rquote s so bad,\rdblquote  said Hermione, now performing complicated figure-of-eight movements with her wand, \ldblquote so Ron\rquote s dad said I could borrow it. \i Erecto\i0 !\rdblquote  she added, pointing her wand at the misshapen canvas, which in one fluid motion rose into the air and settled, fully constructed, onto the ground before Harry, out of whose startled hands a tent peg soared, to land with a final thud at the end of a guy rope.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Cave Inimicum,\i0\rdblquote  Hermione finished with a skyward flourish. \ldblquote That\rquote s as much as I can do. At the very least, we should know they\rquote re coming, I can\rquote t guarantee it will keep out Vol \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t say the name!\rdblquote  Ron cut across her, his voice harsh.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry and Hermione looked at each other.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry,\rdblquote  Ron said, moaning a little as he raised himself to look at them, \ldblquote but it feels like a \emdash  a jinx or something. Can\rquote t we call him You-Know-Who \emdash  please?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore said fear of a name \emdash\rdblquote  began Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote In case you hadn\rquote t noticed, mate, calling You-Know-Who by his name didn\rquote t do Dumbledore much good in the end,\rdblquote  Ron snapped back. \ldblquote Just \emdash  just show You-Know-Who some respect, will you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Respect\i0 ?\rdblquote  Harry repeated, but Hermione shot him a warning look; apparently he was not to argue with Ron while the latter was in such a weakened condition.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry and Hermione half carried, half dragged Ron through\lang3081  \lang1033 the entrance of the tent. The interior was exactly as Harry remem\-bered it: a small flat, complete with bathroom and tiny kitchen. He shoved aside an old armchair and lowered Ron carefully onto the lower berth of a bunk bed. Even this very short journey had turned Ron whiter still, and once they had settled him on the mattress he closed his eyes again and did not speak for a while.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ll make some tea,\rdblquote  said Hermione breathlessly, pulling kettle and mugs from the depths of her bag and heading toward the kitchen.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry found the hot drink as welcome as the firewhisky had been on the night that Mad-Eye had died; it seemed to burn away a little of the fear fluttering in his chest. After a minute or two, Ron broke the silence.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What d\rquote you reckon happened to the Cattermoles?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote With any luck, they\rquote ll have got away,\rdblquote  said Hermione, clutching her hot mug for comfort. \ldblquote As long as Mr. Cattermole had his wits about him, he\rquote ll have transported Mrs. Cattermole by Side-Along-Apparition and they\rquote ll be fleeing the country right now with their children. That\rquote s what Harry told her to do.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Blimey, I hope they escaped,\rdblquote  said Ron, leaning back on his pillows. The tea seemed to be doing him good; a little of his color had returned. \ldblquote I didn\rquote t get the feeling Reg Cattermole was all that quick-witted, though, the way everyone was talking to me when I was him. God, I hope they made it. \'85 If they both end up in Az\-kaban because of us \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked over at Hermione and the question he had been about to ask \emdash  about whether Mrs. Cattermole\rquote s lack of a wand would prevent her Apparating alongside her husband \emdash  died in his throat. Hermione was watching Ron fret over the fate of the Cattermoles, and there was such tenderness in her expression that\lang3081  \lang1033 Harry felt almost as if he had surprised her in the act of kissing him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So, have you got it?\rdblquote  Harry asked her, partly to remind her that he was there.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Got \emdash  got what?\rdblquote  she said with a little start.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What did we just go through all that for? The locket! Where\rquote s the locket?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i You got it\i0 ?\rdblquote  shouted Ron, raising himself a little higher on his pillows. \ldblquote No one tells me anything! Blimey, you could have men\-tioned it!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, we were running for our lives from the Death Eaters, weren\rquote t we?\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote Here.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And she pulled the locket out of the pocket of her robes and handed it to Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was as large as a chicken\rquote s egg. An ornate letter \i S,\i0  inlaid with many small green stones, glinted dully in the diffused light shining through the tent\rquote s canvas roof.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There isn\rquote t any chance someone\rquote s destroyed it since Kreacher had it?\rdblquote  asked Ron hopefully. \lang3081\ldblquote I \lang1033 mean, are we sure it\rquote s still a Horcrux?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think so,\rdblquote  said Hermione, taking it back from him and looking at it closely. \ldblquote There\rquote d be some sign of damage if it had been magi\-cally destroyed.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She passed it to Harry, who turned it over in his fingers. The thing looked perfect, pristine. He remembered the mangled remains of the diary, and how the stone in the Horcrux ring had been cracked open when Dumbledore destroyed it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I reckon Kreacher\rquote s right,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote We\rquote re going to have to work out how to open this thing before we can destroy it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sudden awareness of what he was holding, of what lived behind the little golden doors, hit Harry as he spoke. Even after all their efforts to find it, he felt a violent urge to fling the locket from him. Mastering himself again, he tried to prise the locket apart with his fingers, then attempted the charm Hermione had used to open Regulus\rquote s bedroom door. Neither worked. He handed the locket back to Ron and Hermione, each of whom did their best, but were no more successful at opening it than he had been.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Can you feel it, though?\rdblquote  Ron asked in a hushed voice, as he held it tight in his clenched fist.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What d\rquote you mean?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron passed the Horcrux to Harry. After a moment or two, Harry thought he knew what Ron meant. Was it his own blood pulsing through his veins that he could feel, or was it something beating inside the locket, like a tiny metal heart?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What are we going to do with it?\rdblquote  Hermione asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Keep it safe till we work out how to destroy it,\rdblquote  Harry replied, and, little though he wanted to, he hung the chain around his own neck, dropping the locket out of sight beneath his robes, where it rested against his chest beside the pouch Hagrid had given him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think we should take it in turns to keep watch outside the tent,\rdblquote  he added to Hermione, standing up and stretching. \ldblquote And we\rquote ll need to think about some food as well. You stay there,\rdblquote  he added sharply, as Ron attempted to sit up and turned a nasty shade of green.\lang3081\par
