\lang1033\ldblquote What? What did you see?\rdblquote  demanded Ron, whenever he noticed Harry wince.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A face,\rdblquote  muttered Harry, every time. \ldblquote The same face. The thief who stole from Gregorovitch.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And Ron would turn away, making no effort to hide his disap\-pointment. Harry knew that Ron was hoping to hear news of his family or of the rest of the Order of the Phoenix, but after all, he, Harry, was not a television aerial; he could only see what Voldemort was thinking at the time, not tune in to whatever took his fancy. Ap\-parently Voldemort was dwelling endlessly on the unknown youth with the gleeful face, whose name and whereabouts, Harry felt sure, Voldemort knew no better than he did. As Harry\rquote s scar continued to burn and the merry, blond-haired boy swam tantalizingly in his memory, he learned to suppress any sign of pain or discomfort, for the other two showed nothing but impatience at the mention of the thief. He could not entirely blame them, when they were so desper\-ate for a lead on the Horcruxes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As the days stretched into weeks, Harry began to suspect that Ron and Hermione were having conversations without, and about, him. Several times they stopped talking abruptly when Harry en\-tered the tent, and twice he came accidentally upon them, huddled a little distance away, heads together and talking fast; both times they fell silent when they realized he was approaching them and hastened to appear busy collecting wood or water.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry could not help wondering whether they had only agreed to come on what now felt like a pointless and rambling journey be\-cause they thought he had some secret plan that they would learn in due course. Ron was making no effort to hide his bad mood, and Harry was starting to fear that Hermione too was disappointed by his poor leadership. In desperation he tried to think of further Horcrux locations, but the only one that continued to occur to him was Hogwarts, and as neither of the others thought this at all likely, he stopped suggesting it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Autumn rolled over the countryside as they moved through it: They were now pitching the tent on mulches of fallen leaves. Natural mists joined those cast by the dementors; wind and rain added to their troubles. The fact that Hermione was getting better at iden\-tifying edible fungi could not altogether compensate for their con\-tinuing isolation, the lack of other people\rquote s company, or their total ignorance of what was going on in the war against Voldemort.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My mother,\rdblquote  said Ron one night, as they sat in the tent on a riverbank in Wales, \ldblquote can make good food appear out of thin air.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He prodded moodily at the lumps of charred gray fish on his plate. Harry glanced automatically at Ron\rquote s neck and saw, as he had expected, the golden chain of the Horcrux glinting there. He managed to fight down the impulse to swear at Ron, whose attitude would, he knew, improve slightly when the time came to take off the locket.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Your mother can\rquote t produce food out of thin air,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote No one can. Food is the first of the five Principal Exceptions to Gamp\rquote s Law of Elemental Transfigur \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, speak English, can\rquote t you?\rdblquote  Ron said, prising a fish bone out from between his teeth.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s impossible to make good food out of nothing! You can Sum\-mon it if you know where it is, you can transform it, you can increase the quantity if you\rquote ve already got some \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, don\rquote t bother increasing this, it\rquote s disgusting,\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry caught the fish and I did my best with it! I notice I\rquote m al\-ways the one who ends up sorting out the food, because I\rquote m a \i girl, \i0 I suppose!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, it\rquote s because you\rquote re supposed to be the best at magic!\rdblquote  shot back Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione jumped up and bits of roast pike slid off her tin plate onto the floor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i You\i0  can do the cooking tomorrow, Ron, \i you\i0  can find the ingre\-dients and try and charm them into something worth eating, and I\rquote ll sit here and pull faces and moan and you can see how you \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Shut up!\rdblquote  said Harry, leaping to his feet and holding up both hands. \ldblquote Shut up \i now\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione looked outraged.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How can you side with him, he hardly ever does the cook \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hermione, be quiet, I can hear someone!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was listening hard, his hands still raised, warning them not to talk. Then, over the rush and gush of the dark river beside them, he heard voices again. He looked around at the Sneakoscope. It was not moving.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You cast the Muffliato charm over us, right?\rdblquote  he whispered to Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I did everything,\rdblquote  she whispered back, \ldblquote Muffliato, Muggle-Repelling and Disillusionment Charms, all of it. They shouldn\rquote t be able to hear or see us, whoever they are.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Heavy scuffing and scraping noises, plus the sound of dislodged\lang3081  \lang1033 stones and twigs, told them that several people were clambering down the steep, wooded slope that descended to the narrow bank where they had pitched the tent. They drew their wands, waiting. The enchantments they had cast around themselves ought to be suf\-ficient, in the near total darkness, to shield them from the notice of Muggles and normal witches and wizards. If these were Death Eaters, then perhaps their defenses were about to be tested by Dark Magic for the first time.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The voices became louder but no more intelligible as the group of men reached the bank. Harry estimated that their owners were fewer than twenty feet away, but the cascading river made it impossible to tell for sure. Hermione snatched up the beaded bag and started to rummage; after a moment she drew out three Extendable Ears and threw one each to Harry and Ron, who hastily inserted the ends of the flesh-colored strings into their ears and fed the other ends out of the tent entrance.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Within seconds Harry heard a weary male voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There ought to be a few salmon in here, or d\rquote you reckon it\rquote s too early in the season? \i Accio Salmon\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There were several distinct splashes and then the slapping sounds of\lang3081  \lang1033 fish against flesh. Somebody grunted appreciatively. Harry pressed the Extendable Ear deeper into his own: Over the murmur of the river he could make out more voices, but they were not speaking English or any human language he had ever heard. It was a rough and unmelodious tongue, a string of rattling, guttural noises, and there seemed to be two speakers, one with a slightly lower, slower voice than the other.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A fire danced into life on the other side of the canvas; large shad\-ows passed between tent and flames. The delicious smell of baking\lang3081  \lang1033 salmon wafted tantalizingly in their direction. Then came the clink\-ing of cutlery on plates, and the first man spoke again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Here, Griphook, Gornuk.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i Goblins\i0 ! Hermione mouthed at Harry, who nodded.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank you,\rdblquote  said the goblins together in English.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So, you three have been on the run how long?\rdblquote  asked a new, mellow, and pleasant voice; it was vaguely familiar to Harry, who pictured a round-bellied, cheerful-faced man.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Six weeks \'85 seven \'85 I forget,\rdblquote  said the tired man. \ldblquote Met up with Griphook in the first couple of days and joined forces with Gornuk not long after. Nice to have a bit of company.\rdblquote  There was a pause, while knives scraped plates and tin mugs were picked up and replaced on the ground. \ldblquote What made you leave, Ted?\rdblquote  contin\-ued the man.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Knew they were coming for me,\rdblquote  replied mellow-voiced Ted, and Harry suddenly knew who he was: Tonks\rquote s father. \ldblquote Heard Death Eaters were in the area last week and decided I\rquote d better run for it. Refused to register as a Muggle-born on principle, see, so I knew it was a matter of time, knew I\rquote d have to leave in the end. My wife should be okay, she\rquote s pure-blood. And then I met Dean here, what, a few days ago, son?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said another voice, and Harry, Ron, and Hermione stared at each other, silent but beside themselves with excitement, sure they recognized the voice of Dean Thomas, their fellow Gryffindor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Muggle-born, eh?\rdblquote  asked the first man.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not sure,\rdblquote  said Dean. \ldblquote My dad left my mum when I was a kid. I\rquote ve got no proof he was a wizard, though.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was silence for a while, except for the sounds of munching; then Ted spoke again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve got to say, Dirk, I\rquote m surprised to run into you. Pleased, but surprised. Word was you\rquote d been caught.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I was,\rdblquote  said Dirk. \ldblquote I was halfway to Azkaban when I made a break for it, Stunned Dawlish, and nicked his broom. It was easier than you\rquote d think; I don\rquote t reckon he\rquote s quite right at the moment. Might be Confunded. If so, I\rquote d like to shake the hand of the witch or wizard who did it, probably saved my life.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was another pause in which the fire crackled and the river rushed on. Then Ted said, \ldblquote And where do you two fit in? I, er, had the impression the goblins were for You-Know-Who, on the whole.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You had a false impression,\rdblquote  said the higher-voiced of the goblins. \ldblquote We take no sides. This is a wizards\rquote  war.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How come you\rquote re in hiding, then?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I deemed it prudent,\rdblquote  said the deeper-voiced goblin. \ldblquote Having refused what I considered an impertinent request, I could see that my personal safety was in jeopardy.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What did they ask you to do?\rdblquote  asked Ted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Duties ill-befitting the dignity of my race,\rdblquote  replied the goblin, his voice rougher and less human as he said it. \ldblquote I am not a house-elf.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What about you, Griphook?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Similar reasons,\rdblquote  said the higher-voiced goblin. \ldblquote Gringotts is no longer under the sole control of my race. I recognize no Wizarding master.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He added something under his breath in Gobbledegook, and Gornuk laughed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s the joke?\rdblquote  asked Dean.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He said,\rdblquote  replied Dirk, \ldblquote that there are things wizards don\rquote t rec\-ognize, either.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a short pause.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t get it,\rdblquote  said Dean.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I had my small revenge before I left,\rdblquote  said Griphook in English.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good man \emdash  goblin, I should say,\rdblquote  amended Ted hastily. \ldblquote Didn\rquote t manage to lock a Death Eater up in one of the old high-security vaults, I suppose?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If I had, the sword would not have helped him break out,\rdblquote  re\-plied Griphook. Gornuk laughed again and even Dirk gave a dry chuckle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dean and I are still missing something here,\rdblquote  said Ted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So is Severus Snape, though he does not know it,\rdblquote  said Griphook, and the two goblins roared with malicious laughter. Inside the tent Harry\rquote s breathing was shallow with excitement: He and Hermione stared at each other, listening as hard as they could.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Didn\rquote t you hear about that, Ted?\rdblquote  asked Dirk. \ldblquote About the kids who tried to steal Gryffindor\rquote s sword out of Snape\rquote s office at Hogwarts?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 An electric current seemed to course through Harry, jangling his every nerve as he stood rooted to the spot.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Never heard a word,\rdblquote  said Ted. \ldblquote Not in the \i Prophet,\i0  was it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hardly,\rdblquote  chortled Dirk. \ldblquote Griphook here told me, he heard about it from Bill Weasley who works for the bank. One of the kids who tried to take the sword was Bill\rquote s younger sister.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry glanced toward Hermione and Ron, both of whom were clutching the Extendable Ears as tightly as lifelines.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She and a couple of friends got into Snape\rquote s office and smashed open the glass case where he was apparently keeping the sword. Snape caught them as they were trying to smuggle it down the staircase.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah, God bless \rquote em,\rdblquote  said Ted. \ldblquote What did they think, that they\rquote d be able to use the sword on You-Know-Who? Or on Snape himself?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, whatever they thought they were going to do with it, Snape decided the sword wasn\rquote t safe where it was,\rdblquote  said Dirk. \ldblquote Couple of days later, once he\rquote d got the say-so from You-Know-Who, I imagine, he sent it down to London to be kept in Gringotts instead.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The goblins started to laugh again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m still not seeing the joke,\rdblquote  said Ted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s a fake,\rdblquote  rasped Griphook.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The sword of Gryffindor!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yes. It is a copy \emdash  an excellent copy, it is true \emdash  but it was Wizard-made. The original was forged centuries ago by goblins and had certain properties only goblin-made armor possesses. Wherever the genuine sword of Gryffindor is, it is not in a vault at Gringotts bank.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I see,\rdblquote  said Ted. \ldblquote And I take it you didn\rquote t bother telling the Death Eaters this?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I saw no reason to trouble them with the information,\rdblquote  said Griphook smugly, and now Ted and Dean joined in Gornuk and Dirk\rquote s laughter.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Inside the tent, Harry closed his eyes, willing someone to ask the question he needed answered, and after a minute that seemed ten, Dean obliged; he was (Harry remembered with a jolt) an ex-boyfriend of Ginny\rquote s too.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What happened to Ginny and the others? The ones who tried to steal it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, they were punished, and cruelly,\rdblquote  said Griphook indif\-ferently.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They\rquote re okay, though?\rdblquote  asked Ted quickly. \ldblquote I mean, the Weasleys don\rquote t need any more of their kids injured, do they?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They suffered no serious injury, as far as I am aware,\rdblquote  said Griphook.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Lucky for them,\rdblquote  said Ted. \ldblquote With Snape\rquote s track record I suppose we should just be glad they\rquote re still alive.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You believe that story, then, do you, Ted?\rdblquote  asked Dirk. \ldblquote You believe Snape killed Dumbledore?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \rquote Course I do,\rdblquote  said Ted. \ldblquote You\rquote re not going to sit there and tell me you think Potter had anything to do with it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hard to know what to believe these days,\rdblquote  muttered Dirk.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I know Harry Potter,\rdblquote  said Dean. \ldblquote And I reckon he\rquote s the real thing \emdash  the Chosen One, or whatever you want to call it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, there\rquote s a lot would like to believe he\rquote s that, son,\rdblquote  said Dirk, \ldblquote me included. But where is he? Run for it, by the looks of things. You\rquote d think, if he knew anything we don\rquote t, or had anything special going for him, he\rquote d be out there now fighting, rallying resistance, instead of hiding. And you know, the \i Prophet\i0  made a pretty good case against him \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The \i Prophet\i0 ?\rdblquote  scoffed Ted. \ldblquote You deserve to be lied to if you\rquote re still reading that muck, Dirk. You want the facts, try the \i Quibbler.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a sudden explosion of choking and retching, plus a good deal of thumping; by the sound of it, Dirk had swallowed a fish bone. At last he spluttered, \ldblquote The \i Quibbler\i0 ? That lunatic rag of Xeno Lovegood\rquote s?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s not so lunatic these days,\rdblquote  said Ted. \ldblquote You want to give it a look. Xeno is printing all the stuff the \i Prophet\rquote s\i0  ignoring, not a single mention of Crumple-Horned Snorkacks in the last issue. How long they\rquote ll let him get away with it, mind, I don\rquote t know. But\lang3081  \lang1033 Xeno says, front page of every issue, that any wizard who\rquote s against You-Know-Who ought to make helping Harry Potter their number-one priority.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hard to help a boy who\rquote s vanished off the face of the earth,\rdblquote  said Dirk.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Listen, the fact that they haven\rquote t caught him yet\rquote s one hell of an achievement,\rdblquote  said Ted. \ldblquote I\rquote d take tips from him gladly; it\rquote s what we\rquote re trying to do, stay free, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, well, you\rquote ve got a point there,\rdblquote  said Dirk heavily. \ldblquote With the whole of the Ministry and all their informers looking for him I\rquote d have expected him to be caught by now. Mind, who\rquote s to say they haven\rquote t already caught and killed him without publicizing it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah, don\rquote t say that, Dirk,\rdblquote  murmured Ted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a long pause filled with more clattering of knives and forks. When they spoke again it was to discuss whether they ought to sleep on the bank or retreat back up the wooded slope. Deciding the trees would give better cover, they extinguished their fire, then clambered back up the incline, their voices fading away.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry, Ron, and Hermione reeled in the Extendable Ears. Harry, who had found the need to remain silent increasingly difficult the longer they eavesdropped, now found himself unable to say more than, \ldblquote Ginny \emdash  the sword \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I know!\rdblquote  said Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She lunged for the tiny beaded bag, this time sinking her arm in it right up to the armpit.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Here \'85 we \'85 are \'85\rdblquote  she said between gritted teeth, and she pulled at something that was evidently in the depths of the bag. Slowly the edge of an ornate picture frame came into sight. Harry hurried to help her. As they lifted the empty portrait of Phineas\lang3081  \lang1033 Nigellus free of Hermione\rquote s bag, she kept her wand pointing at it, ready to cast a spell at any moment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If somebody swapped the real sword for the fake while it was in Dumbledore\rquote s office,\rdblquote  she panted, as they propped the painting against the side of the tent, \ldblquote Phineas Nigellus would have seen it happen, he hangs right beside the case!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Unless he was asleep,\rdblquote  said Harry, but he still held his breath as Hermione knelt down in front of the empty canvas, her wand directed at its center, cleared her throat, then said:\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash  Phineas? Phineas Nigellus?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Nothing happened.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Phineas Nigellus?\rdblquote  said Hermione again. \ldblquote Professor Black? Please could we talk to you? Please?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote Please\rquote  always helps,\rdblquote  said a cold, snide voice, and Phineas Ni\-gellus slid into his portrait. At once, Hermione cried:\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Obscuro\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A black blindfold appeared over Phineas Nigellus\rquote s clever, dark eyes, causing him to bump into the frame and shriek with pain.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What \emdash  how dare \emdash  what are you \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m very sorry, Professor Black,\rdblquote  said Hermione, \ldblquote but it\rquote s a nec\-essary precaution!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Remove this foul addition at once! Remove it, I say! You are ru\-ining a great work of art! Where am I? What is going on?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Never mind where we are,\rdblquote  said Harry, and Phineas Nigellus froze, abandoning his attempts to peel off the painted blindfold.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Can that possibly be the voice of the elusive Mr. Potter?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Maybe,\rdblquote  said Harry, knowing that this would keep Phineas Ni\-gellus\rquote s interest. \ldblquote We\rquote ve got a couple of questions to ask you \emdash  about the sword of Gryffindor.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah,\rdblquote  said Phineas Nigellus, now turning his head this way and that in an effort to catch sight of Harry, \ldblquote yes. That silly girl acted most unwisely there \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Shut up about my sister,\rdblquote  said Ron roughly. Phineas Nigellus raised supercilious eyebrows.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Who else is here?\rdblquote  he asked, turning his head from side to side. \ldblquote Your tone displeases me! The girl and her friends were foolhardy in the extreme. Thieving from the headmaster!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They weren\rquote t thieving,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote That sword isn\rquote t Snape\rquote s.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It belongs to Professor Snape\rquote s school,\rdblquote  said Phineas Nigellus. \ldblquote Exactly what claim did the Weasley girl have upon it? She deserved her punishment, as did the idiot Longbottom and the Lovegood oddity!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Neville is not an idiot and Luna is not an oddity!\rdblquote  said Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where am I?\rdblquote  repeated Phineas Nigellus, starting to wrestle with the blindfold again. \ldblquote Where have you brought me? Why have you removed me from the house of my forebears?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Never mind that! How did Snape punish Ginny, Neville, and Luna?\rdblquote  asked Harry urgently.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Professor\i0  Snape sent them into the Forbidden Forest, to do some work for the oaf, Hagrid.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hagrid\rquote s not an oaf!\rdblquote  said Hermione shrilly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And Snape might\rquote ve thought that was a punishment,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote but Ginny, Neville, and Luna probably had a good laugh with Hagrid. The Forbidden Forest\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 they\rquote ve faced plenty worse than the Forbidden Forest, big deal!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He felt relieved; he had been imagining horrors, the Cruciatus Curse at the very least.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What we really wanted to know, Professor Black, is whether anyone else has, um, taken out the sword at all? Maybe it\rquote s been taken away for cleaning or \emdash  or something?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Phineas Nigellus paused again in his struggles to free his eyes and sniggered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Muggle-borns,\i0\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Goblin-made armor does not require cleaning, simple girl. Goblins\rquote  silver repels mundane dirt, imbibing only that which strengthens it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t call Hermione simple,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I grow weary of contradiction,\rdblquote  said Phineas Nigellus. \ldblquote Perhaps it is time for me to return to the headmaster\rquote s office?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Still blindfolded, he began groping the side of his frame, trying to feel his way out of his picture and back into the one at Hogwarts. Harry had a sudden inspiration.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore! Can\rquote t you bring us Dumbledore?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I beg your pardon?\rdblquote  asked Phineas Nigellus.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor Dumbledore\rquote s portrait \emdash  couldn\rquote t you bring him along, here, into yours?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Phineas Nigellus turned his face in the direction of Harry\rquote s voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Evidently it is not only Muggle-borns who are ignorant, Potter. The portraits of Hogwarts may commune with each other, but they cannot travel outside the castle except to visit a painting of them\-selves hanging elsewhere. Dumbledore cannot come here with me, and after the treatment I have received at your hands, I can assure you that I shall not be making a return visit!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Slightly crestfallen, Harry watched Phineas redouble his attempts to leave his frame.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor Black,\rdblquote  said Hermione, \ldblquote couldn\rquote t you just tell us, \i please,\lang3081\i0  \lang1033 when was the last time the sword was taken out of its case? Before Ginny took it out, I mean?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Phineas snorted impatiently.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I believe that the last time I saw the sword of Gryffindor leave its case was when Professor Dumbledore used it to break open a ring.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione whipped around to look at Harry. Neither of them dared say more in front of Phineas Nigellus, who had at last man\-aged to locate the exit.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, good night to you,\rdblquote  he said a little waspishly, and he began to move out of sight again. Only the edge of his hat brim remained in view when Harry gave a sudden shout.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wait! Have you told Snape you saw this?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Phineas Nigellus stuck his blindfolded head back into the picture.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor Snape has more important things on his mind than the many eccentricities of Albus Dumbledore. \i Good-bye,\i0  Potter!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And with that, he vanished completely, leaving behind him noth\-ing but his murky backdrop.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry!\rdblquote  Hermione cried.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I know!\rdblquote  Harry shouted. Unable to contain himself, he punched the air; it was more than he had dared to hope for. He strode up and down the tent, feeling that he could have run a mile; he did not even feel hungry anymore. Hermione was squashing Phineas Nigellus\rquote s portrait back into the beaded bag; when she had fastened the clasp she threw the bag aside and raised a shining face to Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The sword can destroy Horcruxes! Goblin-made blades imbibe only that which strengthen them \emdash  Harry, that sword\rquote s impreg\-nated with basilisk venom!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And Dumbledore didn\rquote t give it to me because he still needed it, he wanted to use it on the locket \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  and he must have realized they wouldn\rquote t let you have it if he put it in his will \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  so he made a copy \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  and put a fake in the glass case \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  and he left the real one \emdash  where?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They gazed at each other; Harry felt that the answer was dangling invisibly in the air above them, tantalizingly close. Why hadn\rquote t Dum\-bledore told him? Or had he, in fact, told Harry, but Harry had not realized it at the time?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Think!\rdblquote  whispered Hermione. \ldblquote Think! Where would he have left it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not at Hogwarts,\rdblquote  said Harry, resuming his pacing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Somewhere in Hogsmeade?\rdblquote  suggested Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Shrieking Shack?\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Nobody ever goes in there.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But Snape knows how to get in, wouldn\rquote t that be a bit risky?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore trusted Snape,\rdblquote  Harry reminded her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not enough to tell him that he had swapped the swords,\rdblquote  said Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, you\rquote re right!\rdblquote  said Harry, and he felt even more cheered at the thought that Dumbledore had had some reservations, however faint, about Snape\rquote s trustworthiness. \ldblquote So, would he have hidden the sword well away from Hogsmeade, then? What d\rquote you reckon, Ron? Ron?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked around. For one bewildered moment he thought that Ron had left the tent, then realized that Ron was lying in the shadow of a lower bunk, looking stony.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, remembered me, have you?\rdblquote  he said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron snorted as he stared up at the underside of the upper bunk.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You two carry on. Don\rquote t let me spoil your fun.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Perplexed, Harry looked to Hermione for help, but she shook her head, apparently as nonplussed as he was.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s the problem?\rdblquote  asked Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Problem? There\rquote s no problem,\rdblquote  said Ron, still refusing to look at Harry. \ldblquote Not according to you, anyway.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There were several \i plunks\i0  on the canvas over their heads. It had started to rain.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, you\rquote ve obviously got a problem,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Spit it out, will you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron swung his long legs off the bed and sat up. He looked mean, unlike himself.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All right, I\rquote ll spit it out. Don\rquote t expect me to skip up and down the tent because there\rquote s some other damn thing we\rquote ve got to find. Just add it to the list of stuff you don\rquote t know.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t know?\rdblquote  repeated Harry, \ldblquote\i I\lang3081\i0  \lang1033 don\rquote t know?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i Plunk,\i0  \i plunk,\i0  \i plunk.\i0  The rain was falling harder and heavier; it pattered on the leaf-strewn bank all around them and into the river chattering through the dark. Dread doused Harry\rquote s jubilation: Ron was saying exactly what he had suspected and feared him to be thinking.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s not like I\rquote m not having the time of my life here,\rdblquote  said Ron, \ldblquote you know, with my arm mangled and nothing to eat and freezing my backside off every night. I just hoped, you know, after we\rquote d been running round a few weeks, we\rquote d have achieved something.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ron,\rdblquote  Hermione said, but in such a quiet voice that Ron could pretend not to have heard it over the loud tattoo the rain was now beating on the tent.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I thought you knew what you\rquote d signed up for,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I thought I did too.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So what part of it isn\rquote t living up to your expectations?\rdblquote  asked Harry. Anger was coming to his defense now. \ldblquote Did you think we\rquote d be staying in five-star hotels? Finding a Horcrux every other day? Did you think you\rquote d be back to Mummy by Christmas?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We thought you knew what you were doing!\rdblquote  shouted Ron, standing up, and his words pierced Harry like scalding knives. \ldblquote We thought Dumbledore had told you what to do, we thought you had a real plan!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ron!\rdblquote  said Hermione, this time clearly audible over the rain thundering on the tent roof, but again, he ignored her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, sorry to let you down,\rdblquote  said Harry, his voice quite calm even though he felt hollow, inadequate. \ldblquote I\rquote ve been straight with you from the start, I told you everything Dumbledore told me. And in case you haven\rquote t noticed, we\rquote ve found one Horcrux \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, and we\rquote re about as near getting rid of it as we are to finding the rest of them \emdash  nowhere effing near, in other words!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Take off the locket, Ron,\rdblquote  Hermione said, her voice unusually high. \ldblquote Please take it off. You wouldn\rquote t be talking like this if you hadn\rquote t been wearing it all day.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, he would,\rdblquote  said Harry, who did not want excuses made for Ron. \ldblquote D\rquote you think I haven\rquote t noticed the two of you whispering behind my back? D\rquote you think I didn\rquote t guess you were thinking this stuff?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, we weren\rquote t \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t lie!\rdblquote  Ron hurled at her. \ldblquote You said it too, you said you were disappointed, you said you\rquote d thought he had a bit more to go on than \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I didn\rquote t say it like that \emdash  Harry, I didn\rquote t!\rdblquote  she cried.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The rain was pounding the tent, tears were pouring down Hermi\-one\rquote s face, and the excitement of a few minutes before had vanished as if it had never been, a short-lived firework that had flared and died, leaving everything dark, wet, and cold. The sword of Gryffin\-dor was hidden they knew not where, and they were three teenagers in a tent whose only achievement was not, yet, to be dead.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So why are you still here?\rdblquote  Harry asked Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Search me,\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Go home then,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, maybe I will!\rdblquote  shouted Ron, and he took several steps toward Harry, who did not back away. \ldblquote Didn\rquote t you hear what they said about my sister? But you don\rquote t give a rat\rquote s fart, do you, it\rquote s only the Forbidden Forest, Harry \i I\rquote ve-Faced-Worse\i0  Potter doesn\rquote t care what happens to her in here \emdash  well, I do, all right, giant spiders and mental stuff\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I was only saying \emdash  she was with the others, they were with Hagrid \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I get it, you don\rquote t care! And what about the rest of my family, \lquote the Weasleys don\rquote t need another kid injured,\rquote  did you hear that?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not bothered what it meant, though?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ron!\rdblquote  said Hermione, forcing her way between them. \lang3081\ldblquote I \lang1033 don\rquote t think it means anything new has happened, anything we don\rquote t know about; think, Ron, Bill\rquote s already scarred, plenty of people\lang3081  \lang1033 must have seen that George has lost an ear by now, and you\rquote re sup\-posed to be on your deathbed with spattergroit, I\rquote m sure that\rquote s all he meant \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, you\rquote re sure, are you? Right then, well, I won\rquote t bother my\-self about them. It\rquote s all right for you two, isn\rquote t it, with your parents safely out of the way \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My parents are \i dead\i0 !\rdblquote  Harry bellowed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And mine could be going the same way!\rdblquote  yelled Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Then GO!\rdblquote  roared Harry. \ldblquote Go back to them, pretend you\rquote ve got over your spattergroit and Mummy\rquote ll be able to feed you up and \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron made a sudden movement: Harry reacted, but before ei\-ther wand was clear of its owner\rquote s pocket, Hermione had raised her own.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Protego\i0 !\rdblquote  she cried, and an invisible shield expanded between her and Harry on the one side and Ron on the other; all of them were forced backward a few steps by the strength of the spell, and Harry and Ron glared from either side of the transparent barrier as though they were seeing each other clearly for the first time. Harry felt a corrosive hatred toward Ron: Something had broken between them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Leave the Horcrux,\rdblquote  Harry said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron wrenched the chain from over his head and cast the locket into a nearby chair. He turned to Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What are you doing?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What do you mean?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you staying, or what?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote  She looked anguished. \ldblquote Yes \emdash  yes, I\rquote m staying. Ron, we said we\rquote d go with Harry, we said we\rquote d help \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I get it. You choose him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ron, no \emdash  please \emdash  come back, come back!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She was impeded by her own Shield Charm; by the time she had removed it he had already stormed into the night. Harry stood quite still and silent, listening to her sobbing and calling Ron\rquote s name amongst the trees.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 After a few minutes she returned, her sopping hair plastered to her face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s g-g-gone! Disapparated!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She threw herself into a chair, curled up, and started to cry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt dazed. He stooped, picked up the Horcrux, and placed it around his own neck. He dragged blankets off Ron\rquote s bunk and threw them over Hermione. Then he climbed onto his own bed and stared up at the dark canvas roof, listening to the pounding of the rain.\lang3081\par
