When Harry woke the following day it was several sec\-onds before he remembered what had happened. Then he hoped, childishly, that it had been a dream, that Ron was still there and had never left. Yet by turning his head on his pillow he could see Ron\rquote s deserted bunk. It was like a dead body in the way it seemed to draw his eyes. Harry jumped down from his own bed, keeping his eyes averted from Ron\rquote s. Hermione, who was already busy in the kitchen, did not wish Harry good morning, but turned her face away quickly as he went by.\par
\i He\rquote s gone,\i0  Harry told himself. \i He\rquote s gone.\i0  He had to keep think\-ing it as he washed and dressed, as though repetition would dull the shock of it. \i He\rquote s gone and he\rquote s not coming back.\i0  And that was the simple truth of it, Harry knew, because their protective enchant\-ments meant that it would be impossible, once they vacated this spot, for Ron to find them again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He and Hermione ate breakfast in silence. Hermione\rquote s eyes were\lang3081  \lang1033 puffy and red; she looked as if she had not slept. They packed up their things, Hermione dawdling. Harry knew why she wanted to spin out their time on the riverbank; several times he saw her look up eagerly, and he was sure she had deluded herself into thinking that she heard footsteps through the heavy rain, but no red-haired figure appeared between the trees. Every time Harry imitated her, looked around (for he could not help hoping a little, himself) and saw nothing but rain-swept woods, another little parcel of fury exploded inside him. He could hear Ron saying, \ldblquote\i We thought you knew what you were doing\i0 !\rdblquote , and he resumed packing with a hard knot in the pit of his stomach.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The muddy river beside them was rising rapidly and would soon spill over onto their bank. They had lingered a good hour after they would usually have departed their campsite. Finally having entirely repacked the beaded bag three times, Hermione seemed unable to find any more reasons to delay: She and Harry grasped hands and Disapparated, reappearing on a windswept heather-covered hillside.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The instant they arrived, Hermione dropped Harry\rquote s hand and walked away from him, finally sitting down on a large rock, her face on her knees, shaking with what he knew were sobs. He watched her, supposing that he ought to go and comfort her, but something kept him rooted to the spot. Everything inside him felt cold and tight: Again he saw the contemptuous expression on Ron\rquote s face. Harry strode off through the heather, walking in a large circle with the distraught Hermione at its center, casting the spells she usually performed to ensure their protection.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They did not discuss Ron at all over the next few days. Harry was determined never to mention his name again, and Hermione seemed\lang3081  \lang1033 to know that it was no use forcing the issue, although sometimes at night when she thought he was sleeping, he would hear her crying. Meanwhile Harry had started bringing out the Marauder\rquote s Map and examining it by wandlight. He was waiting for the moment when Ron\rquote s labeled dot would reappear in the corridors of Hogwarts, proving that he had returned to the comfortable castle, protected by his status of pureblood. However, Ron did not appear on the map, and after a while Harry found himself taking it out simply to stare at Ginny\rquote s name in the girls\rquote  dormitory, wondering whether the intensity with which he gazed at it might break into her sleep, that she would somehow know he was thinking about her, hoping that she was all right.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 By day, they devoted themselves to trying to determine the pos\-sible locations of Gryffindor\rquote s sword, but the more they talked about the places in which Dumbledore might have hidden it, the more des\-perate and far-fetched their speculation became. Cudgel his brains though he might, Harry could not remember Dumbledore ever mentioning a place in which he might hide something. There were moments when he did not know whether he was angrier with Ron or with Dumbledore. \i We thought you knew what you were doing. \'85\i0  \i We thought Dumbledore had told you what to do. \'85\i0  \i We thought you had a real plan\i0 !\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He could not hide it from himself: Ron had been right. Dumble\-dore had left him with virtually nothing. They had discovered one Horcrux, but they had no means of destroying it: The others were as unattainable as they had ever been. Hopelessness threatened to engulf him. He was staggered now to think of his own presumption in accepting his friends\rquote  offers to accompany him on this meander\-ing, pointless journey. He knew nothing, he had no ideas, and he\lang3081  \lang1033 was constantly, painfully on the alert for any indication that Her\-mione too was about to tell him that she had had enough, that she was leaving.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were spending many evenings in near silence, and Hermi\-one took to bringing out Phineas Nigellus\rquote s portrait and propping it up in a chair, as though he might fill part of the gaping hole left by Ron\rquote s departure. Despite his previous assertion that he would never visit them again, Phineas Nigellus did not seem able to re\-sist the chance to find out more about what Harry was up to, and consented to reappear, blindfolded, every few days or so. Harry was even glad to see him, because he was company, albeit of a snide and taunting kind. They relished any news about what was happening at Hogwarts, though Phineas Nigellus was not an ideal informer. He venerated Snape, the first Slytherin headmaster since he himself had controlled the school, and they had to be careful not to criticize or ask impertinent questions about Snape, or Phineas Nigellus would instantly leave his painting.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 However, he did let drop certain snippets. Snape seemed to be facing a constant, low level of mutiny from a hard core of students. Ginny had been banned from going into Hogsmeade. Snape had reinstated Umbridge\rquote s old decree forbidding gatherings of three or more students or any unofficial student societies.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 From all of these things, Harry deduced that Ginny, and prob\-ably Neville and Luna along with her, had been doing their best to continue Dumbledore\rquote s Army. This scant news made Harry want to see Ginny so badly it felt like a stomachache; but it also made him think of Ron again, and of Dumbledore, and of Hogwarts itself, which he missed nearly as much as his ex-girlfriend. Indeed, as Phineas Nigellus talked about Snape\rquote s crackdown, Harry expe\-rienced a split second of madness when he imagined simply going back to school to join the destabilization of Snape\rquote s regime: Be\-ing fed, and having a soft bed, and other people being in charge, seemed the most wonderful prospect in the world at that moment. But then he remembered that he was Undesirable Number One, that there was a ten-thousand-Galleon price on his head, and that to walk into Hogwarts these days was just as dangerous as walking into the Ministry of Magic. Indeed, Phineas Nigellus inadvertently emphasized this fact by slipping in leading questions about Harry and Hermione\rquote s whereabouts. Hermione shoved him back inside the beaded bag every time he did this, and Phineas Nigellus invari\-ably refused to reappear for several days after these unceremonious good-byes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The weather grew colder and colder. They did not dare remain in any one area too long, so rather than staying in the south of Eng\-land, where a hard ground frost was the worst of their worries, they continued to meander up and down the country, braving a moun\-tainside, where sleet pounded the tent; a wide, flat marsh, where the tent was flooded with chill water; and a tiny island in the middle of a Scottish loch, where snow half buried the tent in the night.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They had already spotted Christmas trees twinkling from several sitting room windows before there came an evening when Harry resolved to suggest, again, what seemed to him the only unexplored avenue left to them. They had just eaten an unusually good meal: Hermione had been to a supermarket under the Invisibility Cloak (scrupulously dropping the money into an open till as she left), and Harry thought that she might be more persuadable than usual on a stomach full of spaghetti Bolognese and tinned pears. He had also had the foresight to suggest that they take a few hours\rquote  break from\lang3081  \lang1033 wearing the Horcrux, which was hanging over the end of the bunk beside him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hermione?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hmm?\rdblquote  She was curled up in one of the sagging armchairs with \i The Tales of\lang3081  \lang1033 Beedle the Bard.\i0  He could not imagine how much more she could get out of the book, which was not, after all, very long; but evidently she was still deciphering something in it, because \i Spellman\rquote s Syllabary\i0  lay open on the arm of the chair.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry cleared his throat. He felt exactly as he had done on the occasion, several years previously, when he had asked Professor Mc\-Gonagall whether he could go into Hogsmeade, despite the fact that he had not persuaded the Dursleys to sign his permission slip.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hermione, I\rquote ve been thinking, and \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, could you help me with something?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Apparently she had not been listening to him. She leaned forward and held out \i The Tales of\lang3081  \lang1033 Beedle the Bard.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Look at that symbol,\rdblquote  she said, pointing to the top of a page. Above what Harry assumed was the title of the story (being unable to read runes, he could not be sure), there was a picture of what looked like a triangular eye, its pupil crossed with a vertical line.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I never took Ancient Runes, Hermione.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I know that, but it isn\rquote t a rune and it\rquote s not in the syllabary, either. All along I thought it was a picture of an eye, but I don\rquote t think it is! It\rquote s been inked in, look, somebody\rquote s drawn it there, it isn\rquote t really part of the book. Think, have you ever seen it before?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No \'85 No, wait a moment.\rdblquote  Harry looked closer. \ldblquote Isn\rquote t it the same symbol Luna\rquote s dad was wearing round his neck?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, that\rquote s what I thought too!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Then it\rquote s Grindelwald\rquote s mark.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She stared at him, openmouthed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i What\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Krum told me \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He recounted the story that Viktor Krum had told him at the wedding. Hermione looked astonished.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Grindelwald\rquote s \i0 mark?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She looked from Harry to the weird symbol and back again. \ldblquote I\rquote ve never heard that Grindelwald had a mark. There\rquote s no mention of it in anything I\rquote ve ever read about him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, like I say, Krum reckoned that symbol was carved on a wall at Durmstrang, and Grindelwald put it there.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She fell back into the old armchair, frowning.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s very odd. If it\rquote s a symbol of Dark Magic, what\rquote s it doing in a book of children\rquote s stories?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, it is weird,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote And you\rquote d think Scrimgeour would have recognized it. He was Minister, he ought to have been expert on Dark stuff.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I know. \'85 Perhaps he thought it was an eye, just like I did. All the other stories have little pictures over the titles.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She did not speak, but continued to pore over the strange mark. Harry tried again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hermione?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hmm?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve been thinking. I \emdash  I want to go to Godric\rquote s Hollow.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She looked up at him, but her eyes were unfocused, and he was sure she was still thinking about the mysterious mark on the book.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote Yes, I\rquote ve been wondering that too. I really think we\rquote ll have to.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did you hear me right?\rdblquote  he asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course I did. You want to go to Godric\rquote s Hollow. I agree, I think we should. I mean, I can\rquote t think of anywhere else it could be either. It\rquote ll be dangerous, but the more I think about it, the more likely it seems it\rquote s there.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash  \i what\rquote s\i0  there?\rdblquote  asked Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 At that, she looked just as bewildered as he felt.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, the sword, Harry! Dumbledore must have known you\rquote d want to go back there, and I mean, Godric\rquote s Hollow is Godric Gryffindor\rquote s birthplace \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Really? Gryffindor came from Godric\rquote s Hollow?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, did you ever even open \i A History of Magic\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Erm,\rdblquote  he said, smiling for what felt like the first time in months: The muscles in his face felt oddly stiff. \ldblquote I might\rquote ve opened it, you know, when I bought it\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 just the once. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, as the village is named after him I\rquote d have thought you might have made the connection,\rdblquote  said Hermione. She sounded much more like her old self than she had done of late; Harry half expected her to announce that she was off to the library. \ldblquote There\rquote s a bit about the village in \i A History of Magic,\i0  wait\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She opened the beaded bag and rummaged for a while, finally extracting her copy of their old school textbook, \i A History of Magic \i0 by Bathilda Bagshot, which she thumbed through until finding the page she wanted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i Upon the signature of the International Statute of Secrecy in 1689, wizards went into hiding for good. It was natural, perhaps, that they formed their own small communities within a community. Many small villages and hamlets attracted several magical families, who banded together for mutual support and protection. The villages of Tinworth\lang3081\i0  \lang1033\i in Cornwall, Upper Flagley in Yorkshire, and Ottery St. Catchpole on the south coast of England were notable homes to knots of\lang3081  \lang1033 Wizarding families who lived alongside tolerant and sometimes Confunded Mug\-gles. Most celebrated of these half-magical dwelling places is, perhaps, Godric\rquote s Hollow, the West Country village where the great wizard Godric Gryffindor was born, and where Bowman Wright, Wizard\-ing smith, forged the first Golden Snitch. The graveyard is full of the names of ancient magical families, and this accounts, no doubt, for the stories of\lang3081  \lang1033 hauntings that have dogged the little church beside it for many centuries.\i0\rquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You and your parents aren\rquote t mentioned,\rdblquote  Hermione said, closing the book, \ldblquote because Professor Bagshot doesn\rquote t cover anything later than the end of the nineteenth century. But you see? Godric\rquote s Hol\-low, Godric Gryffindor, Gryffindor\rquote s sword; don\rquote t you think Dum\-bledore would have expected you to make the connection?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yeah \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry did not want to admit that he had not been thinking about the sword at all when he suggested they go to Godric\rquote s Hol\-low. For him, the lure of the village lay in his parents\rquote  graves, the house where he had narrowly escaped death, and in the person of Bathilda Bagshot.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Remember what Muriel said?\rdblquote  he asked eventually.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Who?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You know,\rdblquote  he hesitated: He did not want to say Ron\rquote s name. \ldblquote Ginny\rquote s great-aunt. At the wedding. The one who said you had skinny ankles.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh,\rdblquote  said Hermione. It was a sticky moment: Harry knew that she had sensed Ron\rquote s name in the offing. He rushed on:\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She said Bathilda Bagshot still lives in Godric\rquote s Hollow.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bathilda Bagshot,\rdblquote  murmured Hermione, running her index finger over Bathilda\rquote s embossed name on the front cover of \i A His\-tory of Magic.\i0  \ldblquote Well, I suppose \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She gasped so dramatically that Harry\rquote s insides turned over; he drew his wand, looking around at the entrance, half expecting to see a hand forcing its way through the entrance flap, but there was nothing there.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  he said, half angry, half relieved. \ldblquote What did you do that for? I thought you\rquote d seen a Death Eater unzipping the tent, at least \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, \i what if Bathilda\rquote s got the sword\i0 ? What if Dumbledore entrusted it to her?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry considered this possibility. Bathilda would be an extremely old woman by now, and according to Muriel, she was \ldblquote gaga.\rdblquote  Was it likely that Dumbledore would have hidden the sword of Gryffindor with her? If so, Harry felt that Dumbledore had left a great deal to chance: Dumbledore had never revealed that he had replaced the sword with a fake, nor had he so much as mentioned a friendship with Bathilda. Now, however, was not the moment to cast doubt on Hermione\rquote s theory, not when she was so surprisingly willing to fall in with Harry\rquote s dearest wish.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, he might have done! So, are we going to go to Godric\rquote s Hollow?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, but we\rquote ll have to think it through carefully, Harry.\rdblquote  She was sitting up now, and Harry could tell that the prospect of hav\-ing a plan again had lifted her mood as much as his. \ldblquote We\rquote ll need to practice Disapparating together under the Invisibility Cloak for a start, and perhaps Disillusionment Charms would be sensible too, unless you think we should go the whole hog and use Polyjuice\lang3081  \lang1033 Potion? In that case we\rquote ll need to collect hair from somebody. I actually think we\rquote d better do that, Harry, the thicker our disguises the better. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry let her talk, nodding and agreeing whenever there was a pause, but his mind had left the conversation. For the first time since he had discovered that the sword in Gringotts was a fake, he felt excited.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was about to go home, about to return to the place where he had had a family. It was in Godric\rquote s Hollow that, but for Voldemort, he would have grown up and spent every school holiday. He could have invited friends to his house. \'85 He might even have had broth\-ers and sisters. \'85 It would have been his mother who had made his seventeenth birthday cake. The life he had lost had hardly ever seemed so real to him as at this moment, when he knew he was about to see the place where it had been taken from him. After Hermione had gone to bed that night, Harry quietly extracted his rucksack from Hermione\rquote s beaded bag, and from inside it, the photograph album Hagrid had given him so long ago. For the first time in months, he perused the old pictures of his parents, smiling and waving up at him from the images, which were all he had left of them now.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry would gladly have set out for Godric\rquote s Hollow the follow\-ing day, but Hermione had other ideas. Convinced as she was that Voldemort would expect Harry to return to the scene of his parents\rquote  deaths, she was determined that they would set off only after they had ensured that they had the best disguises possible. It was therefore a full week later \emdash  once they had surreptitiously obtained hairs from innocent Muggles who were Christmas shopping, and had prac\-ticed Apparating and Disapparating while underneath the Invisibility Cloak together \emdash  that Hermione agreed to make the journey.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were to Apparate to the village under cover of darkness, so it was late afternoon when they finally swallowed Polyjuice Po\-tion, Harry transforming into a balding, middle-aged Muggle man, Hermione into his small and rather mousy wife. The beaded bag containing all of their possessions (apart from the Horcrux, which Harry was wearing around his neck) was tucked into an inside pocket of Hermione\rquote s buttoned-up coat. Harry lowered the Invis\-ibility Cloak over them, then they turned into the suffocating dark\-ness once again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Heart beating in his throat, Harry opened his eyes. They were standing hand in hand in a snowy lane under a dark blue sky, in which the night\rquote s first stars were already glimmering feebly. Cot\-tages stood on either side of the narrow road, Christmas decorations twinkling in their windows. A short way ahead of them, a glow of golden streetlights indicated the center of the village.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All this snow!\rdblquote  Hermione whispered beneath the cloak. \ldblquote Why didn\rquote t we think of snow? After all our precautions, we\rquote ll leave prints! We\rquote ll just have to get rid of them \emdash  you go in front, I\rquote ll do it \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry did not want to enter the village like a pantomime horse, trying to keep themselves concealed while magically covering their traces.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let\rquote s take off the Cloak,\rdblquote  said Harry, and when she looked frightened, \ldblquote Oh, come on, we don\rquote t look like us and there\rquote s no one around.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He stowed the Cloak under his jacket and they made their way forward unhampered, the icy air stinging their faces as they passed more cottages: Any one of them might have been the one in which James and Lily had once lived or where Bathilda lived now. Harry gazed at the front doors, their snow-burdened roofs, and their front\lang3081  \lang1033 porches, wondering whether he remembered any of them, knowing deep inside that it was impossible, that he had been little more than a year old when he had left this place forever. He was not even sure whether he would be able to see the cottage at all; he did not know what happened when the subjects of a Fidelius Charm died. Then the little lane along which they were walking curved to the left and the heart of the village, a small square, was revealed to them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Strung all around with colored lights, there was what looked like a war memorial in the middle, partly obscured by a windblown Christmas tree. There were several shops, a post office, a pub, and a little church whose stained-glass windows were glowing jewel-bright across the square.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The snow here had become impacted: It was hard and slippery where people had trodden on it all day. Villagers were crisscrossing in front of them, their figures briefly illuminated by streetlamps. They heard a snatch of laughter and pop music as the pub door opened and closed; then they heard a carol start up inside the little church.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, I think it\rquote s Christmas Eve!\rdblquote  said Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He had lost track of the date; they had not seen a newspaper for weeks.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m sure it is,\rdblquote  said Hermione, her eyes upon the church. \ldblquote They \'85 they\rquote ll be in there, won\rquote t they? Your mum and dad? I can see the graveyard behind it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt a thrill of something that was beyond excitement, more like fear. Now that he was so near, he wondered whether he wanted to see after all. Perhaps Hermione knew how he was feel\-ing, because she reached for his hand and took the lead for the first\lang3081  \lang1033 time, pulling him forward. Halfway across the square, however, she stopped dead.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, look!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She was pointing at the war memorial. As they had passed it, it had transformed. Instead of an obelisk covered in names, there was a statue of three people: a man with untidy hair and glasses, a woman with long hair and a kind, pretty face, and a baby boy sit\-ting in his mother\rquote s arms. Snow lay upon all their heads, like fluffy white caps.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry drew closer, gazing up into his parents\rquote  faces. He had never imagined that there would be a statue. \'85 How strange it was to see himself represented in stone, a happy baby without a scar on his forehead. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote C\rquote mon,\rdblquote  said Harry, when he had looked his fill, and they turned again toward the church. As they crossed the road, he glanced over his shoulder; the statue had turned back into the war memorial.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The singing grew louder as they approached the church. It made Harry\rquote s throat constrict, it reminded him so forcefully of Hogwarts, of Peeves bellowing rude versions of carols from inside suits of ar\-mor, of the Great Hall\rquote s twelve Christmas trees, of Dumbledore wearing a bonnet he had won in a cracker, of Ron in a hand-knitted sweater. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a kissing gate at the entrance to the graveyard. Hermi\-one pushed it open as quietly as possible and they edged through it. On either side of the slippery path to the church doors, the snow lay deep and untouched. They moved off through the snow, carv\-ing deep trenches behind them as they walked around the building, keeping to the shadows beneath the brilliant windows.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Behind the church, row upon row of snowy tombstones pro\-truded from a blanket of pale blue that was flecked with dazzling red, gold, and green wherever the reflections from the stained glass hit the snow. Keeping his hand closed tightly on the wand in his jacket pocket, Harry moved toward the nearest grave.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Look at this, it\rquote s an Abbott, could be some long-lost relation of Hannah\rquote s!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Keep your voice down,\rdblquote  Hermione begged him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They waded deeper and deeper into the graveyard, gouging dark tracks into the snow behind them, stooping to peer at the words on old headstones, every now and then squinting into the surrounding darkness to make absolutely sure that they were unaccompanied.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, here!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione was two rows of tombstones away; he had to wade back to her, his heart positively banging in his chest.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is it \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, but look!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She pointed to the dark stone. Harry stooped down and saw, upon the frozen, lichen-spotted granite, the words KENDRA DUM\-BLEDORE and, a short way below her dates of birth and death, AND HER DAUGHTER ARIANA. There was also a quotation:\par
\par
\pard\qc\i Where your treasure is, there will\lang3081  \lang1033 your heart be also.\lang3081\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\i0\par
\lang1033 So Rita Skeeter and Muriel had got some of their facts right. The Dumbledore family had indeed lived here, and part of it had died here.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Seeing the grave was worse than hearing about it. Harry could not help thinking that he and Dumbledore both had deep roots in this graveyard, and that Dumbledore ought to have told him so, yet he\lang3081  \lang1033 had never thought to share the connection. They could have visited the place together; for a moment Harry imagined coming here with Dumbledore, of what a bond that would have been, of how much it would have meant to him. But it seemed that to Dumbledore, the fact that their families lay side by side in the same graveyard had been an unimportant coincidence, irrelevant, perhaps, to the job he wanted Harry to do.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione was looking at Harry, and he was glad that his face was hidden in shadow. He read the words on the tombstone again. \i Where your treasure is, there will your heart be also.\i0  He did not understand what these words meant. Surely Dumbledore had chosen them, as the eldest member of the family once his mother had died.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you sure he never mentioned \emdash  ?\rdblquote  Hermione began.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry curtly, then, \ldblquote let\rquote s keep looking,\rdblquote  and he turned away, wishing he had not seen the stone: He did not want his excited trepidation tainted with resentment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Here!\rdblquote  cried Hermione again a few moments later from out of the darkness. \ldblquote Oh no, sorry! I thought it said Potter.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She was rubbing at a crumbling, mossy stone, gazing down at it, a little frown on her face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, come back a moment.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He did not want to be sidetracked again, and only grudgingly made his way back through the snow toward her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Look at this!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The grave was extremely old, weathered so that Harry could hardly make out the name. Hermione showed him the symbol be\-neath it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, that\rquote s the mark in the book!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He peered at the place she indicated: The stone was so worn that it was hard to make out what was engraved there, though there did seem to be a triangular mark beneath the nearly illegible name.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah \'85 it could be. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione lit her wand and pointed it at the name on the headstone.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It says Ig \emdash  Ignotus, I think. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m going to keep looking for my parents, all right?\rdblquote  Harry told her, a slight edge to his voice, and he set off again, leaving her crouched beside the old grave.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Every now and then he recognized a surname that, like Abbott, he had met at Hogwarts. Sometimes there were several generations of the same Wizarding family represented in the graveyard: Harry could tell from the dates that it had either died out, or the cur\-rent members had moved away from Godric\rquote s Hollow. Deeper and deeper amongst the graves he went, and every time he reached a new headstone he felt a little lurch of apprehension and anticipation.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The darkness and the silence seemed to become, all of a sudden, much deeper. Harry looked around, worried, thinking of demen\-tors, then realized that the carols had finished, that the chatter and flurry of churchgoers were fading away as they made their way back into the square. Somebody inside the church had just turned off the lights.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Then Hermione\rquote s voice came out of the blackness for the third time, sharp and clear from a few yards away.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, they\rquote re here \'85 right here.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And he knew by her tone that it was his mother and father this time: He moved toward her, feeling as if something heavy were pressing on his chest, the same sensation he had had right after\lang3081  \lang1033 Dumbledore had died, a grief that had actually weighed on his heart and lungs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The headstone was only two rows behind Kendra and Ariana\rquote s. It was made of white marble, just like Dumbledore\rquote s tomb, and this made it easy to read, as it seemed to shine in the dark. Harry did not need to kneel or even approach very close to it to make out the words engraved upon it.\par
