Now approaching his eighteenth birthday, Dumbledore left Hogwarts in a blaze of glory \emdash  Head Boy, Prefect, Winner of the Barnabus Finkley Prize for Exceptional Spell-Casting, British Youth Representative to the Wizengamot, Gold Medal-Winner for Ground-Breaking Contribution to the International Alchemical Conference in Cairo. Dumbledore intended, next, to take a Grand Tour with Elphias \ldblquote Dogbreath\rdblquote  Doge, the dim-witted but devoted sidekick he had picked up at school.\par
The two young men were staying at the Leaky Cauldron in London, preparing to depart for Greece the following morning, when an owl arrived bearing news of Dumbledore\rquote s mother\rquote s\lang3081  \lang1033 death. \ldblquote Dogbreath\rdblquote  Doge, who refused to be interviewed for this book, has given the public his own sentimental version of what happened next. He represents Kendra\rquote s death as a tragic blow, and Dumbledore\rquote s decision to give up his expedition as an act of noble self-sacrifice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Certainly Dumbledore returned to Godric\rquote s Hollow at once, supposedly to \ldblquote care\rdblquote  for his younger brother and sister. But how much care did he actually give them?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He were a head case, that Aberforth,\rdblquote  says Enid Smeek, whose family lived on the outskirts of Godric\rquote s Hollow at that time. \ldblquote Ran wild. \rquote Course, with his mum and dad gone you\rquote d have felt sorry for him, only he kept chucking goat dung at my head. I don\rquote t think Albus was fussed about him, I never saw them together, anyway.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 So what was Albus doing, if not comforting his wild young brother? The answer, it seems, is ensuring the continued im\-prisonment of his sister. For, though her first jailer had died, there was no change in the pitiful condition of Ariana Dumble\-dore. Her very existence continued to be known only to those few outsiders who, like \ldblquote Dogbreath\rdblquote  Doge, could be counted upon to believe in the story of her \ldblquote ill health.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Another such easily satisfied friend of the family was Bathilda Bagshot, the celebrated magical historian who has lived in Godric\rquote s Hollow for many years. Kendra, of course, had rebuffed Bathilda when she first attempted to welcome the family to the village. Several years later, however, the author sent an owl to Albus at Hogwarts, having been favorably im\-pressed by his paper on trans-species transformation in \i Trans\-figuration Today.\i0  This initial contact led to acquaintance with\lang3081  \lang1033 the entire Dumbledore family. At the time of Kendra\rquote s death, Bathilda was the only person in Godric\rquote s Hollow who was on speaking terms with Dumbledore\rquote s mother.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Unfortunately, the brilliance that Bathilda exhibited earlier in her life has now dimmed. \ldblquote The fire\rquote s lit, but the cauldron\rquote s empty,\rdblquote  as Ivor Dillonsby put it to me, or, in Enid Smeek\rquote s slightly earthier phrase, \ldblquote She\rquote s nutty as squirrel poo.\rdblquote  Never\-theless, a combination of tried-and-tested reporting techniques enabled me to extract enough nuggets of hard fact to string together the whole scandalous story.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Like the rest of the Wizarding world, Bathilda puts Kendra\rquote s premature death down to a backfiring charm, a story repeated by Albus and Aberforth in later years. Bathilda also parrots the family line on Ariana, calling her \ldblquote frail\rdblquote  and \ldblquote delicate.\rdblquote  On one subject, however, Bathilda is well worth the effort I put into procuring Veritaserum, for she, and she alone, knows the full story of the best-kept secret of Albus Dumbledore\rquote s life. Now revealed for the first time, it calls into question everything that his admirers believed of Dumbledore: his supposed hatred of the Dark Arts, his opposition to the oppression of Muggles, even his devotion to his own family.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The very same summer that Dumbledore went home to Godric\rquote s Hollow, now an orphan and head of the family, Bathilda Bagshot agreed to accept into her home her great-nephew, Gellert Grindelwald.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The name of Grindelwald is justly famous: In a list of Most Dangerous Dark Wizards of All Time, he would miss out on the top spot only because You-Know-Who arrived, a genera\-tion later, to steal his crown. As Grindelwald never extended\lang3081  \lang1033 his campaign of terror to Britain, however, the details of his rise to power are not widely known here.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Educated at Durmstrang, a school famous even then for its unfortunate tolerance of the Dark Arts, Grindelwald showed himself quite as precociously brilliant as Dumbledore. Rather than channel his abilities into the attainment of awards and prizes, however, Gellert Grindelwald devoted himself to other pursuits. At sixteen years old, even Durmstrang felt it could no longer turn a blind eye to the twisted experiments of Gellert Grindelwald, and he was expelled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hitherto, all that has been known of Grindelwald\rquote s next movements is that he \ldblquote traveled abroad for some months.\rdblquote  It can now be revealed that Grindelwald chose to visit his great-aunt in Godric\rquote s Hollow, and that there, intensely shocking though it will be for many to hear it, he struck up a close friendship with none other than Albus Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He seemed a charming boy to me,\rdblquote  babbles Bathilda, \ldblquote whatever he became later. Naturally I introduced him to poor Albus, who was missing the company of lads his own age. The boys took to each other at once.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
