Astonished and appalled though his many admirers will be, this letter constitutes proof that Albus Dumbledore once dreamed of overthrowing the Statute of Secrecy and establish\-ing Wizard rule over Muggles. What a blow for those who have always portrayed Dumbledore as the Muggle-borns\rquote  greatest champion! How hollow those speeches promoting Muggle rights seem in the light of this damning new evidence! How despicable does Albus Dumbledore appear, busy plotting his\lang3081  \lang1033 rise to power when he should have been mourning his mother and caring for his sister!\lang3081\par
\lang1033 No doubt those determined to keep Dumbledore on his crumbling pedestal will bleat that he did not, after all, put his plans into action, that he must have suffered a change of heart, that he came to his senses. However, the truth seems altogether more shocking.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Barely two months into their great new friendship, Dum\-bledore and Grindelwald parted, never to see each other again until they met for their legendary duel (for more, see chapter 22). What caused this abrupt rupture? \i Had\lang3081\i0  \lang1033 Dumbledore come to his senses? Had he told Grindelwald he wanted no more part in his plans? Alas, no.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It was poor little Ariana dying, I think, that did it,\rdblquote  says Bathilda. \ldblquote It came as an awful shock. Gellert was there in the house when it happened, and he came back to my house all of a dither, told me he wanted to go home the next day. Terribly distressed, you know. So I arranged a Portkey and that was the last I saw of him.\lang3081\par
