\lang1033 This dreadful coffin-side brawl, known only to those few who attended Ariana Dumbledore\rquote s funeral, raises several ques\-tions. Why exactly did Aberforth Dumbledore blame Albus for his sister\rquote s death? Was it, as \ldblquote Batty\rdblquote  pretends, a mere effu\-sion of grief? Or could there have been some more concrete reason for his fury? Grindelwald, expelled from Durmstrang for near-fatal attacks upon fellow students, fled the country hours after the girl\rquote s death, and Albus (out of shame or fear?) never saw him again, not until forced to do so by the pleas of the Wizarding world.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Neither Dumbledore nor Grindelwald ever seems to have referred to this brief boyhood friendship in later life. How\-ever, there can be no doubt that Dumbledore delayed, for some five years of turmoil, fatalities, and disappearances, his attack upon Gellert Grindelwald. Was it lingering affection for the man or fear of exposure as his once best friend that caused Dumbledore to hesitate? Was it only reluctantly that Dumbledore set out to capture the man he was once so de\-lighted he had met?\lang3081\par
