Harry had not expected Hermione\rquote s anger to abate over-night, and was therefore unsurprised that she com\-municated mainly by dirty looks and pointed silences the next morning. Ron responded by maintaining an unnaturally somber demeanor in her presence as an outward sign of continuing re\-morse. In fact, when all three of them were together Harry felt like the only non-mourner at a poorly attended funeral. During those few moments he spent alone with Harry, however (collect\-ing water and searching the undergrowth for mushrooms), Ron became shamelessly cheery.\par
\ldblquote Someone helped us,\rdblquote  he kept saying. \ldblquote Someone sent that doe. Someone\rquote s on our side. One Horcrux down, mate!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Bolstered by the destruction of the locket, they set to debating the possible locations of the other Horcruxes, and even though they had discussed the matter so often before, Harry felt optimistic, cer\-tain that more breakthroughs would succeed the first. Hermione\rquote s\lang3081  \lang1033 sulkiness could not mar his buoyant spirits: The sudden upswing in their fortunes, the appearance of the mysterious doe, the recovery of Gryffindor\rquote s sword, and above all, Ron\rquote s return, made Harry so happy that it was quite difficult to maintain a straight face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Late in the afternoon he and Ron escaped Hermione\rquote s baleful presence again, and under the pretense of scouring the bare hedges for nonexistent blackberries, they continued their ongoing exchange of news. Harry had finally managed to tell Ron the whole story of his and Hermione\rquote s various wanderings, right up to the full story of what had happened at Godric\rquote s Hollow; Ron was now filling Harry in on everything he had discovered about the wider Wizard\-ing world during his weeks away.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 and how did you find out about the Taboo?\rdblquote  he asked Harry after explaining the many desperate attempts of Muggle-borns to evade the Ministry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The what?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You and Hermione have stopped saying You-Know-Who\rquote s name!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, yeah. Well, it\rquote s just a bad habit we\rquote ve slipped into,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote But I haven\rquote t got a problem calling him \lang3081 V \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote NO!\rdblquote  roared Ron, causing Harry to jump into the hedge and Hermione (nose buried in a book at the tent entrance) to scowl over at them. \ldblquote Sorry,\rdblquote  said Ron, wrenching Harry back out of the brambles, \ldblquote but the name\rquote s been jinxed, Harry, that\rquote s how they track people! Using his name breaks protective enchantments, it causes some kind of magical disturbance \emdash  it\rquote s how they found us in Tot\-tenham Court Road!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because we used his \i name\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Exactly! You\rquote ve got to give them credit, it makes sense. It was\lang3081  \lang1033 only people who were serious about standing up to him, like Dum\-bledore, who ever dared use it. Now they\rquote ve put a Taboo on it, any\-one who says it is trackable \emdash  quick-and-easy way to find Order members! They nearly got Kingsley \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re kidding?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, a bunch of Death Eaters cornered him, Bill said, but he fought his way out. He\rquote s on the run now, just like us.\rdblquote  Ron scratched his chin thoughtfully with the end of his wand. \ldblquote You don\rquote t reckon Kingsley could have sent that doe?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote His Patronus is a lynx, we saw it at the wedding, remember?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yeah \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They moved farther along the hedge, away from the tent and Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry \'85 you don\rquote t reckon it could\rquote ve been Dumbledore?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore what?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron looked a little embarrassed, but said in a low voice, \ldblquote Dum\-bledore \'85 the doe? I mean,\rdblquote  Ron was watching Harry out of the corners of his eyes, \ldblquote he had the real sword last, didn\rquote t he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry did not laugh at Ron, because he understood too well the longing behind the question. The idea that Dumbledore had man\-aged to come back to them, that he was watching over them, would have been inexpressibly comforting. He shook his head.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore\rquote s dead,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote I saw it happen, I saw the body. He\rquote s definitely gone. Anyway, his Patronus was a phoenix, not a doe.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Patronuses can change, though, can\rquote t they?\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Tonks\rquote s changed, didn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
