\lang1033\ldblquote You only agreed to try and get back in her good books.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All\rquote s fair in love and war,\rdblquote  said Ron brightly, \ldblquote and this is a bit of both. Cheer up, it\rquote s the Christmas holidays, Luna\rquote ll be home!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They had an excellent view of the village of Ottery St. Catchpole from the breezy hillside to which they Disapparated next morning. From their high vantage point the village looked like a collection of toy houses in the great slanting shafts of sunlight stretching to earth in the breaks between clouds. They stood for a minute or two looking toward the Burrow, their hands shadowing their eyes, but all they could make out were the high hedges and trees of the orchard, which afforded the crooked little house protection from Muggle eyes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s weird, being this near, but not going to visit,\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, it\rquote s not like you haven\rquote t just seen them. You were there for Christmas,\rdblquote  said Hermione coldly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I wasn\rquote t at the Burrow!\rdblquote  said Ron with an incredulous laugh. \ldblquote Do you think I was going to go back there and tell them all I\rquote d walked out on you? Yeah, Fred and George would\rquote ve been great about it. And Ginny, she\rquote d have been really understanding.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But where have you been, then?\rdblquote  asked Hermione, surprised.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bill and Fleur\rquote s new place. Shell Cottage. Bill\rquote s always been de\-cent to me. He \emdash  he wasn\rquote t impressed when he heard what I\rquote d done, but he didn\rquote t go on about it. He knew I was really sorry. None of the rest of the family know I was there. Bill told Mum he and Fleur weren\rquote t going home for Christmas because they wanted to spend it alone. You know, first holiday after they were married. I don\rquote t think Fleur minded. You know how much she hates Celestina Warbeck.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron turned his back on the Burrow.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let\rquote s try up here,\rdblquote  he said, leading the way over the top of the hill.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They walked for a few hours, Harry, at Hermione\rquote s insistence, hidden beneath the Invisibility Cloak. The cluster of low hills ap\-peared to be uninhabited apart from one small cottage, which seemed deserted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Do you think it\rquote s theirs, and they\rquote ve gone away for Christmas?\rdblquote  said Hermione, peering through the window at a neat little kitchen with geraniums on the windowsill. Ron snorted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Listen, I\rquote ve got a feeling you\rquote d be able to tell who lived there if you looked through the Lovegoods\rquote  window. Let\rquote s try the next lot of hills.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 So they Disapparated a few miles farther north.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Aha!\rdblquote  shouted Ron, as the wind whipped their hair and clothes. Ron was pointing upward, toward the top of the hill on which they had appeared, where a most strange-looking house rose vertically against the sky, a great black cylinder with a ghostly moon hanging behind it in the afternoon sky. \ldblquote That\rquote s got to be Luna\rquote s house, who else would live in a place like that? It looks like a giant rook!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
