The gate creaked as they opened it. The zigzagging path leading to the front door was overgrown with a variety of odd plants, includ\-ing a bush covered in the orange radishlike fruit Luna sometimes wore as earrings. Harry thought he recognized a Snargaluff and gave the wizened stump a wide berth. Two aged crab apple trees, bent with the wind, stripped of leaves but still heavy with berry-sized red fruits and bushy crowns of white-beaded mistletoe, stood sentinel on either side of the front door. A little owl with a slightly flattened, hawklike head peered down at them from one of the branches.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote d better take off the Invisibility Cloak, Harry,\rdblquote  said Hermi\-one. \ldblquote It\rquote s you Mr. Lovegood wants to help, not us.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He did as she suggested, handing her the Cloak to stow in the beaded bag. She then rapped three times on the thick black door,\lang3081  \lang1033 which was studded with iron nails and bore a knocker shaped like an eagle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Barely ten seconds passed, then the door was flung open and there stood Xenophilius Lovegood, barefoot and wearing what appeared to be a stained nightshirt. His long white candyfloss hair was dirty and unkempt. Xenophilius had been positively dapper at Bill and Fleur\rquote s wedding by comparison.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What? What is it? Who are you? What do you want?\rdblquote  he cried in a high-pitched, querulous voice, looking first at Hermione, then at Ron, and finally at Harry, upon which his mouth fell open in a perfect, comical O.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hello, Mr. Lovegood,\rdblquote  said Harry, holding out his hand. \ldblquote I\rquote m Harry, Harry Potter.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Xenophilius did not take Harry\rquote s hand, although the eye that was not pointing inward at his nose slid straight to the scar on Harry\rquote s forehead.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Would it be okay if we came in?\rdblquote  asked Harry. \ldblquote There\rquote s some\-thing we\rquote d like to ask you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \'85 I\rquote m not sure that\rquote s advisable,\rdblquote  whispered Xenophilius. He swallowed and cast a quick look around the garden. \ldblquote Rather a shock \'85 My word \'85 I\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 I\rquote m afraid I don\rquote t really think I ought to\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It won\rquote t take long,\rdblquote  said Harry, slightly disappointed by this less-than-warm welcome.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \emdash  oh, all right then. Come in, quickly. \i Quickly\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were barely over the threshold when Xenophilius slammed the door shut behind them. They were standing in the most peculiar kitchen Harry had ever seen. The room was perfectly circular, so that it felt like being inside a giant pepper pot. Everything was curved\lang3081  \lang1033 to fit the walls \emdash  the stove, the sink, and the cupboards \emdash  and all of it had been painted with flowers, insects, and birds in bright pri\-mary colors. Harry thought he recognized Luna\rquote s style: The effect, in such an enclosed space, was slightly overwhelming.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 In the middle of the floor, a wrought-iron spiral staircase led to the upper levels. There was a great deal of clattering and banging coming from overhead: Harry wondered what Luna could be doing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote d better come up,\rdblquote  said Xenophilius, still looking extremely uncomfortable, and he led the way.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The room above seemed to be a combination of living room and workplace, and as such, was even more cluttered than the kitchen. Though much smaller and entirely round, the room somewhat re\-sembled the Room of Requirement on the unforgettable occasion that it had transformed itself into a gigantic labyrinth comprised of centuries of hidden objects. There were piles upon piles of books and papers on every surface. Delicately made models of creatures Harry did not recognize, all flapping wings or snapping jaws, hung from the ceiling.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Luna was not there: The thing that was making such a racket was a wooden object covered in magically turning cogs and wheels. It looked like the bizarre offspring of a workbench and a set of old shelves, but after a moment Harry deduced that it was an old-fashioned printing press, due to the fact that it was churning out \i Quibblers.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Excuse me,\rdblquote  said Xenophilius, and he strode over to the ma\-chine, seized a grubby tablecloth from beneath an immense number of books and papers, which all tumbled onto the floor, and threw it over the press, somewhat muffling the loud bangs and clatters. He then faced Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why have you come here?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Before Harry could speak, however, Hermione let out a small cry of shock.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mr. Lovegood \emdash  what\rquote s that?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She was pointing at an enormous, gray spiral horn, not unlike that of a unicorn, which had been mounted on the wall, protruding several feet into the room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It is the horn of a Crumple-Horned Snorkack,\rdblquote  said Xeno\-philius.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No it isn\rquote t!\rdblquote  said Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hermione,\rdblquote  muttered Harry, embarrassed, \ldblquote now\rquote s not the moment \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But Harry, it\rquote s an Erumpent horn! It\rquote s a Class B Tradeable Material and it\rquote s an extraordinarily dangerous thing to have in a house!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How d\rquote you know it\rquote s an Erumpent horn?\rdblquote  asked Ron, edging away from the horn as fast as he could, given the extreme clutter of the room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There\rquote s a description in \i Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them\i0 ! Mr. Lovegood, you need to get rid of it straightaway, don\rquote t you know it can explode at the slightest touch?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Crumple-Horned Snorkack,\rdblquote  said Xenophilius very clearly, a mulish look upon his face, \ldblquote is a shy and highly magical creature, and its horn \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mr. Lovegood, I recognize the grooved markings around the base, that\rquote s an Erumpent horn and it\rquote s incredibly dangerous \emdash  I don\rquote t know where you got it \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\ldblquote I \lang1033 bought it,\rdblquote  said Xenophilius dogmatically, \ldblquote two weeks ago, from a delightful young wizard who knew of my interest in the exquisite\lang3081  \lang1033 Snorkack. A Christmas surprise for my Luna. Now,\rdblquote  he said, turning to Harry, \ldblquote why exactly have you come here, Mr. Potter?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We need some help,\rdblquote  said Harry, before Hermione could start again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah,\rdblquote  said Xenophilius. \ldblquote Help. Hmm.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His good eye moved again to Harry\rquote s scar. He seemed simultane\-ously terrified and mesmerized.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes. The thing is \'85 helping Harry Potter \'85 rather danger\-ous\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Aren\rquote t you the one who keeps telling everyone it\rquote s their first duty to help Harry?\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote In that magazine of yours?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Xenophilius glanced behind him at the concealed printing press, still banging and clattering beneath the tablecloth.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash  yes, I have expressed that view. However \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s for everyone else to do, not you personally?\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Xenophilius did not answer. He kept swallowing, his eyes darting between the three of them. Harry had the impression that he was undergoing some painful internal struggle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where\rquote s Luna?\rdblquote  asked Hermione. \ldblquote Let\rquote s see what she thinks.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Xenophilius gulped. He seemed to be steeling himself. Finally he said in a shaky voice difficult to hear over the noise of the printing press, \ldblquote Luna is down at the stream, fishing for Freshwater Plimpies. She \'85 she will like to see you. I\rquote ll go and call her and then \emdash  yes, very well. I shall try to help you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He disappeared down the spiral staircase and they heard the front door open and close. They looked at each other.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Cowardly old wart,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Luna\rquote s got ten times his guts.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s probably worried about what\rquote ll happen to them if the Death Eaters find out I was here,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I agree with Ron,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote Awful old hypocrite, telling everyone else to help you and trying to worm out of it him\-self. And for heaven\rquote s sake keep away from that horn.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry crossed to the window on the far side of the room. He could see a stream, a thin, glittering ribbon lying far below them at the base of the hill. They were very high up; a bird fluttered past the window as he stared in the direction of the Burrow, now invis\-ible beyond another line of hills. Ginny was over there somewhere. They were closer to each other today than they had been since Bill and Fleur\rquote s wedding, but she could have no idea he was gazing to\-ward her now, thinking of her. He supposed he ought to be glad of it; anyone he came into contact with was in danger, Xenophilius\rquote s attitude proved that.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He turned away from the window and his gaze fell upon another peculiar object standing upon the cluttered, curved sideboard: a stone bust of a beautiful but austere-looking witch wearing a most bizarre-looking headdress. Two objects that resembled golden ear trumpets curved out from the sides. A tiny pair of glittering blue wings was stuck to a leather strap that ran over the top of her head, while one of the orange radishes had been stuck to a second strap around her forehead.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Look at this,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fetching,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Surprised he didn\rquote t wear that to the wedding.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They heard the front door close, and a moment later Xenophil\-ius had climbed back up the spiral staircase into the room, his thin legs now encased in Wellington boots, bearing a tray of ill-assorted teacups and a steaming teapot.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah, you have spotted my pet invention,\rdblquote  he said, shoving the\lang3081  \lang1033 tray into Hermione\rquote s arms and joining Harry at the statue\rquote s side. \ldblquote Modeled, fittingly enough, upon the head of the beautiful Rowena Ravenclaw. \lquote\i Wit beyond measure is man\rquote s greatest treasure\i0 !\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He indicated the objects like ear trumpets.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote These are the Wrackspurt siphons \emdash  to remove all sources of distraction from the thinker\rquote s immediate area. Here,\rdblquote  he pointed out the tiny wings, \ldblquote a billywig propeller, to induce an elevated frame of mind. Finally,\rdblquote  he pointed to the orange radish, \ldblquote the Dirigible Plum, so as to enhance the ability to accept the extraordinary.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Xenophilius strode back to the tea tray, which Hermione had man\-aged to balance precariously on one of the cluttered side tables.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote May I offer you all an infusion of Gurdyroots?\rdblquote  said Xenophil\-ius. \ldblquote We make it ourselves.\rdblquote  As he started to pour out the drink, which was as deeply purple as beetroot juice, he added, \ldblquote Luna is down beyond Bottom Bridge, she is most excited that you are here. She ought not to be too long, she has caught nearly enough Plimp\-ies to make soup for all of us. Do sit down and help yourselves to sugar.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now,\rdblquote  he removed a tottering pile of papers from an armchair and sat down, his Wellingtoned legs crossed, \ldblquote how may I help you, Mr. Potter?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Harry, glancing at Hermione, who nodded encour\-agingly, \ldblquote it\rquote s about that symbol you were wearing around your neck at Bill and Fleur\rquote s wedding, Mr. Lovegood. We wondered what it meant.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Xenophilius raised his eyebrows.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you referring to the sign of the Deathly Hallows?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\par
