Harry turned to look at Ron and Hermione. Neither of them seemed to have understood what Xenophilius had said either.\par
\ldblquote The Deathly Hallows?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s right,\rdblquote  said Xenophilius. \ldblquote You haven\rquote t heard of them? I\rquote m not surprised. Very, very few wizards believe. Witness that knuckle-headed young man at your brother\rquote s wedding,\rdblquote  he nodded at Ron, \ldblquote who attacked me for sporting the symbol of a well-known Dark wizard! Such ignorance. There is nothing Dark about the Hallows \emdash  at least, not in that crude sense. One simply uses the symbol to reveal oneself to other believers, in the hope that they might help one with the Quest.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He stirred several lumps of sugar into his Gurdyroot infusion and drank some.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry,\rdblquote  said Harry. \lang3081\ldblquote I \lang1033 still don\rquote t really understand.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 To be polite, he took a sip from his cup too, and almost gagged:\lang3081  \lang1033 The stuff was quite disgusting, as though someone had liquidized bogey-flavored Every Flavor Beans.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, you see, believers seek the Deathly Hallows,\rdblquote  said Xeno\-philius, smacking his lips in apparent appreciation of the Gurdyroot infusion.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But what \i are\i0  the Deathly Hallows?\rdblquote  asked Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Xenophilius set aside his empty teacup.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I assume that you are all familiar with \ldblquote The Tale of the Three Brothers\rquote ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry said, \ldblquote No,\rdblquote  but Ron and Hermione both said, \ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote  Xeno\-philius nodded gravely.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, well, Mr. Potter, the whole thing starts with \lquote The Tale of the Three Brothers\rquote  \'85 I have a copy somewhere. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He glanced vaguely around the room, at the piles of parchment and books, but Hermione said, \ldblquote I\rquote ve got a copy, Mr. Lovegood, I\rquote ve got it right here.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And she pulled out \i The Tales of\lang3081  \lang1033 Beedle the Bard\i0  from the small, beaded bag.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The original?\rdblquote  inquired Xenophilius sharply, and when she nod\-ded, he said, \ldblquote Well then, why don\rquote t you read it aloud? Much the best way to make sure we all understand.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 all right,\rdblquote  said Hermione nervously. She opened the book, and Harry saw that the symbol they were investigating headed the top of the page as she gave a little cough, and began to read.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i There were once three brothers who were traveling along a lonely, winding road at twilight\lang3081\i0  \lang1033\emdash\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Midnight, our mum always told us,\rdblquote  said Ron, who had stretched out, arms behind his head, to listen. Hermione shot him a look of annoyance.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sorry, I just think it\rquote s a bit spookier if it\rquote s midnight!\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, because we really need a bit more fear in our lives,\rdblquote  said Harry before he could stop himself. Xenophilius did not seem to be paying much attention, but was staring out of the window at the sky. \ldblquote Go on, Hermione.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i In time, the brothers reached a river too deep to wade through and too dangerous to swim across. However, these brothers were learned in the magical arts, and so they simply waved their wands and made a bridge appear across the treacherous water. They were halfway across it when they found their path blocked by a hooded figure.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i And Death spoke to them\i0  \emdash\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sorry,\rdblquote  interjected Harry, \ldblquote but \i Death\i0  spoke to them?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s a fairy tale, Harry!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right, sorry. Go on.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i And Death spoke to them. He was angry that he had been cheated out of three new victims, for travelers usually drowned in the river. But Death was cunning. He pretended to congratulate the three brothers upon their magic, and said that each had earned a prize for having been clever enough to evade him.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i So the oldest brother, who was a combative man, asked for a wand more powerful than any in existence: a wand that must always win duels for its owner, a wand worthy of a wizard who had conquered Death! So Death crossed to an elder tree on the banks of the river, fashioned a wand from a branch that hung there, and gave it to the oldest brother.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i Then the second brother, who was an arrogant man, decided that he wanted to humiliate Death still further, and asked for the power to recall others from Death. So Death picked up a stone from the riverbank and gave it to the second brother, and told him that the stone would have the power to bring back the dead.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i And then Death asked the third and youngest brother what he would like. The youngest brother was the humblest and also the wisest of the brothers, and he did not trust Death. So he asked for something that would enable him to go forth from that place without being fol\-lowed by Death. And Death, most unwillingly, handed over his own Cloak of Invisibility.\i0\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Death\rquote s got an Invisibility Cloak?\rdblquote  Harry interrupted again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So he can sneak up on people,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Sometimes he gets bored of running at them, flapping his arms and shrieking\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 sorry, Hermione.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i Then Death stood aside and allowed the three brothers to continue on their way, and they did so, talking with wonder of the adventure they had had, and admiring Death\rquote s gifts.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i In due course the brothers separated, each for his own destination.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i The first brother traveled on for a week or more, and reaching a distant village, sought out a fellow wizard with whom he had a quar\-rel. Naturally, with the Elder Wand as his weapon, he could not fail to win the duel that followed. Leaving his enemy dead upon the floor, the oldest brother proceeded to an inn, where he boasted loudly of the powerful wand he had snatched from Death himself, and of how it made him invincible.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i That very night, another wizard crept upon the oldest brother as he lay, wine-sodden, upon his bed. The thief took the wand and, for good measure, slit the oldest brother\rquote s throat.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i And so Death took the first brother for his own.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i Meanwhile, the second brother journeyed to his own home, where he lived alone. Here he took out the stone that had the power to recall the dead, and turned it thrice in his hand. To his amazement and his\lang3081\i0  \lang1033\i delight, the figure of the girl he had once hoped to marry, before her untimely death, appeared at once before him.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i Yet she was sad and cold, separated from him as by a veil. Though she had returned to the mortal world, she did not truly belong there and suffered. Finally the second brother, driven mad with hopeless longing, killed himself so as truly to join her.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i And so Death took the second brother for his own.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i But though Death searched for the third brother for many years, he was never able to find him. It was only when he had attained a great age that the youngest brother finally took off the Cloak of Invisibility and gave it to his son. And then he greeted Death as an old friend, and went with him gladly, and, equals, they departed this life.\i0\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione closed the book. It was a moment or two before Xeno\-philius seemed to realize that she had stopped reading, then he with\-drew his gaze from the window and said, \ldblquote Well, there you are.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sorry?\rdblquote  said Hermione, sounding confused.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Those are the Deathly Hallows,\rdblquote  said Xenophilius.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He picked up a quill from a packed table at his elbow, and pulled a torn piece of parchment from between more books.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Elder Wand,\rdblquote  he said, and he drew a straight vertical line upon the parchment. \ldblquote The Resurrection Stone,\rdblquote  he said, and he added a circle on top of the line. \ldblquote The Cloak of Invisibility,\rdblquote  he finished, en\-closing both line and circle in a triangle, to make the symbol that so intrigued Hermione. \ldblquote Together,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote the Deathly Hallows.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But there\rquote s no mention of the words \lquote Deathly Hallows\rquote  in the story,\rdblquote  said Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, of course not,\rdblquote  said Xenophilius, maddeningly smug. \ldblquote That is a children\rquote s tale, told to amuse rather than to instruct. Those of us\lang3081  \lang1033 who understand these matters, however, recognize that the ancient story refers to three objects, or Hallows, which, if united, will make the possessor master of Death.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a short silence in which Xenophilius glanced out of the window. Already the sun was low in the sky.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Luna ought to have enough Plimpies soon,\rdblquote  he said quietly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote When you say \lquote master of Death\rquote  \emdash\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Master,\rdblquote  said Xenophilius, waving an airy hand. \ldblquote Conqueror. Vanquisher. Whichever term you prefer.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But then \'85 do you mean \'85\rdblquote  said Hermione slowly, and Harry could tell that she was trying to keep any trace of skepticism out of her voice, \ldblquote that you believe these objects \emdash  these Hallows \emdash  actu\-ally exist?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Xenophilius raised his eyebrows again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, of course.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But,\rdblquote  said Hermione, and Harry could hear her restraint starting to crack, \ldblquote Mr. Lovegood, how can you \i possibly\i0  believe \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Luna has told me all about you, young lady,\rdblquote  said Xenophilius. \ldblquote You are, I gather, not unintelligent, but painfully limited. Narrow. Close-minded.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Perhaps you ought to try on the hat, Hermione,\rdblquote  said Ron, nodding toward the ludicrous headdress. His voice shook with the strain of not laughing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mr. Lovegood,\rdblquote  Hermione began again. \ldblquote We all know that there are such things as Invisibility Cloaks. They are rare, but they exist. But\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah, but the Third Hallow is a \i true\i0  Cloak of Invisibility, Miss Granger! I mean to say, it is not a traveling cloak imbued with a Dis\-illusionment Charm, or carrying a Bedazzling Hex, or else woven\lang3081  \lang1033 from Demiguise hair, which will hide one initially but fade with the years until it turns opaque. We are talking about a cloak that really and truly renders the wearer completely invisible, and endures eternally, giving constant and impenetrable concealment, no matter what spells are cast at it. How many cloaks have you ever seen like \i that,\i0  Miss Granger?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione opened her mouth to answer, then closed it again, looking more confused than ever. She, Harry, and Ron glanced at one another, and Harry knew that they were all thinking the same thing. It so happened that a cloak exactly like the one Xeno\-philius had just described was in the room with them at that very moment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Exactly,\rdblquote  said Xenophilius, as if he had defeated them all in reasoned argument. \ldblquote None of you have ever seen such a thing. The possessor would be immeasurably rich, would he not?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He glanced out of the window again. The sky was now tinged with the faintest trace of pink.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All right,\rdblquote  said Hermione, disconcerted. \ldblquote Say the Cloak existed \'85 what about the stone, Mr. Lovegood? The thing you call the Resurrection Stone?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What of it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, how can that be real?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Prove that it is not,\rdblquote  said Xenophilius.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione looked outraged.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But that\rquote s \emdash  I\rquote m sorry, but that\rquote s completely ridiculous! How can I \i possibly\i0  prove it doesn\rquote t exist? Do you expect me to get hold of\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\lang3081  \lang1033 of all the pebbles in the world and test them? I mean, you could claim that \i anything\rquote s\i0  real if the only basis for believing in it is that nobody\rquote s \i proved\i0  it doesn\rquote t exist!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, you could,\rdblquote  said Xenophilius. \ldblquote I am glad to see that you are opening your mind a little.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So the Elder Wand,\rdblquote  said Harry quickly, before Hermione could retort, \ldblquote you think that exists too?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, well, in that case there is endless evidence,\rdblquote  said Xenophil\-ius. \ldblquote The Elder Wand is the Hallow that is most easily traced, be\-cause of the way in which it passes from hand to hand.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Which is what?\rdblquote  asked Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Which is that the possessor of the wand must capture it from its previous owner, if he is to be truly master of it,\rdblquote  said Xenophil\-ius. \ldblquote Surely you have heard of the way the wand came to Egbert the Egregious, after his slaughter of Emeric the Evil? Of how Godelot died in his own cellar after his son, Hereward, took the wand from him? Of the dreadful Loxias, who took the wand from Barnabas Deverill, whom he had killed? The bloody trail of the Elder Wand is splattered across the pages of Wizarding history.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry glanced at Hermione. She was frowning at Xenophilius, but she did not contradict him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So where do you think the Elder Wand is now?\rdblquote  asked Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Alas, who knows?\rdblquote  said Xenophilius, as he gazed out of the window. \ldblquote Who knows where the Elder Wand lies hidden? The trail goes cold with Arcus and Livius. Who can say which of them really defeated Loxias, and which took the wand? And who can say who may have defeated them? History, alas, does not tell us.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a pause. Finally Hermione asked stiffly, \ldblquote Mr. Love\-good, does the Peverell family have anything to do with the Deathly Hallows?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Xenophilius looked taken aback as something shifted in Harry\rquote s\lang3081  \lang1033 memory, but he could not locate it. Peverell\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 he had heard that name before. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But you have been misleading me, young woman!\rdblquote  said Xeno\-philius, now sitting up much straighter in his chair and goggling at Hermione. \ldblquote I thought you were new to the Hallows Quest! Many of us Questers believe that the Peverells have everything \emdash  \i everything\i0 ! \emdash  to do with the Hallows!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Who are the Peverells?\rdblquote  asked Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That was the name on the grave with the mark on it, in Godric\rquote s Hollow,\rdblquote  said Hermione, still watching Xenophilius. \ldblquote Ignotus Peverell.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Exactly!\rdblquote  said Xenophilius, his forefinger raised pedantically. \ldblquote The sign of the Deathly Hallows on Ignotus\rquote s grave is conclusive proof!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of what?\rdblquote  asked Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why, that the three brothers in the story were actually the three Peverell brothers, Antioch, Cadmus, and Ignotus! That they were the original owners of the Hallows!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 With another glance at the window he got to his feet, picked up the tray, and headed for the spiral staircase.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You will stay for dinner?\rdblquote  he called, as he vanished downstairs again. \ldblquote Everybody always requests our recipe for Freshwater Plimpy soup.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Probably to show the Poisoning Department at St. Mungo\rquote s,\rdblquote  said Ron under his breath.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry waited until they could hear Xenophilius moving about in the kitchen downstairs before speaking.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What do you think?\rdblquote  he asked Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, Harry,\rdblquote  she said wearily, \ldblquote it\rquote s a pile of utter rubbish. This can\rquote t be what the sign really means. This must just be his weird take on it. What a waste of time.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I s\rquote pose this \i is\i0  the man who brought us Crumple-Horned Snor\-kacks,\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You don\rquote t believe it either?\rdblquote  Harry asked him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nah, that story\rquote s just one of those things you tell kids to teach them lessons, isn\rquote t it? \lquote Don\rquote t go looking for trouble, don\rquote t pick fights, don\rquote t go messing around with stuff that\rquote s best left alone! Just keep your head down, mind your own business, and you\rquote ll be okay\rquote  Come to think of it,\rdblquote  Ron added, \ldblquote maybe that story\rquote s why elder wands are supposed to be unlucky.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What are you talking about?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote One of those superstitions, isn\rquote t it? \lquote May-born witches will marry Muggles.\rquote  \lquote Jinx by twilight, undone by midnight.\rquote  \lquote Wand of elder, never prosper.\rquote  You must\rquote ve heard them. My mum\rquote s full of them.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry and I were raised by Muggles,\rdblquote  Hermione reminded him. \ldblquote We were taught different superstitions.\rdblquote  She sighed deeply as a rather pungent smell drifted up from the kitchen. The one good thing about her exasperation with Xenophilius was that it seemed to have made her forget that she was annoyed at Ron. \ldblquote I think you\rquote re right,\rdblquote  she told him. \ldblquote It\rquote s just a morality tale, it\rquote s obvious which gift is best, which one you\rquote d choose \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The three of them spoke at the same time; Hermione said, \ldblquote the Cloak,\rdblquote  Ron said, \ldblquote the wand,\rdblquote  and Harry said, \ldblquote the stone.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They looked at each other, half surprised, half amused.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re \i supposed\lang3081\i0  \lang1033 to say the Cloak,\rdblquote  Ron told Hermione, \ldblquote but you wouldn\rquote t need to be invisible if you had the wand. \i An unbeatable wand,\i0  Hermione, come on!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ve already got an Invisibility Cloak,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And it\rquote s helped us rather a lot, in case you hadn\rquote t noticed!\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote Whereas the wand would be bound to attract trouble \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Only if you shouted about it,\rdblquote  argued Ron. \ldblquote Only if you were prat enough to go dancing around, waving it over your head, and singing, \lquote I\rquote ve got an unbeatable wand, come and have a go if you think you\rquote re hard enough.\rquote  As long as you kept your trap shut \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, but \i could\i0  you keep your trap shut?\rdblquote  said Hermione, look\-ing skeptical. \ldblquote You know, the only true thing he said to us was that there have been stories about extra-powerful wands for hundreds of years.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There have?\rdblquote  asked Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione looked exasperated: The expression was so endearingly familiar that Harry and Ron grinned at each other.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Deathstick, the Wand of Destiny, they crop up under differ\-ent names through the centuries, usually in the possession of some Dark wizard who\rquote s boasting about them. Professor Binns mentioned some of them, but \emdash  oh, it\rquote s all nonsense. Wands are only as pow\-erful as the wizards who use them. Some wizards just like to boast that theirs are bigger and better than other people\rquote s.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But how do you know,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote that those wands \emdash  the Deathstick and the Wand of Destiny \emdash  aren\rquote t the same wand, sur\-facing over the centuries under different names?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What, and they\rquote re all really the Elder Wand, made by Death?\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry laughed: The strange idea that had occurred to him was, after all, ridiculous. His wand, he reminded himself, had been of holly, not elder, and it had been made by Ollivander, whatever it had\lang3081  \lang1033 done that night Voldemort had pursued him across the skies. And if it had been unbeatable, how could it have been broken?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So why would you take the stone?\rdblquote  Ron asked him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, if you could bring people back, we could have Sirius \'85 Mad-Eye \'85 Dumbledore \'85 my parents. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Neither Ron nor Hermione smiled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But according to Beedle the Bard, they wouldn\rquote t want to come back, would they?\rdblquote  said Harry, thinking about the tale they had just heard. \ldblquote I don\rquote t suppose there have been loads of other sto\-ries about a stone that can raise the dead, have there?\rdblquote  he asked Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  she replied sadly. \ldblquote I don\rquote t think anyone except Mr. Love\-good could kid themselves that\rquote s possible. Beedle probably took the idea from the Sorcerer\rquote s Stone; you know, instead of a stone to make you immortal, a stone to reverse death.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
