It was like sinking into an old nightmare; for an instant Harry knelt again beside Dumbledore\rquote s body at the foot of the tallest tower at Hogwarts, but in reality he was staring at a tiny body curled upon the grass, pierced by Bellatrix\rquote s silver knife. Harry\rquote s voice was still saying, \ldblquote Dobby \'85 \i Dobby\i0  \'85\rdblquote  even though he knew that the elf had gone where he could not call him back.\par
After a minute or so he realized that they had, after all, come to the right place, for here were Bill and Fleur, Dean and Luna, gath\-ering around him as he knelt over the elf.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hermione?\rdblquote  he said suddenly. \ldblquote Where is she?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Ron\rquote s taken her inside,\rdblquote  said Bill. \ldblquote She\rquote ll be all right.\rdblquote\par
Harry looked back down at Dobby. He stretched out a hand and pulled the sharp blade from the elf\rquote s body, then dragged off his own jacket and covered Dobby in it like a blanket.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The sea was rushing against rock somewhere nearby; Harry lis\-tened to it while the others talked, discussing matters in which he\lang3081  \lang1033 could take no interest, making decisions. Dean carried the injured Griphook into the house, Fleur hurrying with them; now Bill was making suggestions about burying the elf. Harry agreed without really knowing what he was saying. As he did so, he gazed down at the tiny body, and his scar prickled and burned, and in one part of his mind, viewed as if from the wrong end of a long telescope, he saw Voldemort punishing those they had left behind at Malfoy Manor. His rage was dreadful and yet Harry\rquote s grief for Dobby seemed to diminish it, so that it became a distant storm that reached Harry from across a vast, silent ocean.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I want to do it properly,\rdblquote  were the first words of which Harry was fully conscious of speaking. \ldblquote Not by magic. Have you got a spade?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And shortly afterward he had set to work, alone, digging the grave in the place that Bill had shown him at the end of the garden, between bushes. He dug with a kind of fury, relishing the manual work, glorying in the non-magic of it, for every drop of his sweat and every blister felt like a gift to the elf who had saved their lives.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His scar burned, but he was master of the pain; he felt it, yet was apart from it. He had learned control at last, learned to shut his mind to Voldemort, the very thing Dumbledore had wanted him to learn from Snape. Just as Voldemort had not been able to pos\-sess Harry while Harry was consumed with grief for Sirius, so his thoughts could not penetrate Harry now, while he mourned Dobby. Grief, it seemed, drove Voldemort out\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 though Dumbledore, of course, would have said that it was love. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 On Harry dug, deeper and deeper into the hard, cold earth, subsuming his grief in sweat, denying the pain in his scar. In the darkness, with nothing but the sound of his own breath and the\lang3081  \lang1033 rushing sea to keep him company, the things that had happened at the Malfoys\rquote  returned to him, the things he had heard came back to him, and understanding blossomed in the darkness. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The steady rhythm of his arms beat time with his thoughts. Hal\-lows \'85 Horcruxes \'85 Hallows \'85 Horcruxes \'85 Yet he no longer burned with that weird, obsessive longing. Loss and fear had snuffed it out: He felt as though he had been slapped awake again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Deeper and deeper Harry sank into the grave, and he knew where Voldemort had been tonight, and whom he had killed in the top\-most cell of Nurmengard, and why. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And he thought of Wormtail, dead because of one small uncon\-scious impulse of mercy. \'85 Dumbledore had foreseen that. \'85 How much more had he known?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry lost track of time. He knew only that the darkness had lightened a few degrees when he was rejoined by Ron and Dean.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How\rquote s Hermione?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Better,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Fleur\rquote s looking after her.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had his retort ready for when they asked him why he had not simply created a perfect grave with his wand, but he did not need it. They jumped down into the hole he had made with spades of their own, and together they worked in silence until the hole seemed deep enough.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry wrapped the elf more snugly in his jacket. Ron sat on the edge of the grave and stripped off his shoes and socks, which he placed upon the elf\rquote s bare feet. Dean produced a woolen hat, which Harry placed carefully upon Dobby\rquote s head, muffling his batlike ears.\lang3081\par
