\lang1033\i Am I meant to know, but not to seek? Did you know how hard I\rquote d find that? Is that why you made it this difficult? So I\rquote d have time to work that out?\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033 Harry stood quite still, eyes glazed, watching the place where a bright gold rim of dazzling sun was rising over the horizon. Then he looked down at his clean hands and was momentarily surprised to\lang3081  \lang1033 see the cloth he was holding in them. He set it down and returned to the hall, and as he did so, he felt his scar pulse angrily, and there flashed across his mind, swift as the reflection of a dragonfly over water, the outline of a building he knew extremely well.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Bill and Fleur were standing at the foot of the stairs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I need to speak to Griphook and Ollivander,\rdblquote  Harry said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Fleur. \ldblquote You will \rquote ave to wait, \rquote Arry. Zey are both ill, tired \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry,\rdblquote  he said without heat, \ldblquote but it can\rquote t wait. I need to talk to them now. Privately \emdash  and separately. It\rquote s urgent.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, what the hell\rquote s going on?\rdblquote  asked Bill. \ldblquote You turn up here with a dead house-elf and a half-conscious goblin, Hermione looks as though she\rquote s been tortured, and Ron\rquote s just refused to tell me anything \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We can\rquote t tell you what we\rquote re doing,\rdblquote  said Harry flatly. \ldblquote You\rquote re in the Order, Bill, you know Dumbledore left us a mission. We\rquote re not supposed to talk about it to anyone else.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fleur made an impatient noise, but Bill did not look at her; he was staring at Harry. His deeply scarred face was hard to read. Finally Bill said, \ldblquote All right. Who do you want to talk to first?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry hesitated. He knew what hung on his decision. There was hardly any time left; now was the moment to decide: Horcruxes or Hallows?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Griphook,\rdblquote  Harry said. \ldblquote I\rquote ll speak to Griphook first.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His heart was racing as if he had been sprinting and had just cleared an enormous obstacle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Up here, then,\rdblquote  said Bill, leading the way.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had walked up several steps before stopping and looking back.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I need you two as well!\rdblquote  he called to Ron and Hermione, who had been skulking, half concealed, in the doorway of the sitting room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They both moved into the light, looking oddly relieved.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How are you?\rdblquote  Harry asked Hermione. \ldblquote You were amazing \emdash  coming up with that story when she was hurting you like that \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione gave a weak smile as Ron gave her a one-armed squeeze.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What are we doing now, Harry?\rdblquote  he asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote ll see. Come on.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry, Ron, and Hermione followed Bill up the steep stairs onto a small landing. Three doors led off it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote In here,\rdblquote  said Bill, opening the door into his and Fleur\rquote s room. It too had a view of the sea, now flecked with gold in the sunrise. Harry moved to the window, turned his back on the spectacular view, and waited, his arms folded, his scar prickling. Hermione took the chair beside the dressing table; Ron sat on the arm.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Bill reappeared, carrying the little goblin, whom he set down carefully upon the bed. Griphook grunted thanks, and Bill left, closing the door upon them all.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry to take you out of bed,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote How are your legs?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Painful,\rdblquote  replied the goblin. \ldblquote But mending.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was still clutching the sword of Gryffindor, and wore a strange look: half truculent, half intrigued. Harry noted the goblin\rquote s sallow skin, his long thin fingers, his black eyes. Fleur had removed his shoes: His long feet were dirty. He was larger than a house-elf, but not by much. His domed head was much bigger than a human\rquote s.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You probably don\rquote t remember \emdash\rdblquote  Harry began.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  that I was the goblin who showed you to your vault, the first time you ever visited Gringotts?\rdblquote  said Griphook. \ldblquote I remember, Harry Potter. Even amongst goblins, you are very famous.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry and the goblin looked at each other, sizing each other up. Harry\rquote s scar was still prickling. He wanted to get through this in\-terview with Griphook quickly, and at the same time was afraid of making a false move. While he tried to decide on the best way to approach his request, the goblin broke the silence.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You buried the elf,\rdblquote  he said, sounding unexpectedly rancorous. \ldblquote I watched you from the window of the bedroom next door.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Griphook looked at him out of the corners of his slanting black eyes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You are an unusual wizard, Harry Potter.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote In what way?\rdblquote  asked Harry, rubbing his scar absently.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You dug the grave.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote So?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Griphook did not answer. Harry rather thought he was being sneered at for acting like a Muggle, but it did not much matter to him whether Griphook approved of Dobby\rquote s grave or not. He gath\-ered himself for the attack.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Griphook, I need to ask \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You also rescued a goblin.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You brought me here. Saved me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I take it you\rquote re not sorry?\rdblquote  said Harry a little impatiently.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, Harry Potter,\rdblquote  said Griphook, and with one finger he twisted the thin black beard upon his chin, \ldblquote but you are a very odd wizard.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Well, I need some help, Griphook, and you can give it to me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The goblin made no sign of encouragement, but continued to frown at Harry as though he had never seen anything like him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I need to break into a Gringotts vault.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had not meant to say it so baldly; the words were forced from him as pain shot through his lightning scar and he saw, again, the outline of Hogwarts. He closed his mind firmly. He needed to deal with Griphook first. Ron and Hermione were staring at Harry as though he had gone mad.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry \emdash\rdblquote  said Hermione, but she was cut off by Griphook.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Break into a Gringotts vault?\rdblquote  repeated the goblin, wincing a little as he shifted his position upon the bed. \ldblquote It is impossible.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, it isn\rquote t,\rdblquote  Ron contradicted him. \ldblquote It\rquote s been done.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote The same day I first met you, Griphook. My birthday, seven years ago.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The vault in question was empty at the time,\rdblquote  snapped the gob\-lin, and Harry understood that even though Griphook had left Gringotts, he was offended at the idea of its defenses being breached. \ldblquote Its protection was minimal.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, the vault we need to get into isn\rquote t empty, and I\rquote m guess\-ing its protection will be pretty powerful,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote It belongs to the Lestranges.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He saw Hermione and Ron look at each other, astonished, but there would be time enough to explain after Griphook had given his answer.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You have no chance,\rdblquote  said Griphook flatly. \ldblquote No chance at all. \i If you seek beneath our floors, a treasure that was never yours\i0  \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Thief,\lang3081  \lang1033 you have been warned, beware\i0  \emdash  yeah, I know, I remember,\rdblquote\lang3081  \lang1033 said Harry. \ldblquote But I\rquote m not trying to get myself any treasure, I\rquote m not trying to take anything for personal gain. Can you believe that?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The goblin looked slantwise at Harry, and the lightning scar on Harry\rquote s forehead prickled, but he ignored it, refusing to acknowl\-edge its pain or its invitation.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If there was a wizard of whom I would believe that they did not seek personal gain,\rdblquote  said Griphook finally, \ldblquote it would be you, Harry Potter. Goblins and elves are not used to the protection or the re\-spect that you have shown this night. Not from wand-carriers.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wand-carriers,\rdblquote  repeated Harry: The phrase fell oddly upon his ears as his scar prickled, as Voldemort turned his thoughts north\-ward, and as Harry burned to question Ollivander next door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The right to carry a wand,\rdblquote  said the goblin quietly, \ldblquote has long been contested between wizards and goblins.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, goblins can do magic without wands,\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That is immaterial! Wizards refuse to share the secrets of wand-lore with other magical beings, they deny us the possibility of ex\-tending our powers!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, goblins won\rquote t share any of their magic either,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote You won\rquote t tell us how to make swords and armor the way you do. Goblins know how to work metal in a way wizards have never \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It doesn\rquote t matter,\rdblquote  said Harry, noting Griphook\rquote s rising color. \ldblquote This isn\rquote t about wizards versus goblins or any other sort of magi\-cal creature \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Griphook gave a nasty laugh.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But it is, it is about precisely that! As the Dark Lord becomes ever more powerful, your race is set still more firmly above mine!\lang3081  \lang1033 Gringotts falls under Wizarding rule, house-elves are slaughtered, and who amongst the wand-carriers protests?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We do!\rdblquote  said Hermione. She had sat up straight, her eyes bright. \ldblquote We protest! And I\rquote m hunted quite as much as any goblin or elf, Griphook! I\rquote m a Mudblood!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t call yourself\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote  Ron muttered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why shouldn\rquote t I?\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote Mudblood, and proud of it! I\rquote ve got no higher position under this new order than you have, Griphook! It was me they chose to torture, back at the Malfoys\rquote !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As she spoke, she pulled aside the neck of the dressing gown to reveal the thin cut Bellatrix had made, scarlet against her throat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did you know that it was Harry who set Dobby free?\rdblquote  she asked. \ldblquote Did you know that we\rquote ve wanted elves to be freed for years?\rdblquote  (Ron fidgeted uncomfortably on the arm of Hermione\rquote s chair.) \ldblquote You can\rquote t want You-Know-Who defeated more than we do, Griphook!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The goblin gazed at Hermione with the same curiosity he had shown Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What do you seek within the Lestranges\rquote  vault?\rdblquote  he asked abruptly. \ldblquote The sword that lies inside it is a fake. This is the real one.\rdblquote  He looked from one to the other of them. \ldblquote I think that you already know this. You asked me to lie for you back there.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But the fake sword isn\rquote t the only thing in that vault, is it?\rdblquote  asked Harry. \ldblquote Perhaps you\rquote ve seen the other things in there?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His heart was pounding harder than ever. He redoubled his ef\-forts to ignore the pulsing of his scar.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The goblin twisted his beard around his finger again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It is against our code to speak of the secrets of Gringotts. We are the guardians of fabulous treasures. We have a duty to the\lang3081  \lang1033 objects placed in our care, which were, so often, wrought by our fingers.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The goblin stroked the sword, and his black eyes roved from Harry to Hermione to Ron and then back again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So young,\rdblquote  he said finally, \ldblquote to be fighting so many.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Will you help us?\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote We haven\rquote t got a hope of break\-ing in without a goblin\rquote s help. You\rquote re our one chance.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I shall\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 think about it,\rdblquote  said Griphook maddeningly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But \emdash\rdblquote  Ron started angrily; Hermione nudged him in the ribs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank you,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The goblin bowed his great domed head in acknowledgement, then flexed his short legs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think,\rdblquote  he said, settling himself ostentatiously upon Bill and Fleur\rquote s bed, \ldblquote that the Skele-Gro has finished its work. I may be able to sleep at last. Forgive me. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, of course,\rdblquote  said Harry, but before leaving the room he leaned forward and took the sword of Gryffindor from beside the goblin. Griphook did not protest, but Harry thought he saw resent\-ment in the goblin\rquote s eyes as he closed the door upon him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Little git,\rdblquote  whispered Ron. \ldblquote He\rquote s enjoying keeping us hanging.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry,\rdblquote  whispered Hermione, pulling them both away from the door, into the middle of the still-dark landing, \ldblquote are you saying what I think you\rquote re saying? Are you saying there\rquote s a Horcrux in the Lestranges\rquote  vault?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Bellatrix was terrified when she thought we\rquote d been in there, she was beside herself. Why? What did she think we\rquote d seen, what else did she think we might have taken? Something she was petrified You-Know-Who would find out about.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But I thought we were looking for places You-Know-Who\rquote s been, places he\rquote s done something important?\rdblquote  said Ron, looking baffled. \ldblquote Was he ever inside the Lestranges\rquote  vault?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t know whether he was ever inside Gringotts,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote He never had gold there when he was younger, because nobody left him anything. He would have seen the bank from the outside, though, the first time he ever went to Diagon Alley.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s scar throbbed, but he ignored it; he wanted Ron and Hermione to understand about Gringotts before they spoke to Ollivander.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think he would have envied anyone who had a key to a Grin\-gotts vault. I think he\rquote d have seen it as a real symbol of belonging to the Wizarding world. And don\rquote t forget, he trusted Bellatrix and her husband. They were his most devoted servants before he fell, and they went looking for him after he vanished. He said it the night he came back, I heard him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry rubbed his scar.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t think he\rquote d have told Bellatrix it was a Horcrux, though. He never told Lucius Malfoy the truth about the diary. He prob\-ably told her it was a treasured possession and asked her to place it in her vault. The safest place in the world for anything you want to hide, Hagrid told me \'85 except for Hogwarts.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 When Harry had finished speaking, Ron shook his head.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You really understand him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bits of him,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Bits\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 I just wish I\rquote d understood Dum\-bledore as much. But we\rquote ll see. Come on \emdash  Ollivander now.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron and Hermione looked bewildered but impressed as they followed him across the little landing and knocked upon the door opposite Bill and Fleur\rquote s. A weak \ldblquote Come in!\rdblquote  answered them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The wandmaker was lying on the twin bed farthest from the window. He had been held in the cellar for more than a year, and tortured, Harry knew, on at least one occasion. He was emaciated, the bones of his face sticking out sharply against the yellowish skin. His great silver eyes seemed vast in their sunken sockets. The hands that lay upon the blanket could have belonged to a skeleton. Harry sat down on the empty bed, beside Ron and Hermione. The rising sun was not visible here. The room faced the cliff-top garden and the freshly dug grave.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mr. Ollivander, I\rquote m sorry to disturb you,\rdblquote  Harry said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My dear boy.\rdblquote  Ollivander\rquote s voice was feeble. \ldblquote You rescued us. I thought we would die in that place. I can never thank you \'85 \i never \i0 thank you \'85 enough.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We were glad to do it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s scar throbbed. He knew, he was certain, that there was hardly any time left in which to beat Voldemort to his goal, or else to attempt to thwart him. He felt a flutter of panic \'85 yet he had made his decision when he chose to speak to Griphook first. Feign\-ing a calm he did not feel, he groped in the pouch around his neck and took out the two halves of his broken wand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mr. Ollivander, I need some help.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Anything. Anything,\rdblquote  said the wandmaker weakly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Can you mend this? Is it possible?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ollivander held out a trembling hand, and Harry placed the two barely connected halves into his palm.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Holly and phoenix feather,\rdblquote  said Ollivander in a tremulous voice. \ldblquote Eleven inches. Nice and supple.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Can you \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  whispered Ollivander. \ldblquote I am sorry, very sorry, but a wand\lang3081  \lang1033 that has suffered this degree of damage cannot be repaired by any means that I know of.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had been braced to hear it, but it was a blow nevertheless. He took the wand halves back and replaced them in the pouch around his neck. Ollivander stared at the place where the shat\-tered wand had vanished, and did not look away until Harry had taken from his pocket the two wands he had brought from the Malfoys\rquote .\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Can you identify these?\rdblquote  Harry asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The wandmaker took the first of the wands and held it close to his faded eyes, rolling it between his knobble-knuckled fingers, flex\-ing it slightly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Walnut and dragon heartstring,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Twelve-and-three-quarter inches. Unyielding. This wand belonged to Bellatrix Lestrange.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And this one?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ollivander performed the same examination.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hawthorn and unicorn hair. Ten inches precisely. Reasonably springy. This was the wand of Draco Malfoy.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Was?\rdblquote  repeated Harry. \ldblquote Isn\rquote t it still his?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Perhaps not. If you took it \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  I did \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  then it may be yours. Of course, the manner of taking mat\-ters. Much also depends upon the wand itself. In general, however, where a wand has been won, its allegiance will change.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was silence in the room, except for the distant rushing of the sea.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You talk about wands like they\rquote ve got feelings,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote like they can think for themselves.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The wand chooses the wizard,\rdblquote  said Ollivander. \ldblquote That much has always been clear to those of us who have studied wandlore.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A person can still use a wand that hasn\rquote t chosen them, though?\rdblquote  asked Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yes, if you are any wizard at all you will be able to channel your magic through almost any instrument. The best results, how\-ever, must always come where there is the strongest affinity between wizard and wand. These connections are complex. An initial attrac\-tion, and then a mutual quest for experience, the wand learning from the wizard, the wizard from the wand.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The sea gushed forward and backward; it was a mournful sound.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I took this wand from Draco Malfoy by force,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Can I use it safely?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think so. Subtle laws govern wand ownership, but the con\-quered wand will usually bend its will to its new master.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So I should use this one?\rdblquote  said Ron, pulling Wormtail\rquote s wand out of his pocket and handing it to Ollivander.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Chestnut and dragon heartstring. Nine-and-a-quarter inches. Brittle. I was forced to make this shortly after my kidnapping, for Peter Pettigrew. Yes, if you won it, it is more likely to do your bid\-ding, and do it well, than another wand.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And this holds true for all wands, does it?\rdblquote  asked Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think so,\rdblquote  replied Ollivander, his protuberant eyes upon Har\-ry\rquote s face. \ldblquote You ask deep questions, Mr. Potter. Wandlore is a complex and mysterious branch of magic.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So, it isn\rquote t necessary to kill the previous owner to take true pos\-session of a wand?\rdblquote  asked Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ollivander swallowed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Necessary? No, I should not say that it is necessary to kill.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There are legends, though,\rdblquote  said Harry, and as his heart rate quickened, the pain in his scar became more intense; he was sure that Voldemort had decided to put his idea into action. \ldblquote Legends about a wand \emdash  or wands \emdash  that have passed from hand to hand by murder.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ollivander turned pale. Against the snowy pillow he was light gray, and his eyes were enormous, bloodshot, and bulging with what looked like fear.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Only one wand, I think,\rdblquote  he whispered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And You-Know-Who is interested in it, isn\rquote t he?\rdblquote  asked Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \emdash  how?\rdblquote  croaked Ollivander, and he looked appealingly at Ron and Hermione for help. \ldblquote How do you know this?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He wanted you to tell him how to overcome the connection between our wands,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ollivander looked terrified.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He tortured me, you must understand that! The Cruciatus Curse, I \emdash  I had no choice but to tell him what I knew, what I guessed!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I understand,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote You told him about the twin cores? You said he just had to borrow another wizard\rquote s wand?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ollivander looked horrified, transfixed, by the amount that Harry knew. He nodded slowly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But it didn\rquote t work,\rdblquote  Harry went on. \ldblquote Mine still beat the bor\-rowed wand. Do you know why that is?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ollivander shook his head as slowly as he had just nodded.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I had \'85 never heard of such a thing. Your wand performed something unique that night. The connection of the twin cores is incredibly rare, yet why your wand should have snapped the bor\-rowed wand, I do not know. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We were talking about the other wand, the wand that changes hands by murder. When You-Know-Who realized my wand had done something strange, he came back and asked about that other wand, didn\rquote t he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How do you know this?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry did not answer.\lang3081\par
