\lang1033\ldblquote Harry!\rdblquote  Ron said furiously. \ldblquote How long have you known this \emdash  why have we been wasting time? Why did you talk to Griphook first? We could have gone \emdash  we could still go \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry, and he sank to his knees in the grass. \ldblquote Hermi\-one\rquote s right. Dumbledore didn\rquote t want me to have it. He didn\rquote t want me to take it. He wanted me to get the Horcruxes.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The unbeatable wand, Harry!\rdblquote  moaned Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m not supposed to \'85 I\rquote m supposed to get the Horcruxes. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And now everything was cool and dark: The sun was barely vis\-ible over the horizon as he glided alongside Snape, up through the grounds toward the lake.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I shall join you in the castle shortly,\rdblquote  he said in his high, cold voice. \ldblquote Leave me now.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape bowed and set off back up the path, his black cloak billow\-ing behind him. Harry walked slowly, waiting for Snape\rquote s figure to disappear. It would not do for Snape, or indeed anyone else, to see where he was going. But there were no lights in the castle windows, and he could conceal himself\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 and in a second he had cast upon himself a Disillusionment Charm that hid him even from his own eyes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And he walked on, around the edge of the lake, taking in the out\-lines of the beloved castle, his first kingdom, his birthright. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And here it was, beside the lake, reflected in the dark waters. The white marble tomb, an unnecessary blot on the familiar landscape. He felt again that rush of controlled euphoria, that heady sense of purpose in destruction. He raised the old yew wand: How fitting that this would be its last great act.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The tomb split open from head to foot. The shrouded figure was as long and thin as it had been in life. He raised the wand again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The wrappings fell open. The face was translucent, pale, sunken, yet almost perfectly preserved. They had left his spectacles on the crooked nose: He felt amused derision. Dumbledore\rquote s hands were folded upon his chest, and there it lay, clutched beneath them, bur\-ied with him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Had the old fool imagined that marble or death would protect the wand? Had he thought that the Dark Lord would be scared to violate his tomb? The spiderlike hand swooped and pulled the wand from Dumbledore\rquote s grasp, and as he took it, a shower of sparks flew from its tip, sparkling over the corpse of its last owner, ready to serve a new master at last.\lang3081\par
