Bill and Fleur\rquote s cottage stood alone on a cliff overlooking the sea, its walls embedded with shells and whitewashed. It was a lonely and beautiful place. Wherever Harry went inside the tiny cottage or its garden, he could hear the constant ebb and flow of the sea, like the breathing of some great, slumbering creature. He spent much of the next few days making excuses to escape the crowded cottage, craving the cliff-top view of open sky and wide, empty sea, and the feel of cold, salty wind on his face.\par
The enormity of his decision not to race Voldemort to the wand still scared Harry. He could not remember, ever before, choosing \i not\i0  to act. He was full of doubts, doubts that Ron could not help voicing whenever they were together.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What if Dumbledore wanted us to work out the symbol in time to get the wand?\rdblquote  \ldblquote What if working out what the symbol meant made you \lquote worthy\rquote  to get the Hallows?\rdblquote  \ldblquote Harry, if that really is the Elder Wand, how the hell are we supposed to finish off You-Know-Who?\rdblquote\lang3081  \lang1033 Harry had no answers: There were moments when he wondered whether it had been outright madness not to try to prevent Volde\-mort breaking open the tomb. He could not even explain satisfacto\-rily why he had decided against it: Every time he tried to reconstruct the internal arguments that had led to his decision, they sounded feebler to him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The odd thing was that Hermione\rquote s support made him feel just as confused as Ron\rquote s doubts. Now forced to accept that the Elder Wand was real, she maintained that it was an evil object, and that the way Voldemort had taken possession of it was repellent, not to be considered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You could never have done that, Harry,\rdblquote  she said again and again. \ldblquote You couldn\rquote t have broken into Dumbledore\rquote s grave.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But the idea of Dumbledore\rquote s corpse frightened Harry much less than the possibility that he might have misunderstood the living Dumbledore\rquote s intentions. He felt that he was still groping in the dark; he had chosen his path but kept looking back, wondering whether he had misread the signs, whether he should not have taken the other way. From time to time, anger at Dumbledore crashed over him again, powerful as the waves slamming themselves against the cliff beneath the cottage, anger that Dumbledore had not explained before he died.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But \i is\i0  he dead?\rdblquote  said Ron, three days after they had arrived at the cottage. Harry had been staring out over the wall that separated the cottage garden from the cliff when Ron and Hermione had found him; he wished they had not, having no wish to join in with their argument.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, he is, Ron, \i please\i0  don\rquote t start that again!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Look at the facts, Hermione,\rdblquote  said Ron, speaking across Harry,\lang3081  \lang1033 who continued to gaze at the horizon. \ldblquote The silver doe. The sword. The eye Harry saw in the mirror \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry admits he could have imagined the eye! Don\rquote t you, Harry?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I could have,\rdblquote  said Harry without looking at her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But you don\rquote t think you did, do you?\rdblquote  asked Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I don\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There you go!\rdblquote  said Ron quickly, before Hermione could carry on. \ldblquote If it wasn\rquote t Dumbledore, explain how Dobby knew we were in the cellar, Hermione?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I can\rquote t \emdash  but can you explain how Dumbledore sent him to us if he\rquote s lying in a tomb at Hogwarts?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I dunno, it could\rquote ve been his ghost!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore wouldn\rquote t come back as a ghost,\rdblquote  said Harry. There was little about Dumbledore he was sure of now, but he knew that much. \ldblquote He would have gone on.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What d\rquote you mean, \lquote gone on\rquote ?\rdblquote  asked Ron, but before Harry could say any more, a voice behind them said, \ldblquote  \rquote Arry?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fleur had come out of the cottage, her long silver hair flying in the breeze.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \rquote Arry, Grip\rquote ook would like to speak to you. \rquote E eez in ze smallest bedroom, \rquote e says \rquote e does not want to be over\rquote eard.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Her dislike of the goblin sending her to deliver messages was clear; she looked irritable as she walked back around the house.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Griphook was waiting for them, as Fleur had said, in the tiniest of the cottage\rquote s three bedrooms, in which Hermione and Luna slept by night. He had drawn the red cotton curtains against the bright, cloudy sky, which gave the room a fiery glow at odds with the rest of the airy, light cottage.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I have reached my decision, Harry Potter,\rdblquote  said the goblin, who was sitting cross-legged in a low chair, drumming its arms with his spindly fingers. \ldblquote Though the goblins of Gringotts will consider it base treachery, I have decided to help you \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s great!\rdblquote  said Harry, relief surging through him. \ldblquote Griphook, thank you, we\rquote re really \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  in return,\rdblquote  said the goblin firmly, \ldblquote for payment.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Slightly taken aback, Harry hesitated.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How much do you want? I\rquote ve got gold.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not gold,\rdblquote  said Griphook. \ldblquote I have gold.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His black eyes glittered; there were no whites to his eyes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I want the sword. The sword of Godric Gryffindor.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s spirits plummeted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You can\rquote t have that,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote I\rquote m sorry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Then,\rdblquote  said the goblin softly, \ldblquote we have a problem.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We can give you something else,\rdblquote  said Ron eagerly. \ldblquote I\rquote ll bet the Lestranges have got loads of stuff, you can take your pick once we get into the vault.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He had said the wrong thing. Griphook flushed angrily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am not a thief, boy! I am not trying to procure treasures to which I have no right!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The sword\rquote s ours \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It is not,\rdblquote  said the goblin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote re Gryffindors, and it was Godric Gryffindor\rquote s \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And before it was Gryffindor\rquote s, whose was it?\rdblquote  demanded the goblin, sitting up straight.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No one\rquote s,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote It was made for him, wasn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No!\rdblquote  cried the goblin, bristling with anger as he pointed a long finger at Ron. \ldblquote Wizarding arrogance again! That sword was Ragnuk\lang3081  \lang1033 the First\rquote s, taken from him by Godric Gryffindor! It is a lost treasure, a masterpiece of goblinwork! It belongs with the goblins! The sword is the price of my hire, take it or leave it!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Griphook glared at them. Harry glanced at the other two, then said, \ldblquote We need to discuss this, Griphook, if that\rquote s all right. Could you give us a few minutes?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The goblin nodded, looking sour.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Downstairs in the empty sitting room, Harry walked to the fire\-place, brow furrowed, trying to think what to do. Behind him, Ron said, \ldblquote He\rquote s having a laugh. We can\rquote t let him have that sword.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It is true?\rdblquote  Harry asked Hermione. \ldblquote Was the sword stolen by Gryffindor?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t know,\rdblquote  she said hopelessly. \ldblquote Wizarding history often skates over what the wizards have done to other magical races, but there\rquote s no account that I know of that says Gryffindor stole the sword.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote ll be one of those goblin stories,\rdblquote  said Ron, \ldblquote about how the wiz\-ards are always trying to get one over on them. I suppose we should think ourselves lucky he hasn\rquote t asked for one of our wands.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Goblins have got good reason to dislike wizards, Ron,\rdblquote  said Her\-mione. \ldblquote They\rquote ve been treated brutally in the past.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Goblins aren\rquote t exactly fluffy little bunnies, though, are they?\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote They\rquote ve killed plenty of us. They\rquote ve fought dirty too.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But arguing with Griphook about whose race is most under\-handed and violent isn\rquote t going to make him more likely to help us, is it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a pause while they tried to think of a way around the problem. Harry looked out of the window at Dobby\rquote s grave. Luna was arranging sea lavender in a jam jar beside the headstone.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Okay,\rdblquote  said Ron, and Harry turned back to face him, \ldblquote how\rquote s\lang3081  \lang1033 this? We tell Griphook we need the sword until we get inside the vault, and then he can have it. There\rquote s a fake in there, isn\rquote t there? We switch them, and give him the fake.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ron, he\rquote d know the difference better than we would!\rdblquote  said Her\-mione. \ldblquote He\rquote s the only one who realized there had been a swap!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, but we could scarper before he realizes \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He quailed beneath the look Hermione was giving him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That,\rdblquote  she said quietly, \ldblquote is despicable. Ask for his help, then double-cross him? And you wonder why goblins don\rquote t like wizards, Ron?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron\rquote s ears had turned red.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All right, all right! It was the only thing I could think of! What\rquote s your solution, then?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We need to offer him something else, something just as valuable.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Brilliant. I\rquote ll go and get one of our other ancient goblin-made swords and you can gift wrap it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Silence fell between them again. Harry was sure that the goblin would accept nothing but the sword, even if they had something as valuable to offer him. Yet the sword was their one, indispensable weapon against the Horcruxes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He closed his eyes for a moment or two and listened to the rush of the sea. The idea that Gryffindor might have stolen the sword was unpleasant to him: He had always been proud to be a Gryffindor; Gryffindor had been the champion of Muggle-borns, the wizard who had clashed with the pureblood-loving Slytherin. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Maybe he\rquote s lying,\rdblquote  Harry said, opening his eyes again. \ldblquote Griphook. Maybe Gryffindor didn\rquote t take the sword. How do we know the goblin version of history\rquote s right?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Does it make a difference?\rdblquote  asked Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Changes how I feel about it,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He took a deep breath.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ll tell him he can have the sword after he\rquote s helped us get into that vault \emdash  but we\rquote ll be careful to avoid telling him exactly \i when\i0  he can have it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A grin spread slowly across Ron\rquote s face. Hermione, however, looked alarmed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, we can\rquote t \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He can have it,\rdblquote  Harry went on, \ldblquote after we\rquote ve used it on all of the Horcruxes. I\rquote ll make sure he gets it then. I\rquote ll keep my word.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But that could be years!\rdblquote  said Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I know that, but \i he\i0  needn\rquote t. I won\rquote t be lying \'85 really.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry met her eyes with a mixture of defiance and shame. He remembered the words that had been engraved over the gateway to Nurmengard: FOR THE GREATER GOOD. He pushed the idea away. What choice did they have?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t like it,\rdblquote  said Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nor do I, much,\rdblquote  Harry admitted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I think it\rquote s genius,\rdblquote  said Ron, standing up again. \ldblquote Let\rquote s go and tell him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Back in the smallest bedroom, Harry made the offer, careful to phrase it so as not to give any definite time for the handover of the sword. Hermione frowned at the floor while he was speaking; he felt irritated at her, afraid that she might give the game away. However, Griphook had eyes for nobody but Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I have your word, Harry Potter, that you will give me the sword of Gryffindor if I help you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Then shake,\rdblquote  said the goblin, holding out his hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry took it and shook. He wondered whether those black eyes saw any misgivings in his own. Then Griphook relinquished him, clapped his hands together, and said, \ldblquote So. We begin!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was like planning to break into the Ministry all over again. They settled to work in the smallest bedroom, which was kept, ac\-cording to Griphook\rquote s preference, in semidarkness.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I have visited the Lestranges\rquote  vault only once,\rdblquote  Griphook told them, \ldblquote on the occasion I was told to place inside it the false sword. It is one of the most ancient chambers. The oldest Wizarding families store their treasures at the deepest level, where the vaults are largest and best protected. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They remained shut in the cupboardlike room for hours at a time. Slowly the days stretched into weeks. There was problem after prob\-lem to overcome, not least of which was that their store of Polyjuice Potion was greatly depleted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There\rquote s really only enough left for one of us,\rdblquote  said Hermione, tilting the thick mudlike potion against the lamplight.\lang3081\par
