\lang1033 She backed out and he closed the door again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Then I have to say this,\rdblquote  Bill went on. \ldblquote If you have struck any kind of bargain with Griphook, and most particularly if that bar\-gain involves treasure, you must be exceptionally careful. Goblin notions of ownership, payment, and repayment are not the same as human ones.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt a slight squirm of discomfort, as though a small snake had stirred inside him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What do you mean?\rdblquote  he asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We are talking about a different breed of being,\rdblquote  said Bill.\lang3081  \lang1033\ldblquote Dealings between wizards and goblins have been fraught for cen\-turies \emdash  but you\rquote ll know all that from History of Magic. There has been fault on both sides, I would never claim that wizards have been innocent. However, there is a belief among some goblins, and those at Gringotts are perhaps most prone to it, that wizards cannot be trusted in matters of gold and treasure, that they have no respect for goblin ownership.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I respect \emdash\rdblquote  Harry began, but Bill shook his head.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You don\rquote t understand, Harry, nobody could understand unless they have lived with goblins. To a goblin, the rightful and true mas\-ter of any object is the maker, not the purchaser. All goblin-made objects are, in goblin eyes, rightfully theirs.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But if it was bought \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  then they would consider it rented by the one who had paid the money. They have, however, great difficulty with the idea of goblin-made objects passing from wizard to wizard. You saw Griphook\rquote s face when the tiara passed under his eyes. He disap\-proves. I believe he thinks, as do the fiercest of his kind, that it ought to have been returned to the goblins once the original pur\-chaser died. They consider our habit of keeping goblin-made objects, passing them from wizard to wizard without further payment, little more than theft.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had an ominous feeling now; he wondered whether Bill guessed more than he was letting on.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All I am saying,\rdblquote  said Bill, setting his hand on the door back into the sitting room, \ldblquote is to be very careful what you promise goblins, Harry. It would be less dangerous to break into Gringotts than to renege on a promise to a goblin.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right,\rdblquote  said Harry as Bill opened the door, \ldblquote yeah. Thanks. I\rquote ll bear that in mind.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
