\lang1033 Mr. Ollivander had sent Luna a new wand that morning. She was out on the back lawn at that moment, testing its capabilities in the late afternoon sun. Dean, who had lost his wand to the Snatchers, was watching rather gloomily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked down at the hawthorn wand that had once be\-longed to Draco Malfoy. He had been surprised, but pleased, to discover that it worked for him at least as well as Hermione\rquote s had done. Remembering what Ollivander had told them of the secret workings of wands, Harry thought he knew what Hermione\rquote s prob\-lem was: She had not won the walnut wand\rquote s allegiance by taking it personally from Bellatrix.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The door of the bedroom opened and Griphook entered. Harry reached instinctively for the hilt of the sword and drew it close to him, but regretted his action at once: He could tell that the gob\-lin had noticed. Seeking to gloss over the sticky moment, he said, \ldblquote We\rquote ve just been checking the last-minute stuff, Griphook. We\rquote ve told Bill and Fleur we\rquote re leaving tomorrow, and we\rquote ve told them not to get up to see us off.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They had been firm on this point, because Hermione would need\lang3081  \lang1033 to transform into Bellatrix before they left, and the less that Bill and Fleur knew or suspected about what they were about to do, the better. They had also explained that they would not be returning. As they had lost Perkins\rquote s old tent on the night that the Snatchers caught them, Bill had lent them another one. It was now packed inside the beaded bag, which, Harry was impressed to learn, Her\-mione had protected from the Snatchers by the simple expedient of stuffing it down her sock.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Though he would miss Bill, Fleur, Luna, and Dean, not to men\-tion the home comforts they had enjoyed over the last few weeks, Harry was looking forward to escaping the confinement of Shell Cottage. He was tired of trying to make sure that they were not overheard, tired of being shut in the tiny, dark bedroom. Most of all, he longed to be rid of Griphook. However, precisely how and when they were to part from the goblin without handing over Gryffindor\rquote s sword remained a question to which Harry had no answer. It had been impossible to decide how they were going to do it, because the goblin rarely left Harry, Ron, and Hermione alone together for more than five minutes at a time: \ldblquote He could give my mother lessons,\rdblquote  growled Ron, as the goblin\rquote s long fingers kept appearing around the edges of doors. With Bill\rquote s warning in mind, Harry could not help suspecting that Griphook was on the watch for possible skulduggery. Hermione disapproved so heartily of the planned double-cross that Harry had given up attempting to pick her brains on how best to do it; Ron, on the rare occasions that they had been able to snatch a few Griphook-free moments, had come up with nothing better than \ldblquote We\rquote ll just have to wing it, mate.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry slept badly that night. Lying awake in the early hours, he thought back to the way he had felt the night before they had\lang3081  \lang1033 infiltrated the Ministry of Magic and remembered a determination, almost an excitement. Now he was experiencing jolts of anxiety, nagging doubts: He could not shake off the fear that it was all going to go wrong. He kept telling himself that their plan was good, that Griphook knew what they were facing, that they were well-prepared for all the difficulties they were likely to encounter, yet still he felt uneasy. Once or twice he heard Ron stir and was sure that he too was awake, but they were sharing the sitting room with Dean, so Harry did not speak.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was a relief when six o\rquote clock arrived and they could slip out of their sleeping bags, dress in the semidarkness, then creep out into the garden, where they were to meet Hermione and Griphook. The dawn was chilly, but there was little wind now that it was May. Harry looked up at the stars still glimmering palely in the dark sky and listened to the sea washing backward and forward against the cliff: He was going to miss the sound.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Small green shoots were forcing their way up through the red earth of Dobby\rquote s grave now; in a year\rquote s time the mound would be covered in flowers. The white stone that bore the elf\rquote s name had al\-ready acquired a weathered look. He realized now that they could hardly have laid Dobby to rest in a more beautiful place, but Harry ached with sadness to think of leaving him behind. Looking down on the grave, he wondered yet again how the elf had known where to come to rescue them. His fingers moved absentmindedly to the little pouch still strung around his neck, through which he could feel the jagged mirror fragment in which he had been sure he had seen Dumbledore\rquote s eye. Then the sound of a door opening made him look around.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Bellatrix Lestrange was striding across the lawn toward them,\lang3081  \lang1033 accompanied by Griphook. As she walked, she was tucking the small, beaded bag into the inside pocket of another set of the old robes they had taken from Grimmauld Place. Though Harry knew perfectly well that it was really Hermione, he could not suppress a shiver of loathing. She was taller than he was, her long black hair rippling down her back, her heavily lidded eyes disdainful as they rested upon him; but then she spoke, and he heard Hermione through Bellatrix\rquote s low voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She tasted \i disgusting,\i0  worse than Gurdyroots! Okay, Ron, come here so I can do you. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right, but remember, I don\rquote t like the beard too long \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, for heaven\rquote s sake, this isn\rquote t about looking handsome \emdash\rdblquote  \ldblquote It\rquote s not that, it gets in the way! But I liked my nose a bit shorter, try and do it the way you did last time.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione sighed and set to work, muttering under her breath as she transformed various aspects of Ron\rquote s appearance. He was to be given a completely fake identity, and they were trusting to the malevolent aura cast by Bellatrix to protect him. Meanwhile Harry and Griphook were to be concealed under the Invisibility Cloak.\lang3081\par
