\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yes, I see,\rdblquote  said Travers, looking down at Bellatrix\rquote s wand, \ldblquote yes, very handsome. And is it working well? I always think wands require a little breaking in, don\rquote t you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione looked utterly bewildered, but to Harry\rquote s enormous relief she accepted the bizarre turn of events without comment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The old goblin behind the counter clapped his hands and a younger goblin approached.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I shall need the Clankers,\rdblquote  he told the goblin, who dashed away and returned a moment later with a leather bag that seemed to be full of jangling metal, which he handed to his senior. \ldblquote Good, good! So, if you will follow me, Madam Lestrange,\rdblquote  said the old goblin,\lang3081  \lang1033 hopping down off his stool and vanishing from sight, \ldblquote I shall take you to your vault.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He appeared around the end of the counter, jogging happily to\-ward them, the contents of the leather bag still jingling. Travers was now standing quite still with his mouth hanging wide open. Ron was drawing attention to this odd phenomenon by regarding Travers with confusion.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wait \emdash\lang3081  \lang1033 Bogrod!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Another goblin came scurrying around the counter.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We have instructions,\rdblquote  he said with a bow to Hermione. \ldblquote For\-give me, Madam, but there have been special orders regarding the vault of Lestrange.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He whispered urgently in Bogrod\rquote s ear, but the Imperiused goblin shook him off.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am aware of the instructions. Madam Lestrange wishes to visit her vault. \'85 Very old family\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 old clients \'85 This way, please \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And, still clanking, he hurried toward one of the many doors leading off the hall. Harry looked back at Travers, who was still rooted to the spot looking abnormally vacant, and made his deci\-sion: With a flick of his wand he made Travers come with them, walking meekly in their wake as they reached the door and passed into the rough stone passageway beyond, which was lit with flam\-ing torches.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote re in trouble; they suspect,\rdblquote  said Harry as the door slammed behind them and he pulled off the Invisibility Cloak. Griphook jumped down from his shoulders; neither Travers nor Bogrod showed the slightest surprise at the sudden appearance of Harry Potter in their midst. \ldblquote They\rquote re Imperiused,\rdblquote  he added, in response\lang3081  \lang1033 to Hermione and Ron\rquote s confused queries about Travers and Bogrod, who were both now standing there looking blank. \ldblquote I don\rquote t think I did it strongly enough, I don\rquote t know. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And another memory darted through his mind, of the real Bel\-latrix Lestrange shrieking at him when he had first tried to use an Unforgivable Curse: \ldblquote You need to \i mean\i0  them, Potter!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What do we do?\rdblquote  asked Ron. \ldblquote Shall we get out now, while we can?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If we can,\rdblquote  said Hermione, looking back toward the door into the main hall, beyond which who knew what was happening.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ve got this far, I say we go on,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good!\rdblquote  said Griphook. \ldblquote So, we need Bogrod to control the cart; I no longer have the authority. But there will not be room for the wizard.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry pointed his wand at Travers.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Imperio\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The wizard turned and set off along the dark track at a smart pace.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What are you making him do?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hide,\rdblquote  said Harry as he pointed his wand at Bogrod, who whistled to summon a little cart that came trundling along the tracks toward them out of the darkness. Harry was sure he could hear shouting behind them in the main hall as they all clambered into it, Bogrod in front with Griphook, Harry, Ron, and Hermione crammed together in the back.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 With a jerk the cart moved off, gathering speed: They hurtled past Travers, who was wriggling into a crack in the wall, then the cart began twisting and turning through the labyrinthine passages, sloping downward all the time. Harry could not hear anything over\lang3081  \lang1033 the rattling of the cart on the tracks: His hair flew behind him as they swerved between stalactites, flying ever deeper into the earth, but he kept glancing back. They might as well have left enormous footprints behind them; the more he thought about it, the more foolish it seemed to have disguised Hermione as Bellatrix, to have brought along Bellatrix\rquote s wand, when the Death Eaters knew who had stolen it \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were deeper than Harry had ever penetrated within Grin\-gotts; they took a hairpin bend at speed and saw ahead of them, with seconds to spare, a waterfall pounding over the track. Harry heard Griphook shout, \ldblquote No!\rdblquote  but there was no braking: They zoomed through it. Water filled Harry\rquote s eyes and mouth: He could not see or breathe: Then, with an awful lurch, the cart flipped over and they were all thrown out of it. Harry heard the cart smash into pieces against the passage wall, heard Hermione shriek something, and felt himself glide back toward the ground as though weightless, landing painlessly on the rocky passage floor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote C-Cushioning Charm,\rdblquote  Hermione spluttered, as Ron pulled her to her feet, but to Harry\rquote s horror he saw that she was no longer Bella\-trix; instead she stood there in overlarge robes, sopping wet and com\-pletely herself; Ron was red-haired and beardless again. They were realizing it as they looked at each other, feeling their own faces.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Thief\rquote s Downfall!\rdblquote  said Griphook, clambering to his feet and looking back at the deluge onto the tracks, which, Harry knew now, had been more than water. \ldblquote It washes away all enchantment, all magical concealment! They know there are impostors in Grin\-gotts, they have set off defenses against us!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry saw Hermione checking that she still had the beaded bag, and hurriedly thrust his own hand under his jacket to make sure he\lang3081  \lang1033 had not lost the Invisibility Cloak. Then he turned to see Bogrod shaking his head in bewilderment: The Thief\rquote s Downfall seemed to have lifted the Imperius Curse.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We need him,\rdblquote  said Griphook, \ldblquote we cannot enter the vault with\-out a Gringotts goblin. And we need the Clankers!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Imperio\i0 !\rdblquote  Harry said again; his voice echoed through the stone passage as he felt again the sense of heady control that flowed from brain to wand. Bogrod submitted once more to his will, his be\-fuddled expression changing to one of polite indifference, as Ron hurried to pick up the leather bag of metal tools.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, I think I can hear people coming!\rdblquote  said Hermione, and she pointed Bellatrix\rquote s wand at the waterfall and cried, \ldblquote\i Protego\i0 !\rdblquote  They saw the Shield Charm break the flow of enchanted water as it flew up the passageway.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good thinking,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Lead the way, Griphook!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How are we going to get out again?\rdblquote  Ron asked as they hurried on foot into the darkness after the goblin, Bogrod panting in their wake like an old dog.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let\rquote s worry about that when we have to,\rdblquote  said Harry. He was trying to listen: He thought he could hear something clanking and moving around nearby. \ldblquote Griphook, how much farther?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not far, Harry Potter, not far \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And they turned a corner and saw the thing for which Harry had been prepared, but which still brought all of them to a halt.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A gigantic dragon was tethered to the ground in front of them, barring access to four or five of the deepest vaults in the place. The beast\rquote s scales had turned pale and flaky during its long incarcera\-tion under the ground; its eyes were milkily pink; both rear legs bore heavy cuffs from which chains led to enormous pegs driven\lang3081  \lang1033 deep into the rocky floor. Its great spiked wings, folded close to its body, would have filled the chamber if it spread them, and when it turned its ugly head toward them, it roared with a noise that made the rock tremble, opened its mouth, and spat a jet of fire that sent them running back up the passageway.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It is partially blind,\rdblquote  panted Griphook, \ldblquote but even more savage for that. However, we have the means to control it. It has learned what to expect when the Clankers come. Give them to me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron passed the bag to Griphook, and the goblin pulled out a number of small metal instruments that when shaken made a loud, ringing noise like miniature hammers on anvils. Griphook handed them out: Bogrod accepted his meekly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You know what to do,\rdblquote  Griphook told Harry, Ron, and Hermi\-one. \ldblquote It will expect pain when it hears the noise: It will retreat, and Bogrod must place his palm upon the door of the vault.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
