\lang1033 The shelf on which the cup reposed was out of reach for any of them, even Ron, who was tallest. The heat from the enchanted treasure rose in waves, and sweat ran down Harry\rquote s face and back as he struggled to think of a way up to the cup; and then he heard the dragon roar on the other side of the vault door, and the sound of clanking growing louder and louder.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were truly trapped now: There was no way out except through the door, and a horde of goblins seemed to be approach\-ing on the other side. Harry looked at Ron and Hermione and saw terror in their faces.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hermione,\rdblquote  said Harry as the clanking grew louder, \ldblquote I\rquote ve got to get up there, we\rquote ve got to get rid of it \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She raised her wand, pointed it at Harry, and whispered, \ldblquote\i Levi\-corpus.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hoisted into the air by his ankle, Harry hit a suit of armor and replicas burst out of it like white-hot bodies, filling the cramped space. With screams of pain Ron, Hermione, and the two goblins were knocked aside into other objects, which also began to replicate. Half buried in a rising tide of red-hot treasure, they struggled and yelled as Harry thrust the sword through the handle of Hufflepuff\rquote s cup, hooking it onto the blade.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Impervius\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081  \lang1033 screeched Hermione in an attempt to protect herself, Ron, and the goblins from the burning metal.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Then the worst scream yet made Harry look down: Ron and Her\-mione were waist-deep in treasure, struggling to keep Bogrod from slipping beneath the rising tide, but Griphook had sunk out of sight and nothing but the tips of a few long fingers were left in view.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry seized Griphook\rquote s fingers and pulled. The blistered goblin emerged by degrees, howling.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Liberacorpus\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081  \lang1033 yelled Harry, and with a crash he and Griphook landed on the surface of the swelling treasure, and the sword flew out of Harry\rquote s hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Get it!\rdblquote  Harry yelled, fighting the pain of the hot metal on his skin, as Griphook clambered onto his shoulders again, determined to avoid the swelling mass of red-hot objects. \ldblquote Where\rquote s the sword? It had the cup on it!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The clanking on the other side of the door was growing deafen\-ing \emdash  it was too late \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was Griphook who had seen it and Griphook who lunged, and in that instant Harry knew that the goblin had never expected them to keep their word. One hand holding tightly to a fistful of Harry\rquote s hair, to make sure he did not fall into the heaving sea of burning gold, Griphook seized the hilt of the sword and swung it high out of Harry\rquote s reach.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The tiny golden cup, skewered by the handle on the sword\rquote s blade, was flung into the air. The goblin still astride him, Harry dived and caught it, and although he could feel it scalding his flesh he did not relinquish it, even while countless Hufflepuff cups burst from his fist, raining down upon him as the entrance of the vault opened up again and he found himself sliding uncontrollably on an expanding\lang3081  \lang1033 avalanche of fiery gold and silver that bore him, Ron, and Hermione into the outer chamber.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hardly aware of the pain from the burns covering his body, and still borne along on the swell of replicating treasure, Harry shoved the cup into his pocket and reached up to retrieve the sword, but Griphook was gone. Sliding from Harry\rquote s shoulders the moment he could, he had sprinted for cover amongst the surrounding goblins, brandishing the sword and crying, \ldblquote Thieves! Thieves! Help! Thieves!\rdblquote  He vanished into the midst of the advancing crowd, all of whom were holding daggers and who accepted him without question.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Slipping on the hot metal, Harry struggled to his feet and knew that the only way out was through.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Stupefy\i0 !\rdblquote  he bellowed, and Ron and Hermione joined in: Jets of red light flew into the crowd of goblins, and some toppled over, but others advanced, and Harry saw several wizard guards running around the corner.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The tethered dragon let out a roar, and a gush of flame flew over the goblins: The wizards fled, doubled-up, back the way they had come, and inspiration, or madness, came to Harry. Pointing his wand at the thick cuffs chaining the beast to the floor, he yelled, \ldblquote\i Relashio\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The cuffs broke open with loud bangs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This way!\rdblquote  Harry yelled, and still shooting Stunning Spells at the advancing goblins, he sprinted toward the blind dragon.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry \emdash  Harry \emdash  what are you doing?\rdblquote  cried Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Get up, climb up, come on \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The dragon had not realized that it was free: Harry\rquote s foot found the crook of its hind leg and he pulled himself up onto its back.\lang3081  \lang1033 The scales were hard as steel; it did not even seem to feel him. He stretched out an arm; Hermione hoisted herself up; Ron climbed on behind them, and a second later the dragon became aware that it was untethered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 With a roar it reared: Harry dug in his knees, clutching as tightly as he could to the jagged scales as the wings opened, knocking the shrieking goblins aside like skittles, and it soared into the air. Harry, Ron, and Hermione, flat on its back, scraped against the ceiling as it dived toward the passage opening, while the pursuing goblins hurled daggers that glanced off its flanks.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ll never get out, it\rquote s too big!\rdblquote  Hermione screamed, but the dragon opened its mouth and belched flame again, blasting the tunnel, whose floors and ceiling cracked and crumbled. By sheer force the dragon clawed and fought its way through. Harry\rquote s eyes were shut tight against the heat and dust: Deafened by the crash\-ing of rock and the dragon\rquote s roars, he could only cling to its back, expecting to be shaken off at any moment; then he heard Hermione yelling, \ldblquote\i Defodio\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She was helping the dragon enlarge the passageway, carving out the ceiling as it struggled upward toward the fresher air, away from the shrieking and clanking goblins: Harry and Ron copied her, blasting the ceiling apart with more gouging spells. They passed the underground lake, and the great crawling, snarling beast seemed to sense freedom and space ahead of it, and behind them the passage was full of the dragon\rquote s thrashing, spiked tail, of great lumps of rock, gigantic fractured stalactites, and the clanking of the goblins seemed to be growing more muffled, while ahead, the dragon\rquote s fire kept their progress clear \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And then at last, by the combined force of their spells and the dragon\rquote s brute strength, they had blasted their way out of the passage into the marble hallway. Goblins and wizards shrieked and ran for cover, and finally the dragon had room to stretch its wings: Turning its horned head toward the cool outside air it could smell beyond the entrance, it took off, and with Harry, Ron, and Hermione still clinging to its back, it forced its way through the metal doors, leav\-ing them buckled and hanging from their hinges, as it staggered into Diagon Alley and launched itself into the sky.\lang3081\par
